00:00:19.200 --> 00:00:26.940
Alice's Adventures in Wonderland by Lewis Carroll, Chapter 1, Down the Rabbit Hole.

00:00:26.940 --> 00:00:35.920
Alice was beginning to get very tired of sitting by her sister on the bank, and of having nothing to do.

00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:46.000
Once or twice, she had peeped into the book her sister was reading, but it had no pictures or conversations in it.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:53.560
"And what is the use of a book?" thought Alice, without pictures or conversations.

00:00:53.560 --> 00:01:03.560
So she was considering in her own mind, as well as she could, for the hot day made her feel very sleepy and stupid.

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:12.560
Whether the pleasure of making a daisy chain would be worth the trouble of getting up and picking the daisies.

00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:19.560
When suddenly, a white rabbit with pink eyes ran close by her.

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:32.560
There was nothing so very remarkable in that. Nor did Alice think it so very much out of the way to hear the rabbit say to itself.

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:36.560
"Oh dear! Oh dear! I shall be late!"

00:01:36.560 --> 00:01:48.060
When she thought it over afterwards, it occurred to her that she ought to have wondered at this, but at the time it all seemed quite natural.

00:01:48.060 --> 00:02:02.060
But when the rabbit actually took a watch out of its waistcoat pocket and looked at it, and then hurried on, Alice started to her feet.

00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:18.060
For it flashed across her mind that she had never before seen a rabbit with either a waistcoat pocket, or a watch to take out of it, and burning with curiosity.

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:39.060
She ran across the field after it, and fortunately, was just in time to see it pop down a large rabbit hole under the hedge. In another moment, down, went Alice after it, never once considering how in the world she was to get out again.

00:02:39.060 --> 00:02:58.060
The rabbit hole went straight on like a tunnel for some way, and then dipped suddenly down. So suddenly, that Alice had not a moment to think about stopping herself before she found herself falling down a very deep well.

00:02:58.060 --> 00:03:15.060
Either the well was very deep, or she fell very slowly, for she had plenty of time as she went down to look about her, and to wonder what was going to happen next.

00:03:15.060 --> 00:03:32.060
First, she tried to look down, and make out what she was coming to, but it was too dark to see anything. Then, she looked at the sides of the well, and noticed that they were filled with cupboards and bookshelves.

00:03:32.060 --> 00:03:55.060
Here and there, she saw maps and pictures hung upon pegs. She took down a jar from one of the shelves as she passed. It was labeled orange marmalade, but to her great disappointment, it was empty. She did not like to drop the jar, for fear of killing somebody underneath.

00:03:55.060 --> 00:04:04.060
So managed to put it into one of the cupboards as she fell past it. Well, thought Alice to herself.

00:04:04.060 --> 00:04:21.060
After such a fall as this, I shall think nothing of tumbling downstairs. How brave they'll all think me at home. Why, I wouldn't say anything about it, even if I fell off the top of the house.

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:30.060
Which was very likely true. Down, down, down. Would the fall never come to an end?

00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:38.060
I wonder how many miles I've fallen by this time. She said aloud.

00:04:38.060 --> 00:04:51.060
I must be getting somewhere near the center of the earth. Let me see. That would be 4,000 miles down, I think.

00:04:51.060 --> 00:05:12.060
4, you see. Alice had learned several things of this sort in her lessons in the school room. And though this was not a very good opportunity for showing off her knowledge, as there was no one to listen to her. Still, it was good practice to say it over.

00:05:12.060 --> 00:05:22.060
Yes, that's about the right distance. But then I wonder, what latitude or longitude I've got to.

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:34.060
Alice had no idea what latitude was. Or longitude either. But thought they were nice, grand words to say.

00:05:34.060 --> 00:05:49.060
Presently, she began again. I wonder if I shall fall right through the earth. How funny it'll seem to come out among the people that walk with their heads downward.

00:05:49.060 --> 00:06:12.060
The Antipatties, I think. She was rather glad there was no one listening, this time, as it didn't sound at all the right word. But I shall have to ask them what the name of the country is. You know, please ma'am, is this New Zealand or Australia?

00:06:12.060 --> 00:06:22.060
And she tried to curtsy as she spoke. Fancy curtsying as you're falling through the air. Do you think you could manage it?

00:06:22.060 --> 00:06:33.060
And what an ignorant little girl shall think me for asking. No, it'll never do to ask. Perhaps I shall see it written up somewhere.

00:06:33.060 --> 00:06:42.060
Down, down, down. There was nothing else to do. So Alice began talking again.

00:06:42.060 --> 00:06:49.060
Dina'll miss me very much tonight, I should think. Dina was the cat.

00:06:49.060 --> 00:07:02.060
I hope they'll remember her saucer of milk at tea time. Dina, my dear. I wish you were down here with me. There are no mice in the air. I'm afraid.

00:07:02.060 --> 00:07:12.060
But you might catch a bat. And that's very like a mouse, you know. But do cats eat bats? I wonder?

00:07:12.060 --> 00:07:26.060
And here Alice began to get rather sleepy and went on saying to herself in a dreamy sort of way. Do cats eat bats? Do cats eat bats?

00:07:26.060 --> 00:07:41.060
And sometimes, do bats eat cats? Or you see, as she couldn't answer either question, it didn't much matter which way she put it.

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:57.060
She felt that she was dozing off. And it just begun to dream that she was walking hand in hand with Dina and saying to her very earnestly, "Now, Dina, tell me the truth. Did you ever eat a bat?"

00:07:57.060 --> 00:08:15.060
When suddenly, thump, thump, down she came upon a heap of sticks and dry leaves, and the fall was over. Alice was not a bit hurt, and she jumped up onto her feet in a moment. She looked up, but it was all dark overhead.

00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:32.060
Before her was another long passage, and the white rabbit was still in sight, hurrying down it. There was not a moment to be lost. A way went Alice like the wind, and it was just in time to hear it say, as it turned to corner.

00:08:32.060 --> 00:08:44.060
"Oh my ears and whiskers! How late it's getting!" She was close behind it when she turned the corner, but the rabbit was no longer to be seen.

00:08:44.060 --> 00:09:03.060
She found herself in a long, low hall, which was lit up by a row of lamps hanging from the roof. There were doors all round the hall, but they were all locked, and when Alice had been all the way down one side and up the other, trying every door.

00:09:03.060 --> 00:09:16.060
She walked sadly down the middle, wondering how she was ever to get out again. Suddenly, she came upon a little three-legged table, all made of solid glass.

00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:40.060
There was nothing on it except a tiny golden key, and Alice's first thought was that it might belong to one of the doors of the hall. But, Alice, either the locks were too large, or the key was too small, but at any rate it would not open any of them.

00:09:40.060 --> 00:10:01.060
However, on the second time round, she came upon a low curtain she had not noticed before, and behind it was a little door about 15 inches high. She tried the little golden key in the lock, and to her great delight it fitted.

00:10:01.060 --> 00:10:17.060
Alice opened the door, and found that it led into a small passage, not much larger than a rattle. She knelt down, and looked along the passage, into the loveliest garden you ever saw.

00:10:17.060 --> 00:10:37.060
How she longed to get out of that dark hall, and wander about among those beds of bright flowers, and those cool fountains. But she could not even get her head through the doorway, and even if my head would go through, thought poor Alice.

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:51.060
It would be of very little use without my shoulders. Oh, how I wish I could shut up like a telescope. I think I could, if I only knew how to begin.

00:10:51.060 --> 00:11:12.060
For you see, so many out of the way things had happened lately, that Alice had begun to think that very few things indeed were really impossible. There seemed to be no use in waiting by the little door, so she went back to the table, half hoping she might find another key on it.

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:21.060
Or at any rate, a book of rules for shutting people up like telescopes. This time, she found a little bottle on it.

00:11:21.060 --> 00:11:35.060
"Which, certainly, was not here before?" said Alice, and round the neck of the bottle was a paper label, with the words "drink me," beautifully printed on it in large letters.

00:11:35.060 --> 00:11:45.060
"It was all very well to say, "drink me," but the wise little Alice was not going to do that in a hurry.

00:11:45.060 --> 00:12:04.060
"No, I'll look first," she said, and see whether it's marked poison or not. For she had read several nice little histories about children who had got burnt, and eaten up by wild beasts,

00:12:04.060 --> 00:12:31.060
and other unpleasant things. All because they would not remember the simple rules their friends had taught them, such as that a red-hot poker will burn you if you hold it too long, and that if you cut your finger very deeply with a knife, it usually bleeds.

00:12:31.060 --> 00:12:43.060
And she had never forgotten that. If you drink from a bottle marked poison, it is almost certain to disagree with you sooner or later.

00:12:43.060 --> 00:13:03.060
However, this bottle was not marked poison, so Alice ventured to taste it, and finding it very nice. It had, in fact, a sort of mixed flavor of cherry tart, custard, pineapple, roast turkey,

00:13:03.060 --> 00:13:17.060
coffee, and hot-buttered toast. She very soon finished it off. "What a curious feeling," said Alice. "I must be shutting up like a telescope."

00:13:17.060 --> 00:13:36.060
And so it was, indeed. She was now only ten inches high, and her face brightened up, at the thought that she was now the right size for going through the little door into that lovely garden.

00:13:36.060 --> 00:13:47.060
First, however, she waited for a few minutes to see if she was going to shrink any further. She felt a little nervous about this.

00:13:47.060 --> 00:14:00.060
"For it might end, you know," said Alice to herself. "In my going out altogether, like a candle. I wonder what I should be like then."

00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:18.060
And she tried to fancy what the flame of a candle is like. After the candle is blown out, for she could not remember ever having seen such a thing. After a while, finding that nothing more happened.

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:39.060
She decided on going into the garden at once. But, Alice, for poor Alice, when she got to the door, she found she had forgotten the little golden key. And, when she went back to the table for it, she found she could not possibly reach it.

00:14:39.060 --> 00:14:58.060
She could see it quite plainly through the glass, and she tried her best to climb up one of the legs of the table. But it was too slippery. And when she had tired herself out with trying, the poor little thing sat down and cried.

00:14:58.060 --> 00:15:10.060
"Bum, there's no use in crying like that," said Alice to herself, rather sharply. "I advise you to leave off this minute."

00:15:10.060 --> 00:15:25.060
She generally gave herself very good advice. Though she very seldom followed it. And sometimes, she scolded herself so severely as to bring tears into her eyes.

00:15:25.060 --> 00:15:43.060
And once, she remembered trying to box her own ears for having cheated herself. In a game of croquet, she was playing against herself. For this curious child was very fond of pretending to be two people.

00:15:43.060 --> 00:15:56.060
"But it's no use now," thought poor Alice. "To pretend to be two people?" Why, there's hardly enough of me left to make one respectable person.

00:15:56.060 --> 00:16:12.060
"Soon, her eye fell on a little glass box that was lying under the table." She opened it, and found in it a very small cake. On which the words "eat me" were beautifully marked in currents.

00:16:12.060 --> 00:16:26.060
"Well, I'll eat it," said Alice. "And if it makes me grow larger, I can reach the key. And if it makes me grow smaller, I can creep under the door."

00:16:26.060 --> 00:16:45.060
"So either way, I'll get into the garden, and I don't care which happens." She ate a little bit, and said anxiously to herself. "Which way? Which way?" holding her hand on the top of her head to feel which way it was growing.

00:16:45.060 --> 00:17:06.060
"And she was quite surprised to find that she remained the same size." To be sure, this generally happens when one eats cake. But Alice had got so much into the way of expecting nothing but out of the way things to happen.

00:17:06.060 --> 00:17:19.060
"That it seemed quite dull and stupid for life to go on in the common way. So she sat to work, and very soon, finished off the cake."

00:17:19.060 --> 00:17:41.060
"And of Chapter 1."

00:17:41.060 --> 00:17:51.060
"Curiouser and curiouser," cried Alice. "She was so much surprised, that for the moment, she quite forgot how to speak good English."

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:58.060
"Now I'm opening out like the largest telescope that ever was. Goodbye, feet!"

00:17:58.060 --> 00:18:04.060
"For when she looked down at her feet, they seemed to be almost out of sight. They were getting so far off."

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:13.060
"Oh, my poor little feet. I wonder, who will put on your shoes and stockings for you now, dears?"

00:18:13.060 --> 00:18:27.060
"I'm sure I, shan't be able. I shall be a great deal too far off to trouble myself about you. You must manage the best way you can. But I must be kind to them," thought Alice.

00:18:27.060 --> 00:18:36.060
"Or perhaps they won't walk the way I want to go. Let me see. I'll give them a new pair of boots every Christmas."

00:18:36.060 --> 00:18:46.060
"And she went on, planning to herself, how she would manage it. They must go by the carrier," she thought.

00:18:46.060 --> 00:18:54.060
"And how funny it'll seem, sending presents to one's own feet. And how odd the directions will look."

00:18:54.060 --> 00:19:02.060
"Alice's right foot. Esquire. Her throat. Near the fender. With Alice's love."

00:19:02.060 --> 00:19:05.060
"Oh, dear. What nonsense I'm talking."

00:19:05.060 --> 00:19:19.060
"Just then, her head struck against the roof of the hall. In fact, she was now more than nine feet high. And she at once took up the little golden key and hurried off to the garden door."

00:19:19.060 --> 00:19:38.060
"Poor Alice. It was as much as she could do, lying down on one side, to look through into the garden with one eye. But to get through was more hopeless than ever. She sat down and began to cry again. You ought to be ashamed of yourself," said Alice.

00:19:38.060 --> 00:19:51.060
"A great girl like you." She might well say this. "To go on crying in this way. Stop this moment. I tell you." But she went on all the same, shedding gallons of tears.

00:19:51.060 --> 00:20:07.060
"Until there was a large pool all round her, about four inches deep, and reaching half down the hall. After a time, she heard a little patterning of feet in the distance. And she hastily dried her eyes to see what was coming."

00:20:07.060 --> 00:20:28.060
"It was the white rabbit returning, splendidly dressed, with a pair of white kid gloves in one hand, and a large fan in the other. He came trotting along in a great hurry, muttering to himself as he came. Oh, the Duchess, the Duchess, oh, won't she be savage if I've kept her waiting?"

00:20:28.060 --> 00:20:41.060
Alice felt so desperate that she was ready to ask help of anyone. So, when the rabbit came near her, she began, in a low timid voice.

00:20:41.060 --> 00:20:54.060
"If you please, sir," the rabbit started violently, dropped the white kid gloves and the fan, and scurried away into the darkness as hard as he could go.

00:20:54.060 --> 00:21:04.060
Alice took up the fanning gloves, and, as the hall was very hot, she kept fanning herself all the time she went on talking.

00:21:04.060 --> 00:21:09.060
"Dear dear, how queer everything is today."

00:21:09.060 --> 00:21:18.060
"And yesterday things went on just as usual. I wonder if I've been changed in the night. Let me think."

00:21:18.060 --> 00:21:26.060
"Was I the same when I got up this morning?" "I almost think I can remember feeling a little different."

00:21:26.060 --> 00:21:34.060
"But if I'm not the same, the next question is, who in the world am I?"

00:21:34.060 --> 00:21:37.060
"Ah, that's the great puzzle."

00:21:37.060 --> 00:21:48.060
"And she began thinking over all the children she knew that were of the same age as herself. To see if she could have been changed for any of them."

00:21:48.060 --> 00:21:51.060
"I'm sure I'm not Ada," she said.

00:21:51.060 --> 00:21:56.060
"For her hair goes in such long ringlets, and mine doesn't go in ringlets at all."

00:21:56.060 --> 00:22:01.060
"And I'm sure I can't be mabel, for I know all sorts of things."

00:22:01.060 --> 00:22:07.060
"And she, oh, she knows such a very little."

00:22:07.060 --> 00:22:12.060
"Besides, she's she, and I'm I."

00:22:12.060 --> 00:22:17.060
"And, oh dear, how puzzling it all is."

00:22:17.060 --> 00:22:23.060
"I'll try if I know all the things I used to know."

00:22:23.060 --> 00:22:29.060
"Let me see. Four times five is twelve."

00:22:29.060 --> 00:22:33.060
"And four times six is thirteen."

00:22:33.060 --> 00:22:37.060
"And four times seven is."

00:22:37.060 --> 00:22:41.060
"Oh dear, I shall never get to twenty at that rate."

00:22:41.060 --> 00:22:46.060
"However, the multiplication table doesn't signify."

00:22:46.060 --> 00:22:49.060
"Let's try geography."

00:22:49.060 --> 00:22:52.060
"London is the capital of Paris."

00:22:52.060 --> 00:22:55.060
"And Paris is the capital of Rome."

00:22:55.060 --> 00:22:59.060
"And Rome?"

00:22:59.060 --> 00:23:03.060
"No, that's all wrong. I'm certain."

00:23:03.060 --> 00:23:07.060
"I must have been changed for mabel."

00:23:07.060 --> 00:23:11.060
"I'll try and say, how doth little?"

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:16.060
"And she crossed her hands on her lap, as if she were saying lessons."

00:23:16.060 --> 00:23:22.060
"And began to repeat it. But her voice sounded horse and strange."

00:23:22.060 --> 00:23:26.060
"The words did not come the same as they used to do."

00:23:26.060 --> 00:23:32.060
"How doth the little crocodile improve his shining tail?"

00:23:32.060 --> 00:23:37.060
"And pour the waters of the Nile on every golden scale."

00:23:37.060 --> 00:23:42.060
"How cheerfully he seems to grin. How neatly spread his claws."

00:23:42.060 --> 00:23:48.060
"And welcome little fishes in, with gently smiling jaws."

00:23:48.060 --> 00:23:52.060
"I'm sure those are not the right words."

00:23:52.060 --> 00:23:58.060
" Said pour Alice, and her eyes filled with tears again as she went on."

00:23:58.060 --> 00:24:05.060
"I must be mabel after all, and I shall have to go and live in that pokey little house."

00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:09.060
"And have next to no toys to play with."

00:24:09.060 --> 00:24:13.060
"And oh, ever so many lessons to learn."

00:24:13.060 --> 00:24:17.060
"No, I've made up my mind about it.

00:24:17.060 --> 00:24:22.060
If I'm mabel, I'll stay down here. It'll be no use.

00:24:22.060 --> 00:24:27.060
They're putting their heads down and saying, "Come up again, dear."

00:24:27.060 --> 00:24:33.060
"I shall only look up and say, 'Who am I then?' Tell me that first."

00:24:33.060 --> 00:24:43.060
"And then, if I like being that person, I'll come up. If not, I'll stay down here till I'm somebody else."

00:24:43.060 --> 00:24:49.060
"But oh dear!" cried Alice, with a sudden burst of tears.

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:59.060
"I do wish they would put their heads down. I am so very tired of being all alone here."

00:24:59.060 --> 00:25:12.060
As she said this, she looked down at her hands, and was surprised to see that she had put on one of the rabbit's little white kid gloves while she was talking.

00:25:12.060 --> 00:25:20.060
"How can I have done that?" she thought. "I must be growing small again."

00:25:20.060 --> 00:25:28.060
She got up and went to the table to measure herself by it, and found that, as nearly as she could guess.

00:25:28.060 --> 00:25:33.060
She was now about two feet high, and was going on shrinking rapidly.

00:25:33.060 --> 00:25:44.060
She soon found out that the cause of this was the fan she was holding, and she dropped it hastily, just in time to avoid shrinking away altogether.

00:25:44.060 --> 00:25:56.060
"That was a narrow escape," said Alice, a good deal frightened at the sudden change, but very glad to find herself still in existence.

00:25:56.060 --> 00:25:59.060
"And now for the garden!"

00:25:59.060 --> 00:26:04.060
And she ran with all speed, back to the little door.

00:26:04.060 --> 00:26:13.060
But alas, the little door was shut again, and the little golden key was lying on the glass table as before.

00:26:13.060 --> 00:26:18.060
"And things are worse than ever," thought the poor child.

00:26:18.060 --> 00:26:28.060
"For I was never so small as this before, never, and I declare it's too bad, that it is."

00:26:28.060 --> 00:26:37.060
As she said these words, her foot slit, and in another moment, splash, she was up to her chin in saltwater.

00:26:37.060 --> 00:26:42.060
Her first idea was that she had somehow fallen into the sea.

00:26:42.060 --> 00:26:48.060
"And in that case, I can go back by railway," she said to herself.

00:26:48.060 --> 00:26:56.060
Alice had been to the seaside once in her life, and had come to the general conclusion,

00:26:56.060 --> 00:27:04.060
"that wherever you go to on the English coast, you find a number of bathing machines in the sea.

00:27:04.060 --> 00:27:15.060
Some children digging in the sand with wooden spades, then a row of lodging houses, and behind them, a railway station.

00:27:15.060 --> 00:27:24.060
However, she soon made out that she was in the pool of tears, which she had wept when she was nine feet high.

00:27:24.060 --> 00:27:32.060
"I wish I hadn't cried so much," said Alice, as she swam about, trying to find her way out.

00:27:32.060 --> 00:27:39.060
"I shall be punished for it now," I suppose, by being drowned in my own tears.

00:27:39.060 --> 00:27:43.060
"That will be a queer thing to be sure."

00:27:43.060 --> 00:27:47.060
"However, everything is queer today."

00:27:47.060 --> 00:27:56.060
"Just then, she heard something splashing about in the pool a little way off, and she swam nearer to make out what it was."

00:27:56.060 --> 00:28:05.060
At first, she thought it must be a walrus or hip-aponymous, but then she remembered how small she was now,

00:28:05.060 --> 00:28:11.060
and she soon made out that it was only a mouse that had slipped in like herself.

00:28:11.060 --> 00:28:18.060
"Would it be of any use now," thought Alice, to speak to this mouse.

00:28:18.060 --> 00:28:25.060
"Everything is so out of the way down here that I should think very likely it can talk.

00:28:25.060 --> 00:28:28.060
At any rate, there's no harm in trying."

00:28:28.060 --> 00:28:29.060
"So she began."

00:28:29.060 --> 00:28:33.060
"Oh, mouse, do you know the way out of this pool?

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:37.060
I am very tired of sobbing about here, oh, mouse."

00:28:37.060 --> 00:28:42.060
Alice thought this must be the right way of speaking to a mouse.

00:28:42.060 --> 00:28:50.060
She had never done such a thing before, but she remembered having seen in her brother's Latin grammar,

00:28:50.060 --> 00:28:58.060
a mouse, of a mouse, two a mouse, a mouse, o mouse.

00:28:58.060 --> 00:29:05.060
The mouse looked at her rather inquisitively, and seemed to her to wink with one of its little eyes,

00:29:05.060 --> 00:29:07.060
but it said nothing.

00:29:07.060 --> 00:29:11.060
"Perhaps it doesn't understand English," thought Alice.

00:29:11.060 --> 00:29:14.060
"I dare say it's a French mouse.

00:29:14.060 --> 00:29:16.060
Come over with William the Conqueror."

00:29:16.060 --> 00:29:26.060
"For, with all her knowledge of history, Alice had no very clear notion how long ago anything had happened."

00:29:26.060 --> 00:29:28.060
"So she began again."

00:29:28.060 --> 00:29:30.060
"Who a, mashat?"

00:29:30.060 --> 00:29:35.060
"Which was the first sentence in her French lesson book.

00:29:35.060 --> 00:29:40.060
The mouse gave a sudden leap out of the water, and seemed to quiver all over with fright."

00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:48.060
"Oh, I beg your pardon," cried Alice hastily, afraid that she had hurt the poor animals' feelings.

00:29:48.060 --> 00:29:51.060
"I quite forgot you didn't like cats."

00:29:51.060 --> 00:29:57.060
"Not like cats!" cried the mouse in a shrill, passionate voice.

00:29:57.060 --> 00:30:00.060
"Would you like cats if you were me?"

00:30:00.060 --> 00:30:05.060
"Well, perhaps not," said Alice in a soothing tone.

00:30:05.060 --> 00:30:07.060
"Don't be angry about it.

00:30:07.060 --> 00:30:11.060
And yet I wish I could show you our cat, Dina.

00:30:11.060 --> 00:30:15.060
I think you'd take a fancy to cats if you could only see her.

00:30:15.060 --> 00:30:19.060
She is such a dear, quiet thing."

00:30:19.060 --> 00:30:25.060
Alice went on, half to herself, as she swam lazily about in the pool.

00:30:25.060 --> 00:30:32.060
And she sits purring so nicely by the fire, licking her paws and washing her face.

00:30:32.060 --> 00:30:36.060
And she is such a nice, soft thing to nurse.

00:30:36.060 --> 00:30:40.060
And she's such a capital one for catching mice.

00:30:40.060 --> 00:30:47.060
"Oh, I beg your pardon," cried Alice again, for this time the mouse was bristling all over.

00:30:47.060 --> 00:30:51.060
And she felt certain it must be really offended.

00:30:51.060 --> 00:30:56.060
"We won't talk about her anymore if you'd rather not."

00:30:56.060 --> 00:31:02.060
"We indeed," cried the mouse, who was trembling down to the end of his tail.

00:31:02.060 --> 00:31:06.060
"As if I would talk on such a subject."

00:31:06.060 --> 00:31:09.060
Our family always hated cats.

00:31:09.060 --> 00:31:13.060
"Nasty, low, vulgar things.

00:31:13.060 --> 00:31:16.060
Don't let me hear the name again."

00:31:16.060 --> 00:31:19.060
"I won't indeed," said Alice,

00:31:19.060 --> 00:31:23.060
the great hurry to change the subject of conversation.

00:31:23.060 --> 00:31:25.060
"Are you?

00:31:25.060 --> 00:31:29.060
Are you fond of, of dogs?"

00:31:29.060 --> 00:31:33.060
The mouse did not answer, so Alice went on eagerly.

00:31:33.060 --> 00:31:36.060
"There is such a nice little dog near our house.

00:31:36.060 --> 00:31:40.060
I should like to show you a little bright eye to terrier.

00:31:40.060 --> 00:31:46.060
You know, with, oh, such a long curly brown hair.

00:31:46.060 --> 00:31:49.060
And it'll fetch things when you throw them.

00:31:49.060 --> 00:31:52.060
And it'll sit up and beg for its dinner.

00:31:52.060 --> 00:31:54.060
And all sorts of things.

00:31:54.060 --> 00:31:56.060
I can't remember half of them.

00:31:56.060 --> 00:31:59.060
And it belongs to a farmer, you know.

00:31:59.060 --> 00:32:02.060
And he says, "It's so useful.

00:32:02.060 --> 00:32:04.060
It's worth a hundred pounds."

00:32:04.060 --> 00:32:07.060
He says, "It kills all the rats."

00:32:07.060 --> 00:32:11.060
"Oh dear," cried Alice in a sorrowful tone.

00:32:11.060 --> 00:32:14.060
"I'm afraid I've offended it again."

00:32:14.060 --> 00:32:18.060
"For the mouse was swimming away from her as hard as it could go,

00:32:18.060 --> 00:32:22.060
and making quite a commotion in the pool," as it went.

00:32:22.060 --> 00:32:25.060
So she called softly after it.

00:32:25.060 --> 00:32:28.060
"Moustier, do come back again.

00:32:28.060 --> 00:32:33.060
And we won't talk about cats or dogs either if you don't like them."

00:32:33.060 --> 00:32:38.060
When the mouse heard this, it turned round and swam slowly back to her.

00:32:38.060 --> 00:32:43.060
Its face was quite pale, with passion, Alice thought.

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:49.060
And it said in a low trembling voice, "Let us get to the shore.

00:32:49.060 --> 00:32:52.060
And then I'll tell you by history.

00:32:52.060 --> 00:32:58.060
And you'll understand why it is I hate cats and dogs."

00:32:58.060 --> 00:33:00.060
It was high time to go.

00:33:00.060 --> 00:33:07.060
For the pool was getting quite crowded with the birds and animals that had fallen into it.

00:33:07.060 --> 00:33:16.060
There were a duck and a dodo, a lorry, and an eaglet, and several other curious creatures.

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:21.060
Alice led the way, and the whole party swam to the shore.

00:33:21.060 --> 00:33:45.060
CHAPTER III.

00:33:45.060 --> 00:33:49.060
They were indeed a queer-looking party that assembled on the bank.

00:33:49.060 --> 00:33:56.060
The birds, with daggled feathers, the animals with their fur clinging close to them, and

00:33:56.060 --> 00:34:00.060
all dripping wet, cross, and uncomfortable.

00:34:00.060 --> 00:34:04.060
The first question, of course, was, how to get dry again.

00:34:04.060 --> 00:34:11.060
They had a consultation about this, and after a few minutes, it seemed quite natural to Alice,

00:34:11.060 --> 00:34:17.060
to find herself talking familiarly with them, as if she had known them all her life.

00:34:17.060 --> 00:34:25.060
Indeed, she had quite a long argument with the lorry, who at last turned sulky, and would only say,

00:34:25.060 --> 00:34:29.060
"I am older than you, and must know better."

00:34:29.060 --> 00:34:39.060
And this, Alice would not allow, without knowing how old it was, and, as the lorry positively refused to tell its age,

00:34:39.060 --> 00:34:42.060
there was no more to be said.

00:34:42.060 --> 00:34:52.060
At last, the mouse, who seemed to be a person of authority among them, called out, "Sit down, all of you, and listen to me.

00:34:52.060 --> 00:34:55.060
I'll soon make you dry enough."

00:34:55.060 --> 00:35:02.060
They all sat down at once, and a large ring, with the mouse in the middle.

00:35:02.060 --> 00:35:11.060
Alice kept her eyes anxiously fixed on it, for she felt sure she would catch a bad cold if she did not get dry very soon.

00:35:11.060 --> 00:35:15.060
"A hem," said the mouse, with an important air.

00:35:15.060 --> 00:35:17.060
"Are you already?

00:35:17.060 --> 00:35:20.060
This is the driest thing I know.

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:23.060
Silence all round, if you please."

00:35:23.060 --> 00:35:33.060
William the Conqueror, whose cause was favored by the Pope, was soon submitted to, by the English, who wanted leaders,

00:35:33.060 --> 00:35:39.060
and had been, of late, much accustomed to usurpation and conquest.

00:35:39.060 --> 00:35:45.060
Edwin and Morcar, the Earl's of Mercia and Northumbria.

00:35:45.060 --> 00:35:49.060
"Ugh," said the lorry, with a shiver.

00:35:49.060 --> 00:35:54.060
"I beg your pardon," said the mouse, frowning, but very politely.

00:35:54.060 --> 00:35:56.060
"Did you speak?"

00:35:56.060 --> 00:35:59.060
"Not I," said the lorry hastily.

00:35:59.060 --> 00:36:02.060
"I thought you did," said the mouse.

00:36:02.060 --> 00:36:11.060
"I proceed." Edwin and Morcar, the Earl's of Mercia and Northumbria, declared for him,

00:36:11.060 --> 00:36:19.060
and even stiggened the patriotic archbishop of Canterbury, found it advisable, found what?"

00:36:19.060 --> 00:36:20.060
said the duck.

00:36:20.060 --> 00:36:25.060
"Found it," the mouse replied rather crossly.

00:36:25.060 --> 00:36:28.060
"Of course you know what it means.

00:36:28.060 --> 00:36:31.060
I know what it means well enough.

00:36:31.060 --> 00:36:35.060
When I find a thing," said the duck.

00:36:35.060 --> 00:36:39.060
"It's generally a frog or a worm."

00:36:39.060 --> 00:36:43.060
The question is, what did the archbishop find?

00:36:43.060 --> 00:36:48.060
The mouse did not notice this question, but hurriedly went on.

00:36:48.060 --> 00:36:55.060
"Found it advisable to go with Edgar Athling to meet William and offer him the crown."

00:36:55.060 --> 00:36:59.060
William's conduct, at first, was moderate.

00:36:59.060 --> 00:37:04.060
But the insolence of his Normans, how are you getting on now, my dear?"

00:37:04.060 --> 00:37:08.060
It continued, turning to Alice as it spoke.

00:37:08.060 --> 00:37:13.060
"As wet as ever," said Alice in a melancholy tone.

00:37:13.060 --> 00:37:16.060
"It doesn't seem to try me at all."

00:37:16.060 --> 00:37:22.060
"In that case," said the Dotto solemnly, rising to its feet.

00:37:22.060 --> 00:37:30.060
"I move that the meeting adjourned, for the immediate adoption of more energetic remedies."

00:37:30.060 --> 00:37:33.060
"Speak English," said the eaglet.

00:37:33.060 --> 00:37:38.060
"I don't know the meaning of half those long words, and what's more.

00:37:38.060 --> 00:37:41.060
I don't believe you do, either."

00:37:41.060 --> 00:37:45.060
And the eaglet bent down its head to hide a smile.

00:37:45.060 --> 00:37:48.060
Some of the other birds tittered audibly.

00:37:48.060 --> 00:37:53.060
"What I was going to say," said the Dotto in an offended tone,

00:37:53.060 --> 00:37:59.060
"was that the best thing to get us dry would be a caucus race."

00:37:59.060 --> 00:38:06.060
"What is a caucus race?" said Alice, not that she wanted much to know.

00:38:06.060 --> 00:38:12.060
But the Dotto had paused as if it thought that somebody ought to speak,

00:38:12.060 --> 00:38:16.060
and no one else seemed inclined to say anything.

00:38:16.060 --> 00:38:22.060
"Why," said the Dotto, "the best way to explain it is to do it."

00:38:22.060 --> 00:38:27.060
"And, as you might like to try to thing yourself, some winter day,

00:38:27.060 --> 00:38:31.060
I will tell you how the Dotto managed it."

00:38:31.060 --> 00:38:35.060
First, it marked out a race course in a sort of circle.

00:38:35.060 --> 00:38:39.060
"The exact shape doesn't matter," it said,

00:38:39.060 --> 00:38:45.060
"and then all the party were placed along the course, here and there."

00:38:45.060 --> 00:38:50.060
"There was no one, two, three, and away."

00:38:50.060 --> 00:38:54.060
But they began running when they liked, and left off when they liked,

00:38:54.060 --> 00:38:59.060
so that it was not easy to know when the race was over.

00:38:59.060 --> 00:39:03.060
However, when they had been running half an hour or so,

00:39:03.060 --> 00:39:08.060
and were quite dry again, the Dotto suddenly called out the race is over,

00:39:08.060 --> 00:39:13.060
and they all crowded around it, panting and asking.

00:39:13.060 --> 00:39:15.060
"But who has won?"

00:39:15.060 --> 00:39:20.060
This question, the Dotto could not answer without a great deal of thought,

00:39:20.060 --> 00:39:26.060
and it sat for a long time, with one finger pressed upon its forehead,

00:39:26.060 --> 00:39:31.060
the position in which you usually see Shakespeare in the pictures of him,

00:39:31.060 --> 00:39:34.060
while the rest waited in silence.

00:39:34.060 --> 00:39:39.060
At last, the Dotto said, "Everybody has won,

00:39:39.060 --> 00:39:42.060
and all must have prizes.

00:39:42.060 --> 00:39:45.060
But who is to give the prizes?"

00:39:45.060 --> 00:39:48.060
"Quite a course of voices asked."

00:39:48.060 --> 00:39:53.060
"Why, she, of course," said the Dotto,

00:39:53.060 --> 00:39:55.060
pointing to Alice with one finger,

00:39:55.060 --> 00:39:58.060
and the whole party at once crowded round her,

00:39:58.060 --> 00:40:03.060
calling out in a confused way, "Prises, prizes!"

00:40:03.060 --> 00:40:06.060
Alice had no idea what to do,

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:10.060
and in despair she put her hand in her pocket,

00:40:10.060 --> 00:40:16.060
pulled out a box of comforts, luckily the saltwater had not got into it,

00:40:16.060 --> 00:40:19.060
and handed them round as prizes.

00:40:19.060 --> 00:40:22.060
There was exactly one apiece all round,

00:40:22.060 --> 00:40:28.060
"But she must have a prize herself," you know, said the mouse.

00:40:28.060 --> 00:40:32.060
"Of course," the Dotto replied very gravely.

00:40:32.060 --> 00:40:35.060
"What else have you got in your pocket?"

00:40:35.060 --> 00:40:38.060
He went on, turning to Alice.

00:40:38.060 --> 00:40:41.060
"Only a thimble," said Alice, sadly.

00:40:41.060 --> 00:40:45.060
"Handed over here," said the Dotto.

00:40:45.060 --> 00:40:48.060
"Then they all crowded round her once more,

00:40:48.060 --> 00:40:52.060
while the Dotto solemnly presented the thimble,

00:40:52.060 --> 00:40:57.060
saying, "We beg your acceptance of this elegant thimble."

00:40:57.060 --> 00:41:01.060
And when it had finished this short speech,

00:41:01.060 --> 00:41:03.060
they all cheered.

00:41:03.060 --> 00:41:07.060
Alice thought the whole thing very absurd,

00:41:07.060 --> 00:41:12.060
but they all looked so grieve that she did not dare to laugh.

00:41:12.060 --> 00:41:16.060
And, as she could not think of anything to say,

00:41:16.060 --> 00:41:19.060
she simply bowed and took the thimble,

00:41:19.060 --> 00:41:21.060
looking as solemn as she could.

00:41:21.060 --> 00:41:25.060
The next thing was to eat the comforts.

00:41:25.060 --> 00:41:28.060
This caused some noise and confusion,

00:41:28.060 --> 00:41:33.060
as the large birds complained that they could not taste theirs,

00:41:33.060 --> 00:41:37.060
the small ones choked and had to be patted on the back.

00:41:37.060 --> 00:41:40.060
However, it was over at last,

00:41:40.060 --> 00:41:42.060
and they sat down again in a ring,

00:41:42.060 --> 00:41:46.060
and begged the mouse to tell them something more.

00:41:46.060 --> 00:41:51.060
"You promised to tell me your history, you know," said Alice.

00:41:51.060 --> 00:41:56.060
"And why it is you hate? See and D."

00:41:56.060 --> 00:42:01.060
She added in a whisper, half afraid that it would be offended again.

00:42:01.060 --> 00:42:06.060
"Mine is wrong and a sad tale," said the mouse,

00:42:06.060 --> 00:42:09.060
turning to Alice and sighing.

00:42:09.060 --> 00:42:13.060
"It is a long tale, certainly," said Alice,

00:42:13.060 --> 00:42:17.060
looking down with wonder at the mouse's tail.

00:42:17.060 --> 00:42:19.060
"But why do you call it sad?"

00:42:19.060 --> 00:42:21.060
And she kept on puzzling about it,

00:42:21.060 --> 00:42:23.060
while the mouse was speaking,

00:42:23.060 --> 00:42:27.060
so that her idea of the tale was something like this.

00:42:27.060 --> 00:42:31.060
Here, the mouse's story is printed,

00:42:31.060 --> 00:42:34.060
so that there are a few words on each line,

00:42:34.060 --> 00:42:38.060
and the lines are offset, making a wavy pattern,

00:42:38.060 --> 00:42:41.060
that looks like the tale of a mouse.

00:42:41.060 --> 00:42:44.060
Fury said it to a mouse,

00:42:44.060 --> 00:42:46.060
that he met in the house.

00:42:46.060 --> 00:42:50.060
"Let us both go to law. I will prosecute you.

00:42:50.060 --> 00:42:53.060
Come, I'll take no denial.

00:42:53.060 --> 00:42:55.060
We must have a trial.

00:42:55.060 --> 00:42:59.060
For really, this morning, I've nothing to do."

00:42:59.060 --> 00:43:01.060
Said the mouse to the Kerr,

00:43:01.060 --> 00:43:03.060
"Such a trial, dear sir,

00:43:03.060 --> 00:43:05.060
with no jury or judge,

00:43:05.060 --> 00:43:08.060
would be wasting our breath."

00:43:08.060 --> 00:43:12.060
"I'll be judge. I'll be jury," said Cunningham Fury.

00:43:12.060 --> 00:43:14.060
"I'll try the whole cause,

00:43:14.060 --> 00:43:17.060
and condemn you to death."

00:43:17.060 --> 00:43:23.060
"You are not attending," said the mouse to Alice severely.

00:43:23.060 --> 00:43:26.060
"What are you thinking of?"

00:43:26.060 --> 00:43:30.060
"I beg your pardon," said Alice very humbly.

00:43:30.060 --> 00:43:34.060
"You had got to the fifth bend, I think?"

00:43:34.060 --> 00:43:36.060
"I had not."

00:43:36.060 --> 00:43:41.060
Pried the mouse, sharply, and very angrily.

00:43:41.060 --> 00:43:44.060
"A nut!" said Alice,

00:43:44.060 --> 00:43:46.060
always ready to make herself useful,

00:43:46.060 --> 00:43:48.060
and looking anxiously about her.

00:43:48.060 --> 00:43:52.060
"Oh, do let me help to undo it.

00:43:52.060 --> 00:43:56.060
I shall do nothing of the sort," said the mouse,

00:43:56.060 --> 00:43:58.060
getting up and walking away.

00:43:58.060 --> 00:44:03.060
"You insult me by talking such nonsense.

00:44:03.060 --> 00:44:07.060
I didn't mean it," pleaded poor Alice.

00:44:07.060 --> 00:44:10.060
"But you're so easily offended, you know."

00:44:10.060 --> 00:44:13.060
The mouse only growled in reply,

00:44:13.060 --> 00:44:18.060
"Please come back and finish your story," Alice called after it,

00:44:18.060 --> 00:44:21.060
and the others all joined in chorus.

00:44:21.060 --> 00:44:23.060
"Yes, please do."

00:44:23.060 --> 00:44:26.060
But the mouse only shook its head impatiently,

00:44:26.060 --> 00:44:28.060
and walked a little quicker.

00:44:28.060 --> 00:44:33.060
"What a pity it wouldn't stay," sighed the lorry,

00:44:33.060 --> 00:44:36.060
as soon as it was quite out of sight,

00:44:36.060 --> 00:44:41.060
and an old crab took the opportunity of saying to her daughter.

00:44:41.060 --> 00:44:44.060
"Ah, my dear, let this be a lesson to you,

00:44:44.060 --> 00:44:47.060
never to lose your temper."

00:44:47.060 --> 00:44:52.060
"Hold your tongue, ma," said the young crab,

00:44:52.060 --> 00:44:54.060
a little snappishly.

00:44:54.060 --> 00:44:57.060
"You're enough to try the patience of an oyster.

00:44:57.060 --> 00:45:00.060
I wish I had our dina here.

00:45:00.060 --> 00:45:03.060
I know I do," said Alice aloud,

00:45:03.060 --> 00:45:06.060
addressing nobody in particular.

00:45:06.060 --> 00:45:08.060
"She'd soon fetch it back."

00:45:08.060 --> 00:45:15.060
"And who is dina if I might venture to ask the question," said the lorry.

00:45:15.060 --> 00:45:17.060
Alice replied eagerly,

00:45:17.060 --> 00:45:21.060
"For she was always ready to talk about her pet."

00:45:21.060 --> 00:45:23.060
"Dinas are cat.

00:45:23.060 --> 00:45:28.060
And she's such a capital one for catching mice you can't think.

00:45:28.060 --> 00:45:32.060
And oh, I wish you could see her after the birds."

00:45:32.060 --> 00:45:36.060
"Why, she'll eat a little bird as soon as look at it."

00:45:36.060 --> 00:45:41.060
"This speech caused a remarkable sensation among the party.

00:45:41.060 --> 00:45:44.060
Some other birds hurried off at once.

00:45:44.060 --> 00:45:49.060
One old magpie began wrapping itself up very carefully,

00:45:49.060 --> 00:45:53.060
remarking, "I really must be getting home.

00:45:53.060 --> 00:45:56.060
The night air doesn't suit my throat."

00:45:56.060 --> 00:46:00.060
"And a canary called out in a trembling voice to its children."

00:46:00.060 --> 00:46:02.060
"Come away, my dear.

00:46:02.060 --> 00:46:05.060
It's high time you were all in bed."

00:46:05.060 --> 00:46:09.060
On various pretexts, they all moved off.

00:46:09.060 --> 00:46:12.060
And Alice was soon left alone.

00:46:12.060 --> 00:46:19.060
"I wish I hadn't mentioned dina," she said to herself in a melancholy tone.

00:46:19.060 --> 00:46:25.060
"Nobody seems to like her down here, and I'm sure she's the best cat in the world."

00:46:25.060 --> 00:46:28.060
"Oh, my dear, dina.

00:46:28.060 --> 00:46:31.060
I wonder if I shall ever see you any more."

00:46:31.060 --> 00:46:35.060
And here, poor Alice began to cry again.

00:46:35.060 --> 00:46:39.060
For she felt very lonely and low-spirited.

00:46:39.060 --> 00:46:46.060
In a little while, however, she again heard a little patterning of footsteps in the distance,

00:46:46.060 --> 00:46:52.060
and she looked up eagerly, half-hoping that the mouse had changed his mind,

00:46:52.060 --> 00:46:57.060
and was coming back to finish his story.

00:46:57.060 --> 00:47:13.060
CHAPTER IV

00:47:13.060 --> 00:47:25.060
It was the white rabbit, trotting slowly back again,

00:47:25.060 --> 00:47:30.060
acting anxiously about, as it went, as if it had lost something,

00:47:30.060 --> 00:47:33.060
and she heard it muttering to itself.

00:47:33.060 --> 00:47:34.060
"The Duchess!

00:47:34.060 --> 00:47:35.060
The Duchess!

00:47:35.060 --> 00:47:36.060
Oh, my dear, pause!

00:47:36.060 --> 00:47:38.060
Oh, my furs and whiskers!

00:47:38.060 --> 00:47:42.060
She'll get me executed, as sure as ferrets are ferrets!

00:47:42.060 --> 00:47:45.060
Where can I have dropped them, I wonder?"

00:47:45.060 --> 00:47:51.060
Alice guessed in a moment that it was looking for the fan, and the pair of white kid

00:47:51.060 --> 00:47:56.060
gloves, and she very good-naturedly began hunting about for them.

00:47:56.060 --> 00:47:59.060
But they were nowhere to be seen.

00:47:59.060 --> 00:48:03.060
Everything seemed to have changed since her swim in the pool,

00:48:03.060 --> 00:48:09.060
and the great hall, with the glass table and the little door, had vanished completely.

00:48:09.060 --> 00:48:15.060
Very soon, the rabbit noticed Alice, as she went hunting about,

00:48:15.060 --> 00:48:18.060
and called out to her in an angry tone.

00:48:18.060 --> 00:48:22.060
"Why, Mary Ann, what are you doing out here?

00:48:22.060 --> 00:48:24.060
Run home this moment!

00:48:24.060 --> 00:48:27.060
And fetch me a pair of gloves and a fan!

00:48:27.060 --> 00:48:29.060
Quick now!"

00:48:29.060 --> 00:48:35.060
And Alice was so much frightened that she ran off at once in the direction it pointed to,

00:48:35.060 --> 00:48:39.060
without trying to explain the mistake it had made.

00:48:39.060 --> 00:48:43.060
"He took me for his house-made!" she said to herself as she ran.

00:48:43.060 --> 00:48:47.060
"How surprised he'll be when he finds out who I am.

00:48:47.060 --> 00:48:50.060
But I'd better take him his fan in his gloves.

00:48:50.060 --> 00:48:53.060
That is, if I can find them!"

00:48:53.060 --> 00:48:57.060
As she said this, she came upon a neat little house.

00:48:57.060 --> 00:49:03.060
On the door of which was a bright brass pleat, with the name W. Rabbit,

00:49:03.060 --> 00:49:05.060
engraved upon it.

00:49:05.060 --> 00:49:10.060
She went in without knocking, and hurried upstairs.

00:49:10.060 --> 00:49:14.060
In great fear, lest she should meet the real Mary Ann.

00:49:14.060 --> 00:49:20.060
And be turned out of the house before she had found the fan and gloves.

00:49:20.060 --> 00:49:24.060
"How queer it seems," Alice said to herself.

00:49:24.060 --> 00:49:28.060
"To be going messages, for a rabbit!

00:49:28.060 --> 00:49:32.060
I suppose Dina will be sending me on messages next!"

00:49:32.060 --> 00:49:37.060
And she began fancying the sort of thing that would happen.

00:49:37.060 --> 00:49:42.060
"Miss Alice, come here directly, and get ready for your walk!"

00:49:42.060 --> 00:49:44.060
"Coming in a minute, nurse.

00:49:44.060 --> 00:49:48.060
But I've got to see that the mouse doesn't get out.

00:49:48.060 --> 00:49:52.060
Only, I don't think!" Alice went on.

00:49:52.060 --> 00:49:58.060
"That they'd let Dina stop in the house if it began ordering people about like that!"

00:49:58.060 --> 00:50:04.060
By this time, she had found her way into a tiny little room with a table in the window,

00:50:04.060 --> 00:50:11.060
and on it, as she had hoped, a fan and two or three pairs of tiny white kid gloves.

00:50:11.060 --> 00:50:17.060
She took up the fan and a pair of the gloves, and was just going to leave the room.

00:50:17.060 --> 00:50:22.060
When her eyes fell upon, a little bottle that stood near the looking glass.

00:50:22.060 --> 00:50:28.060
There was no label this time, with the words "drink me."

00:50:28.060 --> 00:50:32.060
But nevertheless, she uncorked it and put it to her lips.

00:50:32.060 --> 00:50:39.060
"I know! Something interesting is sure to happen," she said to herself.

00:50:39.060 --> 00:50:45.060
"Whenever I eat or drink anything, so I'll just see what this bottle does.

00:50:45.060 --> 00:50:48.060
I do hope it'll make me grow large again.

00:50:48.060 --> 00:50:53.060
For really, I'm quite tired of being such a tiny little thing."

00:50:53.060 --> 00:50:58.060
It did so indeed, and much sooner than she had expected.

00:50:58.060 --> 00:51:04.060
Before she had drunk half the bottle, she found her head pressing against the ceiling,

00:51:04.060 --> 00:51:08.060
and had to stoop to save her neck from being broken.

00:51:08.060 --> 00:51:13.060
She hastily put down the bottle, saying to herself, "That's quite enough.

00:51:13.060 --> 00:51:16.060
I hope I shan't grow anymore.

00:51:16.060 --> 00:51:19.060
As it is, I can't get out at the door.

00:51:19.060 --> 00:51:23.060
I do wish I hadn't drunk quite so much."

00:51:23.060 --> 00:51:26.060
Alas, it was too late to wish that.

00:51:26.060 --> 00:51:33.060
She went on growing, and growing, and very soon had to kneel down on the floor.

00:51:33.060 --> 00:51:39.060
In another minute, there was not even room for this, and she tried the effect of lying down,

00:51:39.060 --> 00:51:46.060
with one elbow against the door, and the other arm curled round her head.

00:51:46.060 --> 00:51:53.060
Still, she went on growing, and, as a last resource, she put one arm out of the window,

00:51:53.060 --> 00:52:00.060
and one foot up the chimney, and said to herself, "Now I can do no more!

00:52:00.060 --> 00:52:02.060
Whatever happens!

00:52:02.060 --> 00:52:04.060
That will become of me!"

00:52:04.060 --> 00:52:10.060
Luckily for Alice, the little magic bottle had now had its full effect,

00:52:10.060 --> 00:52:12.060
and she grew no larger.

00:52:12.060 --> 00:52:22.060
Still, it was very uncomfortable, and, as there seemed to be no sort of chance of her ever getting out of the room again,

00:52:22.060 --> 00:52:25.060
no wonder she felt unhappy.

00:52:25.060 --> 00:52:28.060
It was much pleasanter at home.

00:52:28.060 --> 00:52:30.060
Thought poor Alice.

00:52:30.060 --> 00:52:38.060
When one wasn't always growing larger and smaller, and being ordered around by mice and rabbits,

00:52:38.060 --> 00:52:42.060
I almost wished I had gone down that rabbit hole.

00:52:42.060 --> 00:52:50.060
And yet, and yet, it's rather curious, you know, this sort of life.

00:52:50.060 --> 00:52:54.060
I do wonder what can have happened to me.

00:52:54.060 --> 00:53:01.060
When I used to read fairy tales, I fancied that kind of thing never happened.

00:53:01.060 --> 00:53:05.060
And now, here I am, in the middle of one.

00:53:05.060 --> 00:53:08.060
There ought to be a book written about me.

00:53:08.060 --> 00:53:10.060
That there ought.

00:53:10.060 --> 00:53:13.060
And when I grow up, I'll write one.

00:53:13.060 --> 00:53:16.060
But I'm grown up now."

00:53:16.060 --> 00:53:18.060
She added in a sorrowful tone.

00:53:18.060 --> 00:53:24.060
"At least there's no room to grow up anymore here."

00:53:24.060 --> 00:53:26.060
"But then," thought Alice.

00:53:26.060 --> 00:53:30.060
"Shall I never get any older than I am now?"

00:53:30.060 --> 00:53:33.060
"That'll be a comfort, one way.

00:53:33.060 --> 00:53:35.060
Never to be an old woman."

00:53:35.060 --> 00:53:39.060
"But then, always to have lessons to learn."

00:53:39.060 --> 00:53:42.060
"Oh, I shouldn't like that."

00:53:42.060 --> 00:53:45.060
"Oh, you foolish Alice?"

00:53:45.060 --> 00:53:47.060
She answered herself.

00:53:47.060 --> 00:53:50.060
"How can you learn lessons in here?

00:53:50.060 --> 00:53:53.060
Why, there's hardly any room for you.

00:53:53.060 --> 00:53:56.060
And no room at all for any lesson books."

00:53:56.060 --> 00:54:02.060
And so she went on, taking first one side, and then the other,

00:54:02.060 --> 00:54:06.060
and making quite a conversation of it altogether.

00:54:06.060 --> 00:54:11.060
But after a few minutes, she heard a voice outside, and stopped to listen.

00:54:11.060 --> 00:54:15.060
"Marianne, Marianne!" said the voice.

00:54:15.060 --> 00:54:18.060
"Fetch me, my gloves, this moment!"

00:54:18.060 --> 00:54:22.060
Then came a little patterning of feet on the stairs.

00:54:22.060 --> 00:54:26.060
Alice knew it was the rabbit coming to look for her.

00:54:26.060 --> 00:54:29.060
And she trembled till she shook the house.

00:54:29.060 --> 00:54:36.060
Quite forgetting that she was now about a thousand times as large as the rabbit.

00:54:36.060 --> 00:54:39.060
And had no reason to be afraid of it.

00:54:39.060 --> 00:54:44.060
Presently, the rabbit came up to the door and tried to open it.

00:54:44.060 --> 00:54:50.060
But as the door opened inwards, and Alice's elbow was pressed hard against it.

00:54:50.060 --> 00:54:53.060
That attempt proved a failure.

00:54:53.060 --> 00:54:58.060
Alice heard it say to itself, "Then I'll go around and get in at the window.

00:54:58.060 --> 00:55:01.060
That you won't!" thought Alice.

00:55:01.060 --> 00:55:07.060
And, after waiting till she fancied, she heard the rabbit just under the window.

00:55:07.060 --> 00:55:12.060
She suddenly spread out her hand and made a snatch in the air.

00:55:12.060 --> 00:55:20.060
She did not get hold of anything, but she heard a little shriek and a fall and a crash of broken glass.

00:55:20.060 --> 00:55:29.060
From which, she concluded that it was just possible it had fallen into a cucumber frame, or something of the sort.

00:55:29.060 --> 00:55:33.060
Next came an angry voice, the rabbits.

00:55:33.060 --> 00:55:36.060
"Pat, Pat, where are you?"

00:55:36.060 --> 00:55:40.060
And then a voice she had never heard before.

00:55:40.060 --> 00:55:45.060
"Sure, then, I'm here, digging for apples," Aaroner.

00:55:45.060 --> 00:55:50.060
"Dicking for apples, indeed!" said the rabbit angrily.

00:55:50.060 --> 00:55:56.060
"Here, come and help me out of this!" sounds of more broken glass.

00:55:56.060 --> 00:56:00.060
"No, tell me, Pat, what's that in the window?"

00:56:00.060 --> 00:56:03.060
"Sure, it's an arm," Aaroner.

00:56:03.060 --> 00:56:10.060
He pronounced it. "Arum," "An arm, you goose?"

00:56:10.060 --> 00:56:14.060
"Whoever saw one that size. Why, it feels the whole window."

00:56:14.060 --> 00:56:19.060
"Sure, it does," Aaroner. "But it's an arm for all that."

00:56:19.060 --> 00:56:24.060
"Well, it's got no business there, at any rate. Go and take it away."

00:56:24.060 --> 00:56:32.060
There was a long silence after this, and Alice could only hear whispers now and then, such as,

00:56:32.060 --> 00:56:39.060
"Sure, I don't like it," Aaroner, "at all, at all. Do as I tell you, you coward."

00:56:39.060 --> 00:56:45.060
And, at last, she spread out her hand again, and made another snatch in the air.

00:56:45.060 --> 00:56:52.060
This time, there were two little shrieks, and more sounds of broken glass.

00:56:52.060 --> 00:56:57.060
"What a number of cucumber frames there must be!" thought Alice.

00:56:57.060 --> 00:57:04.060
"I wonder what they'll do next." As for pulling me out of the window, I only wish they could.

00:57:04.060 --> 00:57:08.060
"I'm sure I don't want to stay in here any longer."

00:57:08.060 --> 00:57:12.060
She waited for some time without hearing anything more.

00:57:12.060 --> 00:57:19.060
At last came a rumbling of little cartwheels, and the sound of a good many voices, all talking together.

00:57:19.060 --> 00:57:23.060
She made out the words. "Where's the other ladder?"

00:57:23.060 --> 00:57:28.060
"Why, I had to bring but one. Bill's got the other."

00:57:28.060 --> 00:57:30.060
"Bill, fetch it here, lad."

00:57:30.060 --> 00:57:33.060
"Here, put 'em up at this corner."

00:57:33.060 --> 00:57:39.060
"No, tie 'em together first. They don't reach half-height yet."

00:57:39.060 --> 00:57:43.060
"Oh, they'll do well enough. Don't be particular."

00:57:43.060 --> 00:57:48.060
"Here, Bill, catch all to this rope. Where's the other ladder?"

00:57:48.060 --> 00:57:52.060
"Why, I had to bring but one. Bill's got the other."

00:57:52.060 --> 00:57:55.060
"Bill, fetch it here, lad."

00:57:55.060 --> 00:57:58.060
"Here, put 'em up at this corner."

00:57:58.060 --> 00:58:03.060
"No, tie 'em together first. They don't reach half-height enough yet."

00:58:03.060 --> 00:58:07.060
"Oh, they'll do well enough. Don't be particular."

00:58:07.060 --> 00:58:10.060
"Here, Bill. Catch all to this rope."

00:58:10.060 --> 00:58:13.060
"Will the roof bear?"

00:58:13.060 --> 00:58:15.060
"Mind that I lose slate."

00:58:15.060 --> 00:58:18.060
"Oh, it's coming down. Heads below."

00:58:18.060 --> 00:58:23.060
"A loud crash."

00:58:23.060 --> 00:58:26.060
"Now, who did that?"

00:58:26.060 --> 00:58:30.060
"It was Bill, I fancy. Who's to go down the chimney?"

00:58:30.060 --> 00:58:34.060
"Nee, I shunt. You do it."

00:58:34.060 --> 00:58:36.060
"That I won't, then."

00:58:36.060 --> 00:58:42.060
"Bill's to go down. Here, Bill. The master says you're to go down the chimney."

00:58:42.060 --> 00:58:46.060
"Oh, so Bill's got to come down the chimney, has he?"

00:58:46.060 --> 00:58:53.060
"Shy, they seem to put everything upon Bill. I wouldn't be in Bill's place for a good deal."

00:58:53.060 --> 00:58:59.060
"This fireplace is narrow, to be sure. But I think I can kick a little."

00:58:59.060 --> 00:59:06.060
"She drew her foot as far down the chimney as she could, and waited till she heard a little animal."

00:59:06.060 --> 00:59:10.060
"She couldn't guess of what sort it was."

00:59:10.060 --> 00:59:16.060
"Scratching and scrambling about in the chimney, close above her."

00:59:16.060 --> 00:59:19.060
"Then, saying to herself, 'This is Bill.'"

00:59:19.060 --> 00:59:24.060
"She gave one sharp kick, and waited to see what would happen next."

00:59:24.060 --> 00:59:29.060
"The first thing she heard was a general course of, 'There goes Bill!'

00:59:29.060 --> 00:59:34.060
"Then the rabbit's voice along. 'Catch him, you by the hedge.'"

00:59:34.060 --> 00:59:42.060
"Then silence. And then another confusion of voices. Hold up his head. Brandy now."

00:59:42.060 --> 00:59:50.060
"Don't choke him. How was it old fellow? What happened to you? Tell us all about it."

00:59:50.060 --> 00:59:56.060
"Last came a feeble, squeaking voice. That's Bill!" thought Alice.

00:59:56.060 --> 01:00:05.060
"Well, I hard to know. No more, thank you. I'm better now. But I'm a deal too flustered to tell you."

01:00:05.060 --> 01:00:13.060
"All I know is, something comes at me like a jack in the box. And up our goes like a sky-rocket."

01:00:13.060 --> 01:00:18.060
"So you did, old fellow," said the others.

01:00:18.060 --> 01:00:23.060
"We must burn the house down," said the rabbit's voice.

01:00:23.060 --> 01:00:30.060
"And Alice called out as loud as she could. If you do, I'll set Dina at you."

01:00:30.060 --> 01:00:35.060
"There was a dead silence instantly, and Alice thought to herself."

01:00:35.060 --> 01:00:42.060
"I wonder what they will do next. If they had any sense, they'd take the roof off."

01:00:42.060 --> 01:00:48.060
After a minute or two, they began moving about again, and Alice heard the rabbit say.

01:00:48.060 --> 01:00:54.060
"A barrel fool will do to begin with. A barrel fool of what?"

01:00:54.060 --> 01:01:01.060
thought Alice, but she had not long to doubt. For the next moment, a shower of little pebbles

01:01:01.060 --> 01:01:06.060
came rattling in at the window, and some of them hit her in the face.

01:01:06.060 --> 01:01:11.060
"I'll put a stop to this," she said to herself, and shouted out.

01:01:11.060 --> 01:01:17.060
"You'd better not do that again," which produced another dead silence.

01:01:17.060 --> 01:01:24.060
Alice noticed with some surprise that the pebbles were all turning into little cakes as

01:01:24.060 --> 01:01:28.060
they lay on the floor, and a bright idea came into her head.

01:01:28.060 --> 01:01:33.060
"If I eat one of these cakes," she thought.

01:01:33.060 --> 01:01:39.060
"It's sure to make some change in my size, and as it can't possibly make me larger,

01:01:39.060 --> 01:01:42.060
it must make me smaller," I suppose.

01:01:42.060 --> 01:01:49.060
So she swallowed one of the cakes, and was delighted to find that she began shrinking directly.

01:01:49.060 --> 01:01:54.060
As soon as she was small enough to get through the door, she ran out of the house,

01:01:54.060 --> 01:02:00.060
and found quite a crowd of little animals and birds waiting outside.

01:02:00.060 --> 01:02:07.060
"The poor little lizard," Bill, was in the middle, being held up by two guinea pigs,

01:02:07.060 --> 01:02:14.060
who were giving it something out of a bottle. They all made a rush at Alice the moment she appeared,

01:02:14.060 --> 01:02:20.060
but she ran off as hard as she could, and soon found herself safe in a thick wood.

01:02:20.060 --> 01:02:27.060
"The first thing I've got to do," said Alice to herself, as she wandered about in the wood,

01:02:27.060 --> 01:02:36.060
"is to grow to my right size again, and the second thing is to find my way into that lovely garden.

01:02:36.060 --> 01:02:40.060
I think that will be the best plan."

01:02:40.060 --> 01:02:47.060
It sounded an excellent plan, no doubt, and very neatly and simply arranged.

01:02:47.060 --> 01:02:54.060
The only difficulty was that she had not the smallest idea how to set about it,

01:02:54.060 --> 01:02:58.060
and while she was peering about anxiously among the trees,

01:02:58.060 --> 01:03:04.060
a little sharp bark, chest over her head, made her look up in a great hurry,

01:03:04.060 --> 01:03:09.060
an enormous puppy was looking down at her with large round eyes,

01:03:09.060 --> 01:03:14.060
and feebly stretching out one paw, trying to touch her.

01:03:14.060 --> 01:03:19.060
"Poor little thing," said Alice, in a coaxing tone,

01:03:19.060 --> 01:03:22.060
and she tried hard to whistle to it,

01:03:22.060 --> 01:03:29.060
but she was terribly frightened all the time at the thought that it might be hungry,

01:03:29.060 --> 01:03:37.060
in which case it would be very likely to eat her up in spite of all her coaxing.

01:03:37.060 --> 01:03:45.060
Hardly knowing what she did, she picked up a little bit of stick and held it out to the puppy,

01:03:45.060 --> 01:03:50.060
whereupon the puppy jumped into the air off all its feet at once,

01:03:50.060 --> 01:03:57.060
with a yelp of delight, and rushed at the stick, and made believe to worry it.

01:03:57.060 --> 01:04:04.060
Then Alice dodged behind a great thistle to keep herself from being run over,

01:04:04.060 --> 01:04:10.060
and the moment she appeared on the other side, the puppy made another rush at the stick,

01:04:10.060 --> 01:04:15.060
and tumbled head over heels in its hurry to get hold of it.

01:04:15.060 --> 01:04:21.060
Then Alice, thinking it was very like having a game of play with a cart horse,

01:04:21.060 --> 01:04:28.060
and expecting every moment to be trampled under its feet, ran round the thistle again.

01:04:28.060 --> 01:04:33.060
Then the puppy began a series of short charges at the stick,

01:04:33.060 --> 01:04:38.060
running a very little ways forward each time, and a long way back,

01:04:38.060 --> 01:04:41.060
and barking hoarsely all the while.

01:04:41.060 --> 01:04:45.060
Till at last, it sat down a good way off,

01:04:45.060 --> 01:04:52.060
panting, with its tongue hanging out of its mouth, and its great eyes half shut.

01:04:52.060 --> 01:04:56.060
This seemed to Alice a good opportunity for making her escape,

01:04:56.060 --> 01:05:02.060
so she set off at once, and ran till she was quite tired and out of breath,

01:05:02.060 --> 01:05:07.060
and till the puppy's bark sounded quite faint in the distance.

01:05:07.060 --> 01:05:12.060
"And yet what a dear little puppy was," said Alice,

01:05:12.060 --> 01:05:16.060
as she went against a buttercup to rest herself,

01:05:16.060 --> 01:05:19.060
and fanned herself with one of the leaves.

01:05:19.060 --> 01:05:23.060
"I should have liked teaching it tricks very much if,

01:05:23.060 --> 01:05:28.060
if I'd only been the right size to do it, oh dear,

01:05:28.060 --> 01:05:32.060
I'd nearly forgotten that I've got to grow up again.

01:05:32.060 --> 01:05:36.060
Let me see, how is it to be managed?

01:05:36.060 --> 01:05:41.060
I suppose I ought to eat or drink something or other,

01:05:41.060 --> 01:05:44.060
but the great question is, what?"

01:05:44.060 --> 01:05:47.060
The great question certainly was.

01:05:47.060 --> 01:05:48.060
"What?"

01:05:48.060 --> 01:05:54.060
Alice looked all round her at the flowers and the bleeds of grass,

01:05:54.060 --> 01:05:59.060
but she did not see anything that looked like the right thing to eat or drink

01:05:59.060 --> 01:06:01.060
under the circumstances.

01:06:01.060 --> 01:06:04.060
There was a large mushroom growing near her,

01:06:04.060 --> 01:06:07.060
about the same height as herself,

01:06:07.060 --> 01:06:12.060
and when she had looked under it, and on both sides of it,

01:06:12.060 --> 01:06:17.060
and behind it, it occurred to her that she might as well look

01:06:17.060 --> 01:06:20.060
and see what was on the top of it.

01:06:20.060 --> 01:06:24.060
She stretched herself up on Tipto,

01:06:24.060 --> 01:06:27.060
and peeped over the edge of the mushroom,

01:06:27.060 --> 01:06:32.060
and her eyes immediately met those of a large blue caterpillar

01:06:32.060 --> 01:06:36.060
that was sitting on the top with its arms folded.

01:06:36.060 --> 01:06:39.060
Quietly smoking a long hookah,

01:06:39.060 --> 01:06:45.060
and taking not the smallest notice of her or of anything else.

01:06:45.060 --> 01:06:53.060
End of Chapter 4

01:06:53.060 --> 01:07:00.060
Chapter 5 of Alice's Adventures in Wonderland by Lewis Carroll.

01:07:00.060 --> 01:07:04.060
This liberal box recording is in the public domain.

01:07:04.060 --> 01:07:07.060
Chapter 5

01:07:07.060 --> 01:07:10.060
Advice from a caterpillar

01:07:10.060 --> 01:07:15.060
The caterpillar and Alice looked at each other for some time in silence.

01:07:15.060 --> 01:07:19.060
At last, the caterpillar took the hookah out of its mouth

01:07:19.060 --> 01:07:23.060
and addressed her in a languid, sleepy voice.

01:07:23.060 --> 01:07:27.060
"Who are you?" said the caterpillar.

01:07:27.060 --> 01:07:32.060
"This was not an encouraging opening for a conversation."

01:07:32.060 --> 01:07:35.060
Alice replied, rather shyly.

01:07:35.060 --> 01:07:39.060
"I hardly know, sir, just that present.

01:07:39.060 --> 01:07:43.060
At least I know who I was when I got up this morning.

01:07:43.060 --> 01:07:48.060
But I think I must have been changed several times since then."

01:07:48.060 --> 01:07:54.060
"What do you mean by that?" said the caterpillar sternly.

01:07:54.060 --> 01:07:56.060
"Explain yourself."

01:07:56.060 --> 01:08:00.060
"I can't explain myself," I'm afraid.

01:08:00.060 --> 01:08:03.060
"Sir," said Alice.

01:08:03.060 --> 01:08:06.060
"Because I'm not myself, you see."

01:08:06.060 --> 01:08:10.060
"I don't see," said the caterpillar.

01:08:10.060 --> 01:08:13.060
"I'm afraid I can't put it more clearly."

01:08:13.060 --> 01:08:16.060
Alice replied very politely.

01:08:16.060 --> 01:08:20.060
"For I can't understand it myself to begin with."

01:08:20.060 --> 01:08:25.060
And being so many different sizes in a day is very confusing.

01:08:25.060 --> 01:08:29.060
"It isn't," said the caterpillar.

01:08:29.060 --> 01:08:33.060
"Well, perhaps you haven't found it so yet,"

01:08:33.060 --> 01:08:34.060
said Alice.

01:08:34.060 --> 01:08:41.060
"But when you have to turn into a chrysalis, you will someday, you know.

01:08:41.060 --> 01:08:47.060
And then after that, into a butterfly, I should think you'll feel it a little queer.

01:08:47.060 --> 01:08:48.060
Won't you?"

01:08:48.060 --> 01:08:51.060
"Not a bit," said the caterpillar.

01:08:51.060 --> 01:08:56.060
"Well, perhaps your feelings may be different," said Alice.

01:08:56.060 --> 01:09:01.060
"All I know is, it would feel very queer to me."

01:09:01.060 --> 01:09:05.060
"You," said the caterpillar, contemptuously.

01:09:05.060 --> 01:09:08.060
"Who are you?"

01:09:08.060 --> 01:09:12.060
Which brought them back again to the beginning of the conversation.

01:09:12.060 --> 01:09:19.060
Alice felt a little irritated at the caterpillar's making such very short remarks.

01:09:19.060 --> 01:09:28.060
And she drew herself up and said very gravely, "I think you ought to tell me who you are."

01:09:28.060 --> 01:09:29.060
"First."

01:09:29.060 --> 01:09:32.060
"Why?" said the caterpillar.

01:09:32.060 --> 01:09:36.060
"Here was another puzzling question."

01:09:36.060 --> 01:09:40.060
And as Alice could not think of any good reason.

01:09:40.060 --> 01:09:46.060
And as the caterpillar seemed to be in a very unpleasant state of mind.

01:09:46.060 --> 01:09:48.060
She turned away.

01:09:48.060 --> 01:09:52.060
"Come back," the caterpillar called after her.

01:09:52.060 --> 01:09:55.060
"I've something important to say."

01:09:55.060 --> 01:09:58.060
"This," sounded promising.

01:09:58.060 --> 01:10:02.060
"Certainly," Alice turned and came back again.

01:10:02.060 --> 01:10:06.060
"Keep your temper," said the caterpillar.

01:10:06.060 --> 01:10:14.060
"Is that all?" said Alice, swallowing down her anger as well as she could.

01:10:14.060 --> 01:10:16.060
"No," said the caterpillar.

01:10:16.060 --> 01:10:22.060
Alice thought she might as well wait, as she had nothing else to do.

01:10:22.060 --> 01:10:27.060
And perhaps, after all, it might tell her something worth hearing.

01:10:27.060 --> 01:10:32.060
"For some minutes it puffed away without speaking.

01:10:32.060 --> 01:10:39.060
But at last it unfolded its arms, took the hookah out of its mouth again, and said,

01:10:39.060 --> 01:10:43.060
"So you think you're changed, do you?"

01:10:43.060 --> 01:10:47.060
"I'm afraid I am, sir," said Alice.

01:10:47.060 --> 01:10:54.060
"I can't remember things as I used, and I don't keep the same size for ten minutes together."

01:10:54.060 --> 01:10:57.060
"Can't remember what?"

01:10:57.060 --> 01:11:00.060
"Things," said the caterpillar.

01:11:00.060 --> 01:11:07.060
"Well, I've tried to say, how doth the little busy be, but it all came different."

01:11:07.060 --> 01:11:13.060
Alice replied in a very melancholy voice.

01:11:13.060 --> 01:11:18.060
"You are old, Father William," said the caterpillar.

01:11:18.060 --> 01:11:21.060
Alice folded her hands and began.

01:11:21.060 --> 01:11:28.060
"You are old, Father William," the young man said, "and your hair has become very white."

01:11:28.060 --> 01:11:32.060
"And yet you incessantly stand on your head."

01:11:32.060 --> 01:11:37.060
"Do you think at your age it is right?"

01:11:37.060 --> 01:11:40.060
"In my youth," Father William replied to his son.

01:11:40.060 --> 01:11:43.060
"I feared it might injure the brain.

01:11:43.060 --> 01:11:50.060
But now that I'm perfectly sure I have none, why I do it again and again."

01:11:50.060 --> 01:11:59.060
"You are old," said the youth, as I mentioned before, and have grown most uncommonly fat.

01:11:59.060 --> 01:12:03.060
"Yet you turned a back somersault in at the door.

01:12:03.060 --> 01:12:06.060
Pray, what is the reason of that?"

01:12:06.060 --> 01:12:11.060
"In my youth," said the sage, as he shook his grey locks.

01:12:11.060 --> 01:12:14.060
"I kept all my limbs very supple.

01:12:14.060 --> 01:12:19.060
By the use of this ointment, one shilling the box.

01:12:19.060 --> 01:12:21.060
"Allow me to sell you a couple?"

01:12:21.060 --> 01:12:26.060
"You are old," said the youth, and your jaws are too weak,

01:12:26.060 --> 01:12:29.060
for anything tougher than soot.

01:12:29.060 --> 01:12:33.060
"Yet you finish the goose with the bones in the beak.

01:12:33.060 --> 01:12:36.060
Pray, how did you manage to do it?"

01:12:36.060 --> 01:12:41.060
"In my youth," said his father, "I took to the law."

01:12:41.060 --> 01:12:44.060
"And argued each case with my wife."

01:12:44.060 --> 01:12:51.060
"And the muscular strength, which it gave to my jaw, has lasted the rest of my life."

01:12:51.060 --> 01:12:54.060
"You are old," said the youth.

01:12:54.060 --> 01:12:57.060
"One would hardly suppose."

01:12:57.060 --> 01:13:00.060
"That your eye was as steady as ever."

01:13:00.060 --> 01:13:04.060
"Yet you bounced an eel on the end of your nose.

01:13:04.060 --> 01:13:07.060
What made you so awfully clever?"

01:13:07.060 --> 01:13:14.060
"I have answered three questions, and that is enough," said his father.

01:13:14.060 --> 01:13:16.060
"Don't give yourself errors."

01:13:16.060 --> 01:13:21.060
"Do you think I can listen all day to such stuff?"

01:13:21.060 --> 01:13:24.060
"Be off, or I'll kick you down the stairs."

01:13:24.060 --> 01:13:29.060
"That is not," said Wright, said the caterpillar.

01:13:29.060 --> 01:13:34.060
"And not quite right, I'm afraid," said Alice, timidly.

01:13:34.060 --> 01:13:37.060
"Some of the words have got altered."

01:13:37.060 --> 01:13:43.060
"It is wrong from beginning to end," said the caterpillar,

01:13:43.060 --> 01:13:47.060
decidedly, and there were silence for some minutes.

01:13:47.060 --> 01:13:51.060
"The caterpillar was the first to speak."

01:13:51.060 --> 01:13:54.060
"What size do you want to be?"

01:13:54.060 --> 01:13:55.060
"It asked."

01:13:55.060 --> 01:14:01.060
"Oh, I'm not particular as the size," Alice hastily replied.

01:14:01.060 --> 01:14:06.060
"Only one doesn't like changing so often, you know."

01:14:06.060 --> 01:14:10.060
"I don't know," said the caterpillar.

01:14:10.060 --> 01:14:12.060
Alice said nothing.

01:14:12.060 --> 01:14:20.060
She had never been so much contradicted in her life before, and she felt that she was losing her temper.

01:14:20.060 --> 01:14:24.060
"Are you content now?" said the caterpillar.

01:14:24.060 --> 01:14:33.060
"Well, I should like to be a little larger, sir, if you wouldn't mind," said Alice.

01:14:33.060 --> 01:14:37.060
"Three inches is such a wretched height to be.

01:14:37.060 --> 01:14:42.060
It is a very good height indeed," said the caterpillar angrily,

01:14:42.060 --> 01:14:45.060
rearing itself upright as it spoke.

01:14:45.060 --> 01:14:49.060
"It was exactly three inches high."

01:14:49.060 --> 01:14:54.060
"But I'm not used to it," pleaded poor Alice in a pittiest tone,

01:14:54.060 --> 01:14:56.060
and she thought of herself.

01:14:56.060 --> 01:15:00.060
"I wish the creatures wouldn't be so easily offended."

01:15:00.060 --> 01:15:06.060
"You'll get used to it in time," said the caterpillar,

01:15:06.060 --> 01:15:12.060
and it put the hookah into its mouth, and began smoking again.

01:15:12.060 --> 01:15:18.060
This time, Alice waited patiently until it chose to speak again.

01:15:18.060 --> 01:15:23.060
In a minute or two, the caterpillar took the hookah out of its mouth,

01:15:23.060 --> 01:15:28.060
and yawned once or twice, and shook itself.

01:15:28.060 --> 01:15:33.060
Then it got down off the mushroom and crawled away in the grass,

01:15:33.060 --> 01:15:36.060
merely remarking as it went,

01:15:36.060 --> 01:15:39.060
"One side will make you grow taller,

01:15:39.060 --> 01:15:43.060
and the other side will make you grow shorter."

01:15:43.060 --> 01:15:46.060
"One side of what?"

01:15:46.060 --> 01:15:49.060
"The other side of what?"

01:15:49.060 --> 01:15:52.060
thought Alice to herself.

01:15:52.060 --> 01:15:55.060
"Of the mushroom," said the caterpillar,

01:15:55.060 --> 01:15:58.060
just as if she had asked it aloud,

01:15:58.060 --> 01:16:02.060
and in another moment it was out of sight.

01:16:02.060 --> 01:16:07.060
Alice remained, looking thoughtfully at the mushroom for a minute,

01:16:07.060 --> 01:16:11.060
trying to make out which were the two sides of it.

01:16:11.060 --> 01:16:14.060
And as it was perfectly round,

01:16:14.060 --> 01:16:17.060
she found this a very difficult question.

01:16:17.060 --> 01:16:24.060
However, at last she stretched her arms around it as far as they would go,

01:16:24.060 --> 01:16:28.060
and broke off a bit of the edge with each hand.

01:16:28.060 --> 01:16:31.060
"And now who which is which?"

01:16:31.060 --> 01:16:33.060
she said to herself,

01:16:33.060 --> 01:16:37.060
and nibbled a little of the right hand bit to try the effect.

01:16:37.060 --> 01:16:39.060
The next moment,

01:16:39.060 --> 01:16:42.060
she felt a violent blow underneath her chin.

01:16:42.060 --> 01:16:44.060
It had struck her foot.

01:16:44.060 --> 01:16:48.060
She was a good deal frightened by this very sudden change.

01:16:48.060 --> 01:16:52.060
But she felt that there was no time to be lost,

01:16:52.060 --> 01:16:54.060
as she was shrinking rapidly.

01:16:54.060 --> 01:16:59.060
So she sat to work at once to eat some of the other bit.

01:16:59.060 --> 01:17:03.060
Her chin was pressed so closely against her foot,

01:17:03.060 --> 01:17:07.060
that there was hardly room to open her mouth.

01:17:07.060 --> 01:17:09.060
But she did it at last,

01:17:09.060 --> 01:17:13.060
and managed to swallow a morsel of the left hand bit.

01:17:13.060 --> 01:17:18.060
"Come, my head's free at last!"

01:17:18.060 --> 01:17:21.060
said Alice in a tone of delight,

01:17:21.060 --> 01:17:24.060
which changed into alarm in another moment,

01:17:24.060 --> 01:17:29.060
when she found that her shoulders were nowhere to be found.

01:17:29.060 --> 01:17:34.060
All she could see when she looked down was an immense length of neck,

01:17:34.060 --> 01:17:42.060
which seemed to rise like a stalk out of a sea of green leaves that lay far below her.

01:17:42.060 --> 01:17:47.060
"What can all that green stuff be?" said Alice,

01:17:47.060 --> 01:17:50.060
"And where have my shoulders got to?"

01:17:50.060 --> 01:17:56.060
"And oh, my poor hands! How is it I can't see you?"

01:17:56.060 --> 01:17:59.060
She was moving them about as she spoke,

01:17:59.060 --> 01:18:01.060
but no result seemed to follow,

01:18:01.060 --> 01:18:06.060
except a little shaking among the distant green leaves.

01:18:06.060 --> 01:18:12.060
As there seemed to be no chance of getting her hands up to her head,

01:18:12.060 --> 01:18:15.060
she tried to get her head down to them,

01:18:15.060 --> 01:18:21.060
and was delighted to find that her neck would bend about easily in any direction,

01:18:21.060 --> 01:18:23.060
like a serpent.

01:18:23.060 --> 01:18:28.060
She had just succeeded in curving it down into a graceful zigzag,

01:18:28.060 --> 01:18:31.060
and was going to dive in among the leaves,

01:18:31.060 --> 01:18:36.060
which she found to be nothing but the tops of the trees,

01:18:36.060 --> 01:18:39.060
under which she had been wandering.

01:18:39.060 --> 01:18:43.060
When a sharp hiss made her draw back in a hurry,

01:18:43.060 --> 01:18:46.060
a large pigeon had flown into her face,

01:18:46.060 --> 01:18:50.060
and was beating her violently with its wings.

01:18:50.060 --> 01:18:53.060
"Sarpent!" screamed the pigeon.

01:18:53.060 --> 01:18:57.060
"I'm not to serpent," said Alice indignantly.

01:18:57.060 --> 01:18:59.060
"Leave me alone!"

01:18:59.060 --> 01:19:03.060
"Sarpent! I say again!" repeated the pigeon,

01:19:03.060 --> 01:19:06.060
but in a more subdued tone,

01:19:06.060 --> 01:19:08.060
and added with a kind of sob.

01:19:08.060 --> 01:19:13.060
"I've tried every way, and nothing seems to suit them.

01:19:13.060 --> 01:19:19.060
I haven't the least idea what you're talking about," said Alice.

01:19:19.060 --> 01:19:26.060
"I've tried the roots of trees, and I've tried banks, and I've tried hedges."

01:19:26.060 --> 01:19:30.060
The pigeon went on, without attending to her.

01:19:30.060 --> 01:19:34.060
"But those serpents, there's no pleasing them!"

01:19:34.060 --> 01:19:38.060
Alice was more and more puzzled.

01:19:38.060 --> 01:19:42.060
"But she thought there was no use in saying anything more,

01:19:42.060 --> 01:19:44.060
till the pigeon had finished."

01:19:44.060 --> 01:19:50.060
"As if it wasn't trouble enough, hatching the eggs," said the pigeon.

01:19:50.060 --> 01:19:55.060
"But I must be on the lookout for serpents night and day.

01:19:55.060 --> 01:20:01.060
Why, I haven't had a wink of sleep these three weeks."

01:20:01.060 --> 01:20:05.060
"I'm very sorry, you've been annoyed," said Alice.

01:20:05.060 --> 01:20:08.060
"Who was beginning to see its meaning?"

01:20:08.060 --> 01:20:13.060
"And just as I'd taken the highest tree in the wood,"

01:20:13.060 --> 01:20:17.060
continued the pigeon, raising its voice to a shriek.

01:20:17.060 --> 01:20:23.060
"And just as I was thinking, I should be free of them at last.

01:20:23.060 --> 01:20:28.060
They must needs come wriggling down from the sky."

01:20:28.060 --> 01:20:34.060
"Ugh, serpent! But I'm not a serpent, I tell you."

01:20:34.060 --> 01:20:37.060
"Set, Alice. I'm a--I'm a--"

01:20:37.060 --> 01:20:41.060
"Well, what are you?" said the pigeon.

01:20:41.060 --> 01:20:44.060
"I can see you're trying to invent something."

01:20:44.060 --> 01:20:50.060
"I--I'm a little girl," said Alice, rather doubtfully.

01:20:50.060 --> 01:20:55.060
As she remembered the number of changes she had gone through that day.

01:20:55.060 --> 01:21:03.060
"A lightly story indeed," said the pigeon in a tone of the deepest contempt.

01:21:03.060 --> 01:21:12.060
"I've seen a good many little girls in my time, but never one with such a neck as that.

01:21:12.060 --> 01:21:18.060
No, no, you're a serpent, and there's no use to dying it.

01:21:18.060 --> 01:21:23.060
I suppose you'll be telling me next, let you never taste it an egg."

01:21:23.060 --> 01:21:31.060
"I have tasted eggs, certainly," said Alice, who was a very truthful child.

01:21:31.060 --> 01:21:37.060
"But little girls eat eggs quite as much as serpents do, you know.

01:21:37.060 --> 01:21:41.060
I don't believe it," said the pigeon.

01:21:41.060 --> 01:21:46.060
"But if they do, why then they're a kind of serpent?"

01:21:46.060 --> 01:21:49.060
"That's all I can say."

01:21:49.060 --> 01:21:59.060
"This was such a new idea to Alice, that she was quite silent for a minute or two, which gave the pigeon the opportunity of adding."

01:21:59.060 --> 01:22:09.060
"You're looking for eggs, I know that well enough, and what does it matter to me, whether you're a little girl, or a serpent?"

01:22:09.060 --> 01:22:14.060
"It matters a good deal to me," said Alice hastily.

01:22:14.060 --> 01:22:23.060
"But I'm not looking for eggs as it happens, and if I was, I shouldn't want yours, I don't like them raw."

01:22:23.060 --> 01:22:31.060
"Well, be off then," said the pigeon in a sulky tone, as it settled down again into its nest.

01:22:31.060 --> 01:22:39.060
Alice crouched down among the trees as well as she could, for her neck kept getting entangled among the branches.

01:22:39.060 --> 01:22:49.060
And every now and then, she had to stop and untwist it. After a while, she remembered that she still held the pieces of mushroom in her hands.

01:22:49.060 --> 01:22:57.060
And she sat to work very carefully, nibbling first at one, and then the other, and growing sometimes taller.

01:22:57.060 --> 01:23:06.060
And sometimes shorter. Until, she had succeeded in bringing herself down to her usual height.

01:23:06.060 --> 01:23:14.060
It was so long, since she had been anything near the right size, that it felt quite strange at first.

01:23:14.060 --> 01:23:21.060
But she got used to it in a few minutes, and began talking to herself, as usual.

01:23:21.060 --> 01:23:31.060
"Come, there's half my plan done now. How puzzling all these changes are. I'm never sure what I'm going to be. From one minute to another."

01:23:31.060 --> 01:23:40.060
"However, I've got back to my right size. The next thing is to get into that beautiful garden."

01:23:40.060 --> 01:23:43.060
"How is that to be done?" I wonder.

01:23:43.060 --> 01:23:54.060
"As she said this, she came suddenly upon an open place. With a little house in it, about four feet high. Whoever lives there."

01:23:54.060 --> 01:24:03.060
"Thought Alice. It'll never do to come upon them this size. Why, I should frighten them out of their wits."

01:24:03.060 --> 01:24:15.060
So she began nibbling at the right hand bit again. And did not venture to go near the house. Till she had brought herself down to nine inches high.

01:24:15.060 --> 01:24:24.060
"And of Chapter 5."

01:24:24.060 --> 01:24:29.060
Chapter 6 of Alice's Adventures in Wonderland by Lewis Carroll.

01:24:29.060 --> 01:24:34.060
This liberal box recording is in the public domain.

01:24:34.060 --> 01:24:38.060
Chapter 6, Pig and Pepper.

01:24:38.060 --> 01:24:45.060
For a minute or two, she stood looking at the house, and wondering what to do next.

01:24:45.060 --> 01:24:55.060
When suddenly a footman in library came running out of the wood, she considered him to be a footman because he was in library.

01:24:55.060 --> 01:25:05.060
Otherwise, judging by his face only, she would have called him a fish, and wrapped loudly at the door with his knuckles.

01:25:05.060 --> 01:25:13.060
It was opened by another footman in library, with a round face, and large eyes like a frog.

01:25:13.060 --> 01:25:21.060
And both footmen, Alice noticed, had powdered hair that curled all over their heads.

01:25:21.060 --> 01:25:30.060
She felt very curious to know what it was all about, and crept a little way out of the wood to listen.

01:25:30.060 --> 01:25:38.060
The fish footman began by producing from under his arm a great letter, nearly as large as himself.

01:25:38.060 --> 01:25:50.060
And this he handed over to the other, saying in a solemn tone, "For the Duchess, an invitation from the Queen to play croquet."

01:25:50.060 --> 01:25:56.060
The frog footman repeated, "In the same solemn tone, only changing the order of the words a little."

01:25:56.060 --> 01:26:01.060
From the Queen, an invitation for the Duchess to play croquet.

01:26:01.060 --> 01:26:07.060
Then they both bowed low, and their curls got entangled together.

01:26:07.060 --> 01:26:21.060
Alice laughed so much at this, that she had to run back into the wood for fear of their hearing her, and when she next peeped out the fish footman was gone.

01:26:21.060 --> 01:26:28.060
And the other was sitting on the ground near the door, staring stupidly up into the sky.

01:26:28.060 --> 01:26:32.060
Alice went timidly up to the door, and knocked.

01:26:32.060 --> 01:26:39.060
"There's no sort of use in knocking," said the footman, "and that, for two reasons.

01:26:39.060 --> 01:26:44.060
First, because I'm on the same side of the door as you are.

01:26:44.060 --> 01:26:51.060
Secondly, because they're making such a noise inside, no one could possibly hear you.

01:26:51.060 --> 01:27:08.060
And certainly there was a most extraordinary noise going on within, a constant howling and sneezing, and every now and then a great crash, as if a dish or kettle had been broken to pieces."

01:27:08.060 --> 01:27:11.060
"Please, then," said Alice.

01:27:11.060 --> 01:27:14.060
"How am I to get in?"

01:27:14.060 --> 01:27:16.060
"There might be some sense in your knocking.

01:27:16.060 --> 01:27:22.060
The footman went on without attending to her, if we had the door between us.

01:27:22.060 --> 01:27:30.060
For instance, if you were inside, you might knock, and I could let you out, you know."

01:27:30.060 --> 01:27:39.060
He was looking up into the sky all the time he was speaking, and this Alice thought decidedly uncivil.

01:27:39.060 --> 01:27:44.060
"But perhaps he can't help it," she said to herself.

01:27:44.060 --> 01:27:49.060
"His eyes are so very nearly at the top of his head.

01:27:49.060 --> 01:27:52.060
But at any rate he might answer questions.

01:27:52.060 --> 01:27:56.060
"How am I to get in?" she repeated aloud.

01:27:56.060 --> 01:28:00.060
"I shall sit here," the footman remarked.

01:28:00.060 --> 01:28:02.060
Till tomorrow.

01:28:02.060 --> 01:28:11.060
At this moment the door of the house opened, and a large plate came skimming out, straight at the footman's head.

01:28:11.060 --> 01:28:18.060
It just grazed his nose, and broke to pieces against one of the trees behind him.

01:28:18.060 --> 01:28:21.060
Or next day, maybe."

01:28:21.060 --> 01:28:28.060
The footman continued in the same tone, exactly as if nothing had happened.

01:28:28.060 --> 01:28:30.060
"How am I to get in?"

01:28:30.060 --> 01:28:34.060
asked Alice again, in a louder tone.

01:28:34.060 --> 01:28:38.060
"Are you to get in that all?" said the footman.

01:28:38.060 --> 01:28:41.060
"That's the first question, you know."

01:28:41.060 --> 01:28:47.060
It was, no doubt, only Alice did not like to be told so.

01:28:47.060 --> 01:28:51.060
"It's really dreadful," she muttered to herself.

01:28:51.060 --> 01:28:56.060
"The way all the creatures argue, it's enough to drive one crazy."

01:28:56.060 --> 01:29:04.060
The footman seemed to think this a good opportunity for repeating his remark, with variations.

01:29:04.060 --> 01:29:11.060
"I shall sit here," he said, on and off, for days and days.

01:29:11.060 --> 01:29:15.060
"But what am I to do?" said Alice.

01:29:15.060 --> 01:29:20.060
"Anything you like," said the footman, and began whistling.

01:29:20.060 --> 01:29:26.060
"Oh, there is no use in talking to him," said Alice, desperately.

01:29:26.060 --> 01:29:32.060
"He's perfectly idiotic," and she opened the door and went in.

01:29:32.060 --> 01:29:39.060
The door led right into a large kitchen, which was full of smoke from one end to the other.

01:29:39.060 --> 01:29:44.060
The Duchess was sitting on a three-legged stool in the middle, nursing a baby.

01:29:44.060 --> 01:29:52.060
The cook was leaning over the fire, stirring a large cauldron, which seemed to be full of soup.

01:29:52.060 --> 01:30:00.060
"There's certainly too much pepper in that soup," Alice said to herself, as well as she could for sneezing.

01:30:00.060 --> 01:30:08.060
There was certainly too much of it in the air, even the Duchess sneezed occasionally, and as for the baby.

01:30:08.060 --> 01:30:14.060
It was sneezing and howling alternately, without a moment's pause.

01:30:14.060 --> 01:30:25.060
The only things in the kitchen that did not sneeze were the cook, and a large cat which was sitting on the hearth and grinning from ear to ear.

01:30:25.060 --> 01:30:37.060
"Please, would you tell me," said Alice, a little timidly, for she was not quite sure whether it was good manners for her to speak first.

01:30:37.060 --> 01:30:40.060
"Why, your cat grins like that?"

01:30:40.060 --> 01:30:44.060
"It's a Cheshire cat," said the Duchess.

01:30:44.060 --> 01:30:46.060
"And that's why."

01:30:46.060 --> 01:30:48.060
"Pig!"

01:30:48.060 --> 01:31:00.060
She said the last word with such sun violence that Alice quite jumped, but she saw in another moment that it was addressed to the baby, and not to her.

01:31:00.060 --> 01:31:03.060
So she took courage and went on again.

01:31:03.060 --> 01:31:12.060
"I didn't know that Cheshire cats always grinned. In fact, I didn't know that cats could grin."

01:31:12.060 --> 01:31:18.060
"They all can," said the Duchess, and most of them do.

01:31:18.060 --> 01:31:27.060
"I don't know of any that do," Alice said very politely, feeling quite pleased to have gone into a conversation.

01:31:27.060 --> 01:31:33.060
"You don't know much," said the Duchess. "And that's a fact."

01:31:33.060 --> 01:31:45.060
Alice did not at all like the tone of this remark, and thought it would be as well to introduce some other subject of conversation.

01:31:45.060 --> 01:31:56.060
While she was trying to fix on one, the cook took the cauldron of soup off the fire, and at once set to work, throwing everything within her reach,

01:31:56.060 --> 01:32:07.060
at the Duchess, and the baby. The fire irons came first, then followed a shower of saucepans, plates, and dishes.

01:32:07.060 --> 01:32:21.060
The Duchess took no notice of them even when they hit her, and the baby was howling so much already, that it was quite impossible to say, whether the blows heard it, or not.

01:32:21.060 --> 01:32:24.060
"Oh, please, mind what you're doing?"

01:32:24.060 --> 01:32:29.060
cried Alice, jumping up and down in an agony of terror.

01:32:29.060 --> 01:32:33.060
"Oh, there goes his precious nose."

01:32:33.060 --> 01:32:40.060
As an unusually large saucepan flew close by it, and very nearly carried it off.

01:32:40.060 --> 01:32:47.060
"If everybody minded their own business," the Duchess said in a horse growl.

01:32:47.060 --> 01:32:52.060
"The world would go round a deal faster than it does."

01:32:52.060 --> 01:33:03.060
"Which would not be an advantage," said Alice, who felt very glad to get an opportunity of showing off a little of her knowledge.

01:33:03.060 --> 01:33:08.060
"Just think of what work it would make with the day and night."

01:33:08.060 --> 01:33:22.060
"You see, the earth takes twenty-four hours to turn round on its axis. Talking of axes," said the Duchess. "Chop off her head."

01:33:22.060 --> 01:33:35.060
Alice glanced rather anxiously at the cook to see if she meant to take the hint, but the cook was busily stirring the soup, and seemed not to be listening, so she went on again.

01:33:35.060 --> 01:33:40.060
"24 hours, I think, or is it twelve?"

01:33:40.060 --> 01:33:44.060
"Oh, don't bother me," said the Duchess.

01:33:44.060 --> 01:33:47.060
"I could never abide figures."

01:33:47.060 --> 01:33:59.060
And with that, she began nursing her child again, singing a sort of lullaby to it as she did so, and giving it a violent shake at the end of every line.

01:33:59.060 --> 01:34:10.060
"Speak roughly to your little boy, and beat him when he sneezes. He only does it to annoy, because he knows it teases."

01:34:10.060 --> 01:34:15.060
"Course, in which the cook and the baby joined."

01:34:15.060 --> 01:34:18.060
"Wow, wow, wow!"

01:34:18.060 --> 01:34:28.060
While the Duchess sang the second verse of the song, she kept tossing the baby violently up and down, and the poor little thing howled so.

01:34:28.060 --> 01:34:31.060
That Alice could hardly hear the words.

01:34:31.060 --> 01:34:36.060
"I speak severely to my boy," I beat him when he sneezes.

01:34:36.060 --> 01:34:41.060
"For he can thoroughly enjoy the pepper when he pleases."

01:34:41.060 --> 01:34:45.060
"Course, wow, wow, wow!"

01:34:45.060 --> 01:34:54.060
"Here, you may nurse it a bit if you like," the Duchess said to Alice, flinging the baby at her as she spoke.

01:34:54.060 --> 01:35:01.060
"I must go and get ready to play croquet with the queen," and she hurried out of the room.

01:35:01.060 --> 01:35:07.060
The cook threw a frying pan after her as she went out, but it just missed her.

01:35:07.060 --> 01:35:18.060
Alice caught the baby with some difficulty, as it was a queer shaped little creature, and held out its arms and lakes in all directions.

01:35:18.060 --> 01:35:24.060
"Just like a starfish," thought Alice.

01:35:24.060 --> 01:35:40.060
The poor little thing was snorting like a steam engine when she caught it, and kept doubling itself up and straightening itself out again, so that altogether for the first minute or two, it was as much as she could do to hold it.

01:35:40.060 --> 01:35:59.060
As soon as she had made out the proper way of nursing it, which was to twist it up into a sort of knot, and then keep tight, hold of its right ear and left foot, so as to prevent its undoing itself, she carried it out into the open air.

01:35:59.060 --> 01:36:04.060
"If I don't take this child away with me," thought Alice.

01:36:04.060 --> 01:36:10.060
"They're sure to kill it in a day or two. Wouldn't it be murder to leave it behind?"

01:36:10.060 --> 01:36:16.060
She said the last words out loud, and the little thing grunted in reply.

01:36:16.060 --> 01:36:20.060
"It had left off sneezing by this time."

01:36:20.060 --> 01:36:23.060
"Don't grunt," said Alice.

01:36:23.060 --> 01:36:28.060
"That's not at all a proper way of expressing yourself."

01:36:28.060 --> 01:36:36.060
The baby grunted again, and Alice looked very anxiously into its face to see what was the matter with it.

01:36:36.060 --> 01:36:45.060
There could be no doubt that it had a very turn-up nose, much more like a snout than a real nose.

01:36:45.060 --> 01:36:50.060
Also, its eyes were getting extremely small for a baby.

01:36:50.060 --> 01:36:55.060
Altogether, Alice did not like the look of the thing at all.

01:36:55.060 --> 01:37:04.060
"But perhaps it was only sobbing," she thought, and looked into its eyes again to see if there were any tears.

01:37:04.060 --> 01:37:08.060
"No. There were no tears."

01:37:08.060 --> 01:37:14.060
"If you're going to turn into a pig, my dear," said Alice, seriously.

01:37:14.060 --> 01:37:18.060
"I'll have nothing more to do with you. Mind now?"

01:37:18.060 --> 01:37:25.060
The poor little thing sobbed again. Or grunted, it was impossible to say which.

01:37:25.060 --> 01:37:29.060
And they went on for some while in silence.

01:37:29.060 --> 01:37:32.060
Alice was just beginning to think to herself.

01:37:32.060 --> 01:37:37.060
"No. What am I to do with this creature when I get it home?"

01:37:37.060 --> 01:37:44.060
When it grunted again, so violently, that she looked down into its face in some alarm.

01:37:44.060 --> 01:37:52.060
"This time there could be no mistake about it. It was neither more nor less than a pig."

01:37:52.060 --> 01:37:57.060
And she felt that it would be quite absurd for her to carry it further.

01:37:57.060 --> 01:38:05.060
So, she sat the little creature down, and felt quite relieved to see it trot away quietly into the wood.

01:38:05.060 --> 01:38:09.060
"If it had grown up," she said to herself.

01:38:09.060 --> 01:38:13.060
"It would have made a dreadfully ugly child."

01:38:13.060 --> 01:38:18.060
"But it makes rather a handsome pig, I think."

01:38:18.060 --> 01:38:25.060
And she began thinking over other children she knew, who might do very well as pigs.

01:38:25.060 --> 01:38:32.060
And it was just saying to herself, "If one only knew the right way to change them."

01:38:32.060 --> 01:38:41.060
When she was a little startled by seeing the Cheshire cat sitting on a bow of a tree, a few yards off,

01:38:41.060 --> 01:38:45.060
the cat only grinned when it saw Alice.

01:38:45.060 --> 01:38:48.060
It looked good-natured, she thought.

01:38:48.060 --> 01:38:54.060
Still, it had very long claws, and a great many teeth.

01:38:54.060 --> 01:38:58.060
So she felt that it ought to be treated with respect.

01:38:58.060 --> 01:39:00.060
"Chesshire pus!"

01:39:00.060 --> 01:39:06.060
She began, rather timidly, as she did not at all know whether it would like the name.

01:39:06.060 --> 01:39:10.060
However, it only grinned a little wider.

01:39:10.060 --> 01:39:16.060
"Come, it's pleased so far," thought Alice, and she went on.

01:39:16.060 --> 01:39:21.060
"Would you tell me, please, which way I ought to go from here?"

01:39:21.060 --> 01:39:27.060
"That depends a good deal on where you want to get to," said the cat.

01:39:27.060 --> 01:39:30.060
"I don't much care where," said Alice.

01:39:30.060 --> 01:39:35.060
"Then it doesn't matter which way you go," said the cat.

01:39:35.060 --> 01:39:41.060
"So long as I get somewhere," Alice added as an explanation.

01:39:41.060 --> 01:39:48.060
"Oh, you're sure to do that," said the cat, "if you only walk long enough."

01:39:48.060 --> 01:39:52.060
Alice felt that this could not be denied.

01:39:52.060 --> 01:39:55.060
So she tried another question.

01:39:55.060 --> 01:39:58.060
"What sort of people live about here?"

01:39:58.060 --> 01:40:05.060
"In that direction," the cat said, waving its right paw around,

01:40:05.060 --> 01:40:10.060
"Lives a hatter," and in that direction, waving the other paw,

01:40:10.060 --> 01:40:12.060
"Lives a march hair.

01:40:12.060 --> 01:40:14.060
Visit either you like.

01:40:14.060 --> 01:40:16.060
They're both mad."

01:40:16.060 --> 01:40:21.060
"But I don't want to go among mad people," Alice remarked.

01:40:21.060 --> 01:40:26.060
"Oh, you can't help that," said the cat.

01:40:26.060 --> 01:40:29.060
"We're all mad here.

01:40:29.060 --> 01:40:30.060
I'm mad.

01:40:30.060 --> 01:40:32.060
You're mad."

01:40:32.060 --> 01:40:36.060
"How do you know I'm mad?" said Alice.

01:40:36.060 --> 01:40:39.060
"You must be," said the cat.

01:40:39.060 --> 01:40:42.060
"Or you wouldn't have come here."

01:40:42.060 --> 01:40:46.060
Alice didn't think that proved it at all.

01:40:46.060 --> 01:40:48.060
However, she went on.

01:40:48.060 --> 01:40:52.060
"And how do you know that you're mad?"

01:40:52.060 --> 01:40:56.060
"To begin with," said the cat.

01:40:56.060 --> 01:40:57.060
"A dog's not mad.

01:40:57.060 --> 01:40:59.060
You grant that?"

01:40:59.060 --> 01:41:02.060
"I suppose so," said Alice.

01:41:02.060 --> 01:41:05.060
"Well, then," the cat went on.

01:41:05.060 --> 01:41:09.060
"You see, a dog growls when it's angry,

01:41:09.060 --> 01:41:12.060
and wags its tail when it's pleased.

01:41:12.060 --> 01:41:16.060
Now I growl when I'm pleased,

01:41:16.060 --> 01:41:20.060
and wag my tail when I'm angry.

01:41:20.060 --> 01:41:23.060
Therefore, I'm mad."

01:41:23.060 --> 01:41:28.060
"I call it purring, not growling," said Alice.

01:41:28.060 --> 01:41:32.060
"Call it what do you like," said the cat.

01:41:32.060 --> 01:41:37.060
"Do you play croquet with the queen today?"

01:41:37.060 --> 01:41:41.060
"I should like it very much," said Alice.

01:41:41.060 --> 01:41:44.060
"But I haven't been invited yet."

01:41:44.060 --> 01:41:49.060
"You'll see me there," said the cat, and vanished.

01:41:49.060 --> 01:41:52.060
Alice was not much surprised at this.

01:41:52.060 --> 01:41:56.060
She was getting so used to queer things happening.

01:41:56.060 --> 01:42:00.060
While she was looking at the place where it had been,

01:42:00.060 --> 01:42:02.060
it suddenly appeared again.

01:42:02.060 --> 01:42:04.060
"By the by."

01:42:04.060 --> 01:42:08.060
"What became of the baby?" said the cat.

01:42:08.060 --> 01:42:11.060
"I'd nearly forgotten to ask."

01:42:11.060 --> 01:42:16.060
"It turned into a pig," Alice quietly said.

01:42:16.060 --> 01:42:20.060
"Just as if it had come back in a natural way.

01:42:20.060 --> 01:42:24.060
I thought it would," said the cat,

01:42:24.060 --> 01:42:26.060
and vanished again.

01:42:26.060 --> 01:42:30.060
Alice waited a little, half expecting to see it again.

01:42:30.060 --> 01:42:35.060
But it did not appear, and after a minute or two,

01:42:35.060 --> 01:42:40.060
she walked on in the direction in which the March hair was said to live.

01:42:40.060 --> 01:42:45.060
"I've seen hatters before," she said to herself.

01:42:45.060 --> 01:42:48.060
"The March hair will be much the most interesting.

01:42:48.060 --> 01:42:53.060
And perhaps as this is May, it won't be raving mad."

01:42:53.060 --> 01:42:57.060
"At least not so mad as it was in March."

01:42:57.060 --> 01:43:02.060
As she said this, she looked up, and there was the cat again,

01:43:02.060 --> 01:43:05.060
sitting on a branch of a tree.

01:43:05.060 --> 01:43:07.060
"Did you say pig?"

01:43:07.060 --> 01:43:11.060
"Or fig," said the cat.

01:43:11.060 --> 01:43:14.060
"I said pig," replied Alice.

01:43:14.060 --> 01:43:19.060
"And I wish you wouldn't keep appearing and vanishing so suddenly.

01:43:19.060 --> 01:43:22.060
You make one quite giddy."

01:43:22.060 --> 01:43:25.060
"All right," said the cat.

01:43:25.060 --> 01:43:28.060
And at this time, it vanished quite slowly,

01:43:28.060 --> 01:43:31.060
beginning with the end of the tail,

01:43:31.060 --> 01:43:33.060
and ending with the grin,

01:43:33.060 --> 01:43:38.060
which remained some time after the rest of it had gone.

01:43:38.060 --> 01:43:43.060
"Well, I've often seen a cat without a grin," thought Alice.

01:43:43.060 --> 01:43:46.060
"But a grin without a cat.

01:43:46.060 --> 01:43:52.060
It's the most curious thing I ever saw in my life."

01:43:52.060 --> 01:43:55.060
She had not gone much farther,

01:43:55.060 --> 01:44:00.060
before she came in sight of the house of the March hair.

01:44:00.060 --> 01:44:03.060
She thought it must be the right house,

01:44:03.060 --> 01:44:06.060
because the chimneys were shaped like ears,

01:44:06.060 --> 01:44:10.060
and the roof was stashed with fur.

01:44:10.060 --> 01:44:13.060
It was so large a house,

01:44:13.060 --> 01:44:16.060
that she did not like to go nearer,

01:44:16.060 --> 01:44:21.060
till she had nibbled some more of the left-hand bit of mushroom,

01:44:21.060 --> 01:44:25.060
and raised herself to about two feet high,

01:44:25.060 --> 01:44:29.060
even then she walked up towards it rather timidly,

01:44:29.060 --> 01:44:31.060
saying to herself,

01:44:31.060 --> 01:44:35.060
"Suppose it should be raving mad after all.

01:44:35.060 --> 01:44:38.060
I almost wish I'd gone to see the hatter instead."

01:44:38.060 --> 01:44:48.060
End of Chapter 6

01:44:48.060 --> 01:44:53.060
Chapter 7 of Alice's Adventures in Wonderland,

01:44:53.060 --> 01:44:55.060
by Lewis Carroll.

01:44:55.060 --> 01:45:00.060
This liberal Vox recording is in the public domain.

01:45:00.060 --> 01:45:04.060
Chapter 7, a mad tea party.

01:45:04.060 --> 01:45:09.060
There was a table set out under a tree in front of the house,

01:45:09.060 --> 01:45:14.060
and the March hair and the hatter were having tea at it.

01:45:14.060 --> 01:45:18.060
A doormouse was sitting between them,

01:45:18.060 --> 01:45:20.060
fast asleep,

01:45:20.060 --> 01:45:23.060
and the other two were using it as a cushion,

01:45:23.060 --> 01:45:26.060
resting their elbows on it,

01:45:26.060 --> 01:45:28.060
and talking over its head.

01:45:28.060 --> 01:45:31.060
"Very uncomfortable for the doormouse!"

01:45:31.060 --> 01:45:35.060
thought Alice, "Only, as it's asleep.

01:45:35.060 --> 01:45:38.060
I suppose it doesn't mind."

01:45:38.060 --> 01:45:40.060
The table was a large one,

01:45:40.060 --> 01:45:44.060
but the three were all crowded together at one corner of it.

01:45:44.060 --> 01:45:49.060
"No room, no room!" they cried out when they saw Alice coming.

01:45:49.060 --> 01:45:54.060
"There's plenty of room!" said Alice indignantly,

01:45:54.060 --> 01:45:59.060
and she sat down in a large armchair at one end of the table.

01:45:59.060 --> 01:46:03.060
"Have some wine," the March hair said,

01:46:03.060 --> 01:46:05.060
in an encouraging tone.

01:46:05.060 --> 01:46:07.060
Alice looked all round the table,

01:46:07.060 --> 01:46:10.060
but there was nothing on it, but tea.

01:46:10.060 --> 01:46:13.060
"I don't see any wine," she remarked.

01:46:13.060 --> 01:46:17.060
"There isn't any," said the March hair.

01:46:17.060 --> 01:46:22.060
"Then it wasn't very civil of you to offer it," said Alice angrily.

01:46:22.060 --> 01:46:27.060
"It wasn't very civil of you to sit down without being invited,"

01:46:27.060 --> 01:46:29.060
said the March hair.

01:46:29.060 --> 01:46:34.060
"I didn't know it was your table," said Alice.

01:46:34.060 --> 01:46:38.060
"It's laid for a great many more than three."

01:46:38.060 --> 01:46:42.060
"Your hair once cutting," said the Hatter.

01:46:42.060 --> 01:46:45.060
He had been looking at Alice for some time,

01:46:45.060 --> 01:46:47.060
with great curiosity.

01:46:47.060 --> 01:46:50.060
And this was his first speech.

01:46:50.060 --> 01:46:55.060
"You should learn not to make personal remarks," Alice said,

01:46:55.060 --> 01:46:58.060
with some severity.

01:46:58.060 --> 01:47:00.060
"It's very rude."

01:47:00.060 --> 01:47:04.060
The Hatter opened his eyes very wide on hearing this,

01:47:04.060 --> 01:47:07.060
but all he said was,

01:47:07.060 --> 01:47:11.060
"Why is a raven, like a writing desk?"

01:47:11.060 --> 01:47:14.060
"Come, we shall have some fun now!"

01:47:14.060 --> 01:47:16.060
thought Alice.

01:47:16.060 --> 01:47:19.060
"I'm glad they've begun asking riddles.

01:47:19.060 --> 01:47:22.060
I believe I can guess that."

01:47:22.060 --> 01:47:25.060
She added aloud.

01:47:25.060 --> 01:47:28.060
"Do you mean that you think you can find out the answer to it?"

01:47:28.060 --> 01:47:30.060
said the March hair.

01:47:30.060 --> 01:47:33.060
"Exactly so," said Alice.

01:47:33.060 --> 01:47:38.060
"Then you should say what you mean," the March hair went on.

01:47:38.060 --> 01:47:42.060
"I do," Alice hastily replied.

01:47:42.060 --> 01:47:45.060
"At least, at least I mean what I say."

01:47:45.060 --> 01:47:48.060
"That's the same thing, you know."

01:47:48.060 --> 01:47:53.060
"Not the same thing a bit," said the Hatter.

01:47:53.060 --> 01:47:56.060
"You might just as well say that.

01:47:56.060 --> 01:47:59.060
I see what I eat.

01:47:59.060 --> 01:48:04.060
Is the same thing as I eat, what I see."

01:48:04.060 --> 01:48:09.060
"You might just as well say," added the March hair.

01:48:09.060 --> 01:48:16.060
"That I like, what I get, is the same thing as I get,

01:48:16.060 --> 01:48:18.060
what I like.

01:48:18.060 --> 01:48:21.060
You might just as well say."

01:48:21.060 --> 01:48:26.060
added the Dormouse, who seemed to be talking in his sleep.

01:48:26.060 --> 01:48:29.060
"That I breathe when I sleep.

01:48:29.060 --> 01:48:33.060
Is the same thing as I sleep when I breathe."

01:48:33.060 --> 01:48:38.060
"It is the same thing with you," said the Hatter.

01:48:38.060 --> 01:48:46.060
"And here the conversation dropped, and the party sat silent for a minute.

01:48:46.060 --> 01:48:52.060
While Alice thought over all she could remember about Ravens and writing desks.

01:48:52.060 --> 01:48:54.060
Which wasn't much.

01:48:54.060 --> 01:48:58.060
The Hatter was the first to break the silence.

01:48:58.060 --> 01:49:04.060
"What day of the month is it?" he said, turning to Alice.

01:49:04.060 --> 01:49:10.060
He had taken his watch out of his pocket, and was looking at it uneasily,

01:49:10.060 --> 01:49:15.060
shaking it every now and then, and holding it to his ear.

01:49:15.060 --> 01:49:20.060
Alice considered a little, and then said, "The fourth!

01:49:20.060 --> 01:49:23.060
Two days wrong!"

01:49:23.060 --> 01:49:25.060
sighed the Hatter.

01:49:25.060 --> 01:49:29.060
"I told you butter wouldn't suit the works."

01:49:29.060 --> 01:49:34.060
He added, looking angrily at the March hair.

01:49:34.060 --> 01:49:39.060
"It was the best butter," the March hair, meekly replied.

01:49:39.060 --> 01:49:45.060
"Yes, but some crumbs must have gotten as well," the Hatter grumbled.

01:49:45.060 --> 01:49:49.060
"You shouldn't have put it in with the bread knife."

01:49:49.060 --> 01:49:53.060
The March hair took the watch, and looked at it gloomily.

01:49:53.060 --> 01:49:58.060
Then he dipped it into his cup of tea, and looked at it again.

01:49:58.060 --> 01:50:03.060
But he could think of nothing better to say than his first remark.

01:50:03.060 --> 01:50:07.060
"It was the best butter," you know.

01:50:07.060 --> 01:50:12.060
Alice had been looking over his shoulder, with some curiosity.

01:50:12.060 --> 01:50:15.060
"What a funny watch!"

01:50:15.060 --> 01:50:16.060
She remarked.

01:50:16.060 --> 01:50:22.060
"It tells the day of the month, and doesn't tell what o'clock it is."

01:50:22.060 --> 01:50:25.060
"Why, should it?" muttered the Hatter.

01:50:25.060 --> 01:50:30.060
"Does your watch tell you what year it is?"

01:50:30.060 --> 01:50:35.060
"Of course not," Alice replied very readily.

01:50:35.060 --> 01:50:41.060
"But that's because it stays the same year for such a long time together."

01:50:41.060 --> 01:50:46.060
"Which is just the case with mine," said the Hatter.

01:50:46.060 --> 01:50:49.060
Alice felt dreadfully puzzled.

01:50:49.060 --> 01:50:56.060
"The Hatter's remark seemed to have no sort of meaning in it, and yet it was certainly English.

01:50:56.060 --> 01:51:03.060
"I don't quite understand you," she said, as politely as she could.

01:51:03.060 --> 01:51:12.060
"The door-mouse is asleep again," said the Hatter, and he poured a little hot tea upon its nose.

01:51:12.060 --> 01:51:19.060
"The door-mouse shook its head impatiently, and said, without opening its eyes.

01:51:19.060 --> 01:51:25.060
"Of course, of course, just what I was going to remark myself."

01:51:25.060 --> 01:51:28.060
"Have you guessed the riddle yet?"

01:51:28.060 --> 01:51:32.060
The Hatter said, turning to Alice again.

01:51:32.060 --> 01:51:35.060
"No, I give it up," Alice replied.

01:51:35.060 --> 01:51:37.060
"What's the answer?"

01:51:37.060 --> 01:51:42.060
"I, haven't the slightest idea," said the Hatter.

01:51:42.060 --> 01:51:46.060
"Nor I," said the March Hare.

01:51:46.060 --> 01:51:48.060
"Alice sighed, weirdly."

01:51:48.060 --> 01:51:56.060
"I think you might do something better with the time," she said, then wasted in asking

01:51:56.060 --> 01:51:58.060
riddles that have no answers.

01:51:58.060 --> 01:52:03.060
"If you knew time, as well as I do," said the Hatter.

01:52:03.060 --> 01:52:06.060
"You wouldn't talk about wasting it.

01:52:06.060 --> 01:52:08.060
It's him."

01:52:08.060 --> 01:52:13.060
"I don't know what you mean," said Alice.

01:52:13.060 --> 01:52:19.060
"Of course you don't," the Hatter said, tossing his head contemptuously.

01:52:19.060 --> 01:52:24.060
"I dare say you never even spoke to time."

01:52:24.060 --> 01:52:28.060
"Perhaps not," Alice cautiously replied.

01:52:28.060 --> 01:52:32.060
"But I know I have to beat time when I learn music."

01:52:32.060 --> 01:52:36.060
"Ah, that accounts for it," said the Hatter.

01:52:36.060 --> 01:52:39.060
"He won't stand beating.

01:52:39.060 --> 01:52:47.060
Now, if you only kept on good terms with him, he'd do almost anything you liked with the clock.

01:52:47.060 --> 01:52:54.060
For instance, suppose it were nine o'clock in the morning, just time to begin lessons.

01:52:54.060 --> 01:53:00.060
You'd only have to whisper a hint to time and round the clock goes in a twinkling.

01:53:00.060 --> 01:53:03.060
Half past one, time for dinner.

01:53:03.060 --> 01:53:09.060
"I only wish it was," the march here said to itself in the whisper.

01:53:09.060 --> 01:53:15.060
"That would be grand, certainly," said Alice thoughtfully.

01:53:15.060 --> 01:53:19.060
"But then I shouldn't be hungry for it, you know."

01:53:19.060 --> 01:53:23.060
"Not at first, perhaps," said the Hatter.

01:53:23.060 --> 01:53:29.060
"But you could keep it to half past one as long as you liked."

01:53:29.060 --> 01:53:33.060
"Is that the way you managed?"

01:53:33.060 --> 01:53:34.060
Alice asked.

01:53:34.060 --> 01:53:37.060
"The Hatter shook his head mournfully."

01:53:37.060 --> 01:53:40.060
"Not I," he replied.

01:53:40.060 --> 01:53:43.060
"We quarreled last March."

01:53:43.060 --> 01:53:47.060
"Just before he went mad, you know."

01:53:47.060 --> 01:53:51.060
Pointing with his teaspoon at the march here.

01:53:51.060 --> 01:53:58.060
"It was at the great concert given by the Queen of Hearts, and I had to sing."

01:53:58.060 --> 01:54:01.060
"Twinkle, twinkle, little bat.

01:54:01.060 --> 01:54:04.060
How I wonder what you're at."

01:54:04.060 --> 01:54:06.060
"You know the song?"

01:54:06.060 --> 01:54:07.060
"Perhaps."

01:54:07.060 --> 01:54:11.060
"I've heard something like it," said Alice.

01:54:11.060 --> 01:54:15.060
"It goes on, you know," the Hatter continued.

01:54:15.060 --> 01:54:23.060
"In this way, up above the world you fly, like a tea tray in the sky.

01:54:23.060 --> 01:54:25.060
Twinkle, twinkle.

01:54:25.060 --> 01:54:29.060
The door mouse shook itself, and began singing in its sleep."

01:54:29.060 --> 01:54:33.060
"Twinkle, twinkle, twinkle."

01:54:33.060 --> 01:54:38.060
"And went on so long that they had to pinch it to make it stop."

01:54:38.060 --> 01:54:43.060
"Well, I'd hardly finished the first verse," said the Hatter.

01:54:43.060 --> 01:54:49.060
"When the Queen jumped up and balled out, he's murdering the time off with his head."

01:54:49.060 --> 01:54:52.060
"How dreadfully savage?"

01:54:52.060 --> 01:54:54.060
exclaimed Alice.

01:54:54.060 --> 01:55:00.060
"And ever since that," the Hatter went on in a mournful tone.

01:55:00.060 --> 01:55:02.060
"He won't do a thing I ask.

01:55:02.060 --> 01:55:05.060
It's always six o'clock now."

01:55:05.060 --> 01:55:09.060
A bright idea, King, into Alice's head.

01:55:09.060 --> 01:55:13.060
"Is that the reason so many tea things are put out here?"

01:55:13.060 --> 01:55:14.060
"She asked."

01:55:14.060 --> 01:55:19.060
"Yes, that's it," said the Hatter with a sigh.

01:55:19.060 --> 01:55:26.060
"It's always tea time, and we've no time to wash the things between

01:55:26.060 --> 01:55:27.060
wiles."

01:55:27.060 --> 01:55:31.060
"Then you keep moving round, I suppose?"

01:55:31.060 --> 01:55:32.060
said Alice.

01:55:32.060 --> 01:55:39.060
"Exactly, so," said the Hatter, as the things get used up.

01:55:39.060 --> 01:55:43.060
"But what happens when you come to the beginning again?"

01:55:43.060 --> 01:55:50.060
Alice ventured to ask.

01:55:50.060 --> 01:55:55.060
"I'm getting tired of this.

01:55:55.060 --> 01:55:59.060
I vote the young lady tells us a story."

01:55:59.060 --> 01:56:03.060
"I'm afraid I don't know one," said Alice.

01:56:03.060 --> 01:56:06.060
Rather alarmed at the proposal.

01:56:06.060 --> 01:56:10.060
"Then the doormouse shall," they both cried.

01:56:10.060 --> 01:56:12.060
"Wake up, doormouse."

01:56:12.060 --> 01:56:16.060
"And they pinched it on both sides at once."

01:56:16.060 --> 01:56:21.060
"The doormouse," slowly opened his eyes.

01:56:21.060 --> 01:56:26.060
"I wasn't asleep," he said in a horse, feeble voice.

01:56:26.060 --> 01:56:30.060
"I heard every word you fellows were saying."

01:56:30.060 --> 01:56:34.060
"Tell us a story," said the March Hare.

01:56:34.060 --> 01:56:38.060
"Yes, please do," pleaded Alice.

01:56:38.060 --> 01:56:42.060
"And be quick about it," added the Hatter.

01:56:42.060 --> 01:56:45.060
"Or you'll be asleep again before it's done."

01:56:45.060 --> 01:56:50.060
Once upon a time there were three little sisters.

01:56:50.060 --> 01:56:53.060
The doormouse began in a great hurry.

01:56:53.060 --> 01:57:04.060
"And their names were Elsie, Lacy, and Tilly, and they lived at the bottom of a well."

01:57:04.060 --> 01:57:06.060
"What did they live on?"

01:57:06.060 --> 01:57:13.060
said Alice, who always took a great interest in questions of eating and drinking.

01:57:13.060 --> 01:57:21.060
"They lived on Trico," said the doormouse, after thinking a minute or two.

01:57:21.060 --> 01:57:25.060
"They couldn't have done that," you know.

01:57:25.060 --> 01:57:27.060
Alice gently remarked.

01:57:27.060 --> 01:57:29.060
"They'd have been ill."

01:57:29.060 --> 01:57:32.060
"So they were," said the doormouse.

01:57:32.060 --> 01:57:35.060
"Very ill."

01:57:35.060 --> 01:57:41.060
Alice tried to fancy herself what such an extraordinary ways of living would be like.

01:57:41.060 --> 01:57:44.060
But it puzzled her too much.

01:57:44.060 --> 01:57:46.060
So she went on.

01:57:46.060 --> 01:57:49.060
"But why did they live at the bottom of a well?"

01:57:49.060 --> 01:57:55.060
"Take some more tea," the March Hare said to Alice, very earnestly.

01:57:55.060 --> 01:58:00.060
"I've had nothing yet," Alice replied in an offended tone.

01:58:00.060 --> 01:58:03.060
"So I can't take more."

01:58:03.060 --> 01:58:08.060
"You mean you can't take less," said the Hatter.

01:58:08.060 --> 01:58:12.060
"It's very easy to take more than nothing."

01:58:12.060 --> 01:58:17.060
"Nobody asked your opinion," said Alice.

01:58:17.060 --> 01:58:21.060
"Who's making personal remarks now?"

01:58:21.060 --> 01:58:24.060
The Hatter asked triumphantly.

01:58:24.060 --> 01:58:28.060
Alice did not quite know what to say to this.

01:58:28.060 --> 01:58:33.060
"So she helped herself to some tea and bread and butter,

01:58:33.060 --> 01:58:38.060
and then turned to the doormouse, and repeated her question.

01:58:38.060 --> 01:58:41.060
"Why did they live at the bottom of a well?"

01:58:41.060 --> 01:58:46.060
The doormouse again took a minute or two to think about it.

01:58:46.060 --> 01:58:50.060
And then said, "It was a tree call well.

01:58:50.060 --> 01:58:52.060
There's no such thing."

01:58:52.060 --> 01:58:59.060
Alice was beginning very angrily, but the Hatter and the March Hare went, "Shh, shh,"

01:58:59.060 --> 01:59:03.060
and the doormouse, soakily remarked.

01:59:03.060 --> 01:59:09.060
"If you can't be civil, you'd better finish the story for yourself."

01:59:09.060 --> 01:59:14.060
"No, please go on," Alice said very humbly.

01:59:14.060 --> 01:59:17.060
"I won't interrupt again.

01:59:17.060 --> 01:59:20.060
I dare say there may be one."

01:59:20.060 --> 01:59:25.060
"One indeed!" said the doormouse indignantly.

01:59:25.060 --> 01:59:28.060
However, he consented to go on.

01:59:28.060 --> 01:59:34.060
"And so these three little sisters, they were learning to draw, you know.

01:59:34.060 --> 01:59:40.060
"What did they draw?" said Alice, quite forgetting her promise.

01:59:40.060 --> 01:59:46.060
"Tree call," said the doormouse, without considering at all this time.

01:59:46.060 --> 01:59:49.060
"I want a clean cup."

01:59:49.060 --> 01:59:51.060
"Interrupted the Hatter.

01:59:51.060 --> 01:59:54.060
Let's all move one place on."

01:59:54.060 --> 02:00:00.060
He moved on as he spoke, and the doormouse followed him.

02:00:00.060 --> 02:00:08.060
The March Hare moved into the doormouse's place, and Alice, rather unwillingly, took the place of the March Hare.

02:00:08.060 --> 02:00:18.060
The Hatter was the only one who got any advantage from the change, and Alice was a good deal worse off than before.

02:00:18.060 --> 02:00:24.060
As the March Hare had just upset the milk jug into his plate.

02:00:24.060 --> 02:00:31.060
Alice did not wish to offend the doormouse again, so she began very cautiously.

02:00:31.060 --> 02:00:34.060
"But I don't understand.

02:00:34.060 --> 02:00:37.060
Where did they draw the treacle from?"

02:00:37.060 --> 02:00:43.060
"You can draw water out of a water well," said the Hatter.

02:00:43.060 --> 02:00:50.060
"So I should think you could draw a treacle out of a treacle well."

02:00:50.060 --> 02:00:52.060
"A, stupid."

02:00:52.060 --> 02:00:55.060
"But they were in the well."

02:00:55.060 --> 02:01:01.060
Alice said to the doormouse, not choosing to notice this last remark.

02:01:01.060 --> 02:01:05.060
"Of course they were," said the doormouse.

02:01:05.060 --> 02:01:07.060
"Well in."

02:01:07.060 --> 02:01:16.060
This answer so confused poor Alice, that she let the doormouse go on for some time without interrupting it.

02:01:16.060 --> 02:01:26.060
"They were learning to draw," the doormouse went on, yawning and rubbing its eyes, for it was getting very sleepy.

02:01:26.060 --> 02:01:29.060
"And they drew all manner of things.

02:01:29.060 --> 02:01:32.060
Everything that begins with an m."

02:01:32.060 --> 02:01:35.060
"Why with an m?" said Alice.

02:01:35.060 --> 02:01:39.060
"Why not?" said the march hair.

02:01:39.060 --> 02:01:41.060
Alice was silent.

02:01:41.060 --> 02:01:48.060
The doormouse had closed its eyes by this time, and was going off into a dose.

02:01:48.060 --> 02:01:56.060
But on being pinched by the Hatter, it woke up again with a little shriek and went on.

02:01:56.060 --> 02:02:07.060
That begins with an m, such as mouse traps, and the moon, and memory, and muchness.

02:02:07.060 --> 02:02:13.060
"You know, you say things are much of a muchness.

02:02:13.060 --> 02:02:18.060
Did you ever see such a thing as a drawing of a muchness?"

02:02:18.060 --> 02:02:24.060
"Really, now you ask me," said Alice, very much confused.

02:02:24.060 --> 02:02:26.060
"I don't think—"

02:02:26.060 --> 02:02:30.060
"Then you shouldn't talk," said the Hatter.

02:02:30.060 --> 02:02:35.060
"This piece of rudeness was more than Alice could bear.

02:02:35.060 --> 02:02:40.060
She got up in great disgust, and walked off.

02:02:40.060 --> 02:02:48.060
The doormouse fell asleep instantly, and neither of the others took the least notice of her going.

02:02:48.060 --> 02:02:54.060
Though she looked back once or twice, half-hoping that they would call after her.

02:02:54.060 --> 02:03:01.060
The last time she saw them, they were trying to put the doormouse into the teapot.

02:03:01.060 --> 02:03:08.060
"At any rate, I'll never go there again," said Alice as she picked her way through the wood.

02:03:08.060 --> 02:03:14.060
"It's the stupidest tea party I ever was at in all my life."

02:03:14.060 --> 02:03:22.060
"Just as she said this, she noticed that one of the trees had a door leading right into it.

02:03:22.060 --> 02:03:25.060
That's very curious," she thought.

02:03:25.060 --> 02:03:28.060
"But everything's curious today.

02:03:28.060 --> 02:03:32.060
I think I may as well go in at once."

02:03:32.060 --> 02:03:34.060
And in she went.

02:03:34.060 --> 02:03:41.060
Once more, she found herself in the long hall, and close to the little glass table.

02:03:41.060 --> 02:03:46.060
"Now I'll manage better this time," she said to herself.

02:03:46.060 --> 02:03:54.060
"And began by taking the little golden key, and unlocking the door, that led into the garden.

02:03:54.060 --> 02:03:58.060
Then she went to work nibbling at the mushroom.

02:03:58.060 --> 02:04:04.060
She had kept a piece of it in her pocket, till she was about a foot high.

02:04:04.060 --> 02:04:18.060
Then she walked down the little passage, and then she found herself at last in the beautiful garden, among the bright flower beds and the cool fountains."

02:04:18.060 --> 02:04:42.060
CHAPTER VIII

02:04:42.060 --> 02:04:52.060
Large rose tree stood near the entrance of the garden.

02:04:52.060 --> 02:05:03.060
Alice thought this a very curious thing, and she went near to watch them, and just as she came up to them, she heard one of them say,

02:05:03.060 --> 02:05:05.060
"Look out now, five!

02:05:05.060 --> 02:05:08.060
Don't go splash in pain over me like that!"

02:05:08.060 --> 02:05:10.060
"I couldn't help it."

02:05:10.060 --> 02:05:13.060
Alice said five in a sulky tone.

02:05:13.060 --> 02:05:15.060
"Seven jogged my elbow."

02:05:15.060 --> 02:05:20.060
"On which seven looked up," and said, "That's right, five.

02:05:20.060 --> 02:05:22.060
Always lay the blame on others."

02:05:22.060 --> 02:05:27.060
"You'd better not talk," said five.

02:05:27.060 --> 02:05:33.060
"I heard the Queen say only yesterday, you deserved to be beheaded."

02:05:33.060 --> 02:05:37.060
"What four?" said the one who had spoken first.

02:05:37.060 --> 02:05:41.060
"That's none of your business," two said seven.

02:05:41.060 --> 02:05:46.060
"Yes, it is his business," said five.

02:05:46.060 --> 02:05:52.060
"And all tell him it was for bringing the cook two of roots instead of onions."

02:05:52.060 --> 02:05:56.060
Seven flung down his brush, and had just begun.

02:05:56.060 --> 02:06:00.060
"Well, of all the unjust things."

02:06:00.060 --> 02:06:08.060
When his eye chanced to fall upon Alice, as she stood watching them, and he checked himself suddenly,

02:06:08.060 --> 02:06:13.060
the others looked round also, and all of them bowed low.

02:06:13.060 --> 02:06:18.060
"Would you tell me?" said Alice, a little timidly.

02:06:18.060 --> 02:06:21.060
"Why are you painting those roses?"

02:06:21.060 --> 02:06:25.060
Five and seven said nothing, but looked at two.

02:06:25.060 --> 02:06:28.060
Two began in a low voice.

02:06:28.060 --> 02:06:37.060
"Why, the fact is, you see, Miss, this year ought to have been a red rose tree,

02:06:37.060 --> 02:06:40.060
and we put a white one in by mistake.

02:06:40.060 --> 02:06:45.060
And if the Queen was to find it out, we should all have our heads cut off, you know.

02:06:45.060 --> 02:06:53.060
So you see, Miss, we're doing our best, a four she comes to, at this moment, five,

02:06:53.060 --> 02:06:57.060
who had been anxiously looking across the garden, called out,

02:06:57.060 --> 02:07:00.060
the Queen, the Queen.

02:07:00.060 --> 02:07:05.060
And the three gardeners instantly threw themselves flat upon their faces.

02:07:05.060 --> 02:07:13.060
There was a sound of many footsteps, and Alice looked round, eager to see the Queen.

02:07:13.060 --> 02:07:17.060
First came ten soldiers carrying clubs.

02:07:17.060 --> 02:07:20.060
These were all shaped like the three gardeners.

02:07:20.060 --> 02:07:26.060
All long and flat, with their hands and feet at the corners.

02:07:26.060 --> 02:07:29.060
Next, the ten courteas.

02:07:29.060 --> 02:07:35.060
These were ornamented all over with diamonds, and walked two and two.

02:07:35.060 --> 02:07:37.060
As the soldiers did.

02:07:37.060 --> 02:07:42.060
After these came the royal children, there were ten of them,

02:07:42.060 --> 02:07:49.060
and the little deers came jumping merrily along, hand and hand, and couples.

02:07:49.060 --> 02:07:52.060
They were all ornamented with hearts.

02:07:52.060 --> 02:07:57.060
Next came the guests, mostly kings and queens.

02:07:57.060 --> 02:08:01.060
And among them, Alice recognized the white rabbit.

02:08:01.060 --> 02:08:08.060
It was talking in a hurried, nervous manner, smiling at everything that was said.

02:08:08.060 --> 02:08:11.060
And went by without noticing her.

02:08:11.060 --> 02:08:20.060
Then followed the need of hearts, carrying the king's crown on a crimson velvet cushion.

02:08:20.060 --> 02:08:28.060
And, last of all this grand procession, came the king and queen of hearts.

02:08:28.060 --> 02:08:36.060
Alice was rather doubtful whether she ought not to lie down on her face like the three gardeners.

02:08:36.060 --> 02:08:42.060
But she could not remember ever having heard of such a rule at precessions.

02:08:42.060 --> 02:08:47.060
And besides, what would be the use of a procession?

02:08:47.060 --> 02:08:55.060
Thought she, if people had all to lie down upon their faces, so that they couldn't see it.

02:08:55.060 --> 02:08:59.060
So she stood still where she was, and waited.

02:08:59.060 --> 02:09:05.060
When the procession came opposite to Alice, they all stopped and looked at her.

02:09:05.060 --> 02:09:09.060
And the queen said severely, "Who is this?"

02:09:09.060 --> 02:09:15.060
She said it to the need of hearts, who only bowed and smiled in reply.

02:09:15.060 --> 02:09:20.060
"Idiot!" said the queen, tossing her head impatiently.

02:09:20.060 --> 02:09:26.060
And, turning to Alice, she went on, "What's your name, child?"

02:09:26.060 --> 02:09:28.060
"My name is Alice."

02:09:28.060 --> 02:09:35.060
"So please, your Majesty?" said Alice very politely, but she added to herself.

02:09:35.060 --> 02:09:39.060
"Why, there are only a pack of cards, after all.

02:09:39.060 --> 02:09:41.060
I needn't be afraid of them."

02:09:41.060 --> 02:09:44.060
"And who are these?"

02:09:44.060 --> 02:09:50.060
said the queen, pointing to the three gardeners who were lying around the rose tree.

02:09:50.060 --> 02:10:00.060
For, you see, as they were lying on their faces, and the pattern on their backs was the same as the rest of the pack.

02:10:00.060 --> 02:10:09.060
She could not tell whether they were gardeners, or soldiers, or courteas, or three of her own children.

02:10:09.060 --> 02:10:11.060
"How should I know?"

02:10:11.060 --> 02:10:15.060
said Alice, surprised at her own courage.

02:10:15.060 --> 02:10:18.060
"It's no business of mine!"

02:10:18.060 --> 02:10:29.060
The queen turned crimson with fury, and, after glaring at her for a moment, like a wild beast, screamed.

02:10:29.060 --> 02:10:31.060
"Off with her head! Off!"

02:10:31.060 --> 02:10:39.060
"Nonsense!" said Alice, very loudly and decidedly, and the queen was silent.

02:10:39.060 --> 02:10:49.060
The king laid his hand upon her arm, and timidly said, "Consider, my dear, she is only a child!"

02:10:49.060 --> 02:10:54.060
The queen turned angrily away from him, and said to the nave.

02:10:54.060 --> 02:10:56.060
"Turn them over!"

02:10:56.060 --> 02:11:01.060
The nave did so, very carefully, with one foot.

02:11:01.060 --> 02:11:06.060
"Get up!" said the queen, in a shrill, loud voice.

02:11:06.060 --> 02:11:10.060
And the three gardeners instantly jumped up.

02:11:10.060 --> 02:11:17.060
And began bowing to the king, the queen, the royal children, and everybody else.

02:11:17.060 --> 02:11:20.060
"Leave off that!" screamed the queen.

02:11:20.060 --> 02:11:22.060
"You make me giddy!"

02:11:22.060 --> 02:11:26.060
And then, turning to the rose tree, she went on.

02:11:26.060 --> 02:11:29.060
"What have you been doing here?"

02:11:29.060 --> 02:11:35.060
"May it please, your Majesty!" said two, in a very humble tone.

02:11:35.060 --> 02:11:38.060
Going down on one knee, as he spoke.

02:11:38.060 --> 02:11:40.060
"We were trying!"

02:11:40.060 --> 02:11:46.060
"I see!" said the queen, who had meanwhile been examining the roses.

02:11:46.060 --> 02:11:48.060
"Off with their heads!"

02:11:48.060 --> 02:11:51.060
And the procession moved on.

02:11:51.060 --> 02:11:56.060
Three of the soldiers remaining behind to execute the unfortunate gardeners,

02:11:56.060 --> 02:11:59.060
who ran to Alice for protection.

02:11:59.060 --> 02:12:02.060
"You shan't be beheaded!" said Alice.

02:12:02.060 --> 02:12:08.060
And she put them into a large flower pot that stood near.

02:12:08.060 --> 02:12:14.060
The three soldiers wandered about for a minute or two, looking for them,

02:12:14.060 --> 02:12:18.060
and then quietly marched off after the others.

02:12:18.060 --> 02:12:22.060
"Are their heads off?" shouted the queen.

02:12:22.060 --> 02:12:29.060
"Their heads are gone. If it please, your Majesty!" the soldiers shouted in reply.

02:12:29.060 --> 02:12:31.060
"That's right!" shouted the queen.

02:12:31.060 --> 02:12:34.060
"Can you play croquet?"

02:12:34.060 --> 02:12:38.060
The soldiers were silent, and looked at Alice,

02:12:38.060 --> 02:12:42.060
as the question was evidently meant for her.

02:12:42.060 --> 02:12:45.060
"Yes!" shouted Alice.

02:12:45.060 --> 02:12:48.060
"Come on then!" roared the queen.

02:12:48.060 --> 02:12:54.060
And Alice joined the procession, wondering very much what would happen next.

02:12:54.060 --> 02:13:00.060
"It's a very fine day!" said a timid voice at her side.

02:13:00.060 --> 02:13:03.060
She was walking by the white rabbit,

02:13:03.060 --> 02:13:06.060
who was peeping anxiously into her face.

02:13:06.060 --> 02:13:09.060
"Very!" said Alice.

02:13:09.060 --> 02:13:11.060
"Where's the Duchess?"

02:13:11.060 --> 02:13:16.060
"Hush, hush!" said the rabbit in a low, hurried tone.

02:13:16.060 --> 02:13:20.060
He looked anxiously over his shoulder as he spoke,

02:13:20.060 --> 02:13:23.060
and then raised himself upon tiptoe.

02:13:23.060 --> 02:13:27.060
"Put his mouth close to her ear," and whispered.

02:13:27.060 --> 02:13:31.060
"She's under sentence of execution."

02:13:31.060 --> 02:13:35.060
"What for?" said Alice.

02:13:35.060 --> 02:13:40.060
"Did you say what a pity?" the rabbit asked.

02:13:40.060 --> 02:13:44.060
"No, I didn't," said Alice.

02:13:44.060 --> 02:13:50.060
"I don't think it's at all a pity." I said, "What for?"

02:13:50.060 --> 02:13:53.060
She boxed the queen's ears.

02:13:53.060 --> 02:13:58.060
The rabbit began. Alice gave a little scream of laughter.

02:13:58.060 --> 02:14:03.060
"Oh, hush!" the rabbit whispered in a frightened tone.

02:14:03.060 --> 02:14:08.060
"The queen will hear you. You see, she came rather late,

02:14:08.060 --> 02:14:13.060
and the queen said, "Get to your places!"

02:14:13.060 --> 02:14:17.060
shouted the queen in a voice of thunder,

02:14:17.060 --> 02:14:20.060
and people began running about in all directions,

02:14:20.060 --> 02:14:23.060
tumbling up against each other.

02:14:23.060 --> 02:14:26.060
However, they got settled down in a minute or two,

02:14:26.060 --> 02:14:29.060
and the game began.

02:14:29.060 --> 02:14:33.060
Alice thought she had never seen such a curious,

02:14:33.060 --> 02:14:36.060
croquet ground in her life.

02:14:36.060 --> 02:14:38.060
It was all ridges and furrows.

02:14:38.060 --> 02:14:41.060
The balls were live hedgehogs.

02:14:41.060 --> 02:14:44.060
The mallets, live flamingos.

02:14:44.060 --> 02:14:50.060
And the soldiers had to double themselves up,

02:14:50.060 --> 02:14:54.060
and to stand on their hands and feet to make the arches.

02:14:54.060 --> 02:14:57.060
The chief difficulty Alice found at first

02:14:57.060 --> 02:14:59.060
was in managing her flamingo.

02:14:59.060 --> 02:15:03.060
She succeeded in getting its body tucked away,

02:15:03.060 --> 02:15:06.060
comfortably enough under her arm,

02:15:06.060 --> 02:15:09.060
with its legs hanging down.

02:15:09.060 --> 02:15:14.060
But generally, just as she had got its neck nicely straightened out,

02:15:14.060 --> 02:15:18.060
and was going to give the hedgehog a blow with its head,

02:15:18.060 --> 02:15:23.060
it would twist itself round and look up in her face.

02:15:23.060 --> 02:15:26.060
With such a puzzled expression,

02:15:26.060 --> 02:15:29.060
then she could not help bursting out laughing.

02:15:29.060 --> 02:15:32.060
And when she had got its head down,

02:15:32.060 --> 02:15:34.060
and was going to begin again,

02:15:34.060 --> 02:15:40.060
it was very provoking to find that the hedgehog had unrolled itself,

02:15:40.060 --> 02:15:43.060
and was in the act of crawling away.

02:15:43.060 --> 02:15:45.060
Besides all this,

02:15:45.060 --> 02:15:48.060
there was generally a ridge or furrow in the way,

02:15:48.060 --> 02:15:52.060
wherever she wanted to send the hedgehog to.

02:15:52.060 --> 02:15:56.060
And, as the doubled up soldiers were always getting up

02:15:56.060 --> 02:15:59.060
and walking off to other parts of the ground,

02:15:59.060 --> 02:16:02.060
Alice soon came to the conclusion

02:16:02.060 --> 02:16:05.060
that it was a very difficult game, indeed.

02:16:05.060 --> 02:16:10.060
The players all played at once without waiting for turns,

02:16:10.060 --> 02:16:13.060
quarreling all the while,

02:16:13.060 --> 02:16:15.060
and fighting for the hedgehogs,

02:16:15.060 --> 02:16:17.060
and in a very short time,

02:16:17.060 --> 02:16:20.060
the queen was in a furious passion

02:16:20.060 --> 02:16:22.060
and went stamping about,

02:16:22.060 --> 02:16:25.060
and shouting off with his head,

02:16:25.060 --> 02:16:28.060
or off with her head.

02:16:28.060 --> 02:16:30.060
About once in a minute,

02:16:30.060 --> 02:16:33.060
Alice began to feel very uneasy.

02:16:33.060 --> 02:16:36.060
To be sure, she had not, as yet,

02:16:36.060 --> 02:16:39.060
had any dispute with the queen,

02:16:39.060 --> 02:16:43.060
but she knew that it might happen any minute.

02:16:43.060 --> 02:16:45.060
And then, thought she,

02:16:45.060 --> 02:16:47.060
what would become of me?

02:16:47.060 --> 02:16:51.060
They're dreadfully fond of beheading people here.

02:16:51.060 --> 02:16:55.060
The great wonder is that there's anyone left alive.

02:16:55.060 --> 02:16:59.060
She was looking about for some way of escape,

02:16:59.060 --> 02:17:03.060
and wondering whether she could get away without being seen,

02:17:03.060 --> 02:17:07.060
when she noticed a curious appearance in the air.

02:17:07.060 --> 02:17:11.060
It puzzled her very much at first,

02:17:11.060 --> 02:17:15.060
but after watching it a minute or two,

02:17:15.060 --> 02:17:17.060
she made it out to be a grin,

02:17:17.060 --> 02:17:20.060
and she said to herself,

02:17:20.060 --> 02:17:22.060
"It's the Cheshire Cat.

02:17:22.060 --> 02:17:25.060
Now I shall have somebody to talk to."

02:17:25.060 --> 02:17:28.060
"How are you getting on?"

02:17:28.060 --> 02:17:30.060
said the Cat,

02:17:30.060 --> 02:17:32.060
as soon as there was mouth enough

02:17:32.060 --> 02:17:34.060
for it to speak with.

02:17:34.060 --> 02:17:37.060
Alice waited till the eyes appeared,

02:17:37.060 --> 02:17:38.060
and then nodded.

02:17:38.060 --> 02:17:41.060
"It's no use speaking to it."

02:17:41.060 --> 02:17:43.060
She thought.

02:17:43.060 --> 02:17:45.060
Till its ears have come,

02:17:45.060 --> 02:17:48.060
or at least one of them,

02:17:48.060 --> 02:17:51.060
in another minute the whole head appeared,

02:17:51.060 --> 02:17:54.060
and then Alice put down her flamingo,

02:17:54.060 --> 02:17:57.060
and began an account of the game.

02:17:57.060 --> 02:18:02.060
Feeling very glad she had someone to listen to her.

02:18:02.060 --> 02:18:06.060
The Cat seemed to think that there was enough of it now in sight,

02:18:06.060 --> 02:18:09.060
and no more of it appeared.

02:18:09.060 --> 02:18:13.060
"I don't think they play at all fairly."

02:18:13.060 --> 02:18:17.060
Alice began in a rather complaining tone.

02:18:17.060 --> 02:18:20.060
And they all quarrel so dreadfully,

02:18:20.060 --> 02:18:23.060
one can't hear oneself speak,

02:18:23.060 --> 02:18:28.060
and they don't seem to have any rules in particular.

02:18:28.060 --> 02:18:30.060
At least, if there are,

02:18:30.060 --> 02:18:33.060
nobody attends to them,

02:18:33.060 --> 02:18:37.060
and you've no idea how confusing it is

02:18:37.060 --> 02:18:40.060
all the things being alive.

02:18:40.060 --> 02:18:44.060
For instance, there's the arch I've got to go through next,

02:18:44.060 --> 02:18:48.060
walking about at the other end of the ground.

02:18:48.060 --> 02:18:52.060
And I should have croaked the Queen's Hedgehog just now,

02:18:52.060 --> 02:18:56.060
only it ran away when it saw mine coming.

02:18:56.060 --> 02:18:59.060
"How do you like the Queen?"

02:18:59.060 --> 02:19:03.060
said the Cat in a low voice.

02:19:03.060 --> 02:19:06.060
"Not at all," said Alice.

02:19:06.060 --> 02:19:09.060
"She's so extremely."

02:19:09.060 --> 02:19:13.060
"Just then," she noticed that the Queen was close behind her,

02:19:13.060 --> 02:19:16.060
listening, so she went on.

02:19:16.060 --> 02:19:22.060
"Likely to win that it's hardly worthwhile finishing the game."

02:19:22.060 --> 02:19:25.060
The Queen smiled and passed on.

02:19:25.060 --> 02:19:28.060
"Who are you talking to?"

02:19:28.060 --> 02:19:31.060
said the King, going up to Alice,

02:19:31.060 --> 02:19:35.060
and looking at the Cat's head with great curiosity.

02:19:35.060 --> 02:19:40.060
"It's a friend of mine, a Cheshire Cat," said Alice.

02:19:40.060 --> 02:19:43.060
"Allow me to introduce it."

02:19:43.060 --> 02:19:49.060
"I don't like the look of it at all," said the King.

02:19:49.060 --> 02:19:53.060
"However, it may kiss my hand if it likes."

02:19:53.060 --> 02:19:57.060
"I'd rather not," the Cat remarked.

02:19:57.060 --> 02:20:00.060
"Don't be impertinent," said the King.

02:20:00.060 --> 02:20:06.060
"And don't look at me like that," he got behind Alice as he spoke.

02:20:06.060 --> 02:20:10.060
"A Cat may look at a King," said Alice.

02:20:10.060 --> 02:20:15.060
"I've read that in some book, but I don't remember where."

02:20:15.060 --> 02:20:20.060
"Well, it must be removed," said the King, very decidedly.

02:20:20.060 --> 02:20:25.060
"And he called the Queen, who is passing at the moment.

02:20:25.060 --> 02:20:29.060
My dear, I wish you would have this Cat removed."

02:20:29.060 --> 02:20:35.060
The Queen had only one way of settling all difficulties, great or small.

02:20:35.060 --> 02:20:37.060
"Off with his head!"

02:20:37.060 --> 02:20:41.060
She said, without even looking round.

02:20:41.060 --> 02:20:48.060
"I'll fetch the executioner myself," said the King eagerly, and he hurried off.

02:20:48.060 --> 02:20:54.060
Alice thought she might as well go back and see how the game was going on,

02:20:54.060 --> 02:20:59.060
as she heard the Queen's voice in the distance, screaming with passion.

02:20:59.060 --> 02:21:08.060
She had already heard her sentence three of the players to be executed for having missed their turns,

02:21:08.060 --> 02:21:13.060
and she did not like the look of things at all.

02:21:13.060 --> 02:21:20.060
As the game was in such confusion that she never knew whether it was her turn or not,

02:21:20.060 --> 02:21:23.060
so she went in search of her hedgehog.

02:21:23.060 --> 02:21:30.060
The hedgehog was engaged in a fight with another hedgehog, which seemed to Alice

02:21:30.060 --> 02:21:35.060
an excellent opportunity for crocheting one of them with the other.

02:21:35.060 --> 02:21:42.060
The only difficulty was that her flamingo was gone across to the other side of the garden,

02:21:42.060 --> 02:21:50.060
where Alice could see it trying in a helpless sort of way to fly up into a tree.

02:21:50.060 --> 02:21:56.060
By the time she had caught the flamingo and brought it back, the fight was over,

02:21:56.060 --> 02:21:59.060
and both the hedgehogs were out of sight.

02:21:59.060 --> 02:22:04.060
"But it doesn't matter much," thought Alice.

02:22:04.060 --> 02:22:09.060
"As all the arches are gone from this side of the ground."

02:22:09.060 --> 02:22:12.060
So she tucked it away under her arm.

02:22:12.060 --> 02:22:19.060
That it might not escape again, and went back for a little more conversation with her friend.

02:22:19.060 --> 02:22:28.060
When she got back to the Cheshire Cat, she was surprised to find quite a large crowd collected around it.

02:22:28.060 --> 02:22:36.060
There was a dispute going on between the executioner, the king, and the queen,

02:22:36.060 --> 02:22:45.060
who were all talking at once, while all the rest were quite silent and looked very uncomfortable.

02:22:45.060 --> 02:22:51.060
The moment Alice appeared, she was appealed to by all three to settle the question,

02:22:51.060 --> 02:22:57.060
and they repeated their arguments to her, though, as they all spoke at once,

02:22:57.060 --> 02:23:03.060
she found it very hard indeed to make out exactly what they said.

02:23:03.060 --> 02:23:13.060
The executioner's argument was that you couldn't cut off ahead unless there was a body to cut it off from,

02:23:13.060 --> 02:23:22.060
that he had never had to do such a thing before, and he wasn't going to begin at his time of life.

02:23:22.060 --> 02:23:29.060
The king's argument was that anything that had ahead could be beheaded,

02:23:29.060 --> 02:23:32.060
and that you weren't to talk nonsense.

02:23:32.060 --> 02:23:39.060
The queen's argument was that if something wasn't done about it in less than no time,

02:23:39.060 --> 02:23:43.060
she'd have everybody executed all round.

02:23:43.060 --> 02:23:50.060
It was this last remark that had made the whole party look so grave and anxious.

02:23:50.060 --> 02:23:57.060
Alice could think of nothing else to say, but it belongs to the Duchess.

02:23:57.060 --> 02:24:00.060
You'd better ask her about it.

02:24:00.060 --> 02:24:02.060
She's in prison.

02:24:02.060 --> 02:24:04.060
The queen said to the executioner.

02:24:04.060 --> 02:24:10.060
Fetch her here, and the executioner went off like an arrow.

02:24:10.060 --> 02:24:18.060
The cat's head began fading away the moment he was gone, and by the time he had come back with the Duchess,

02:24:18.060 --> 02:24:26.060
it had entirely disappeared, so the king and the executioner ran wildly up and down looking for it,

02:24:26.060 --> 02:24:31.060
while the rest of the party went back to the game.

02:24:31.060 --> 02:24:39.060
End of Chapter 8

02:24:39.060 --> 02:24:46.060
Chapter 9 of Alice's Adventures in Wonderland by Louis Carroll.

02:24:46.060 --> 02:24:51.060
This liberal vox recording is in the public domain.

02:24:51.060 --> 02:24:56.060
Chapter 9, The Mock Turtle's Story

02:24:56.060 --> 02:25:02.060
You can't think how glad I am to see you again, you dear old thing.

02:25:02.060 --> 02:25:10.060
Said the Duchess, as she tucked her arm affectionately into Alice's, and they walked off together.

02:25:10.060 --> 02:25:22.060
Alice was very glad to find her in such a pleasant temper, and thought to herself that perhaps it was only the pepper that had made her so savage when they met in the kitchen.

02:25:22.060 --> 02:25:27.060
"When I'm a Duchess," she said to herself.

02:25:27.060 --> 02:25:30.060
"Not in a very hopeful tone, though."

02:25:30.060 --> 02:25:35.060
"I won't have any pepper in my kitchen at all."

02:25:35.060 --> 02:25:38.060
Soup does very well without.

02:25:38.060 --> 02:25:43.060
Maybe it's always pepper that makes people hot-tempered.

02:25:43.060 --> 02:25:49.060
She went on very much pleased at having found out a new kind of rule.

02:25:49.060 --> 02:25:52.060
And vinegar that makes them sour.

02:25:52.060 --> 02:25:55.060
And camel meal that makes them better.

02:25:55.060 --> 02:26:01.060
And barley sugar and such things that make children sweet-tempered.

02:26:01.060 --> 02:26:04.060
I only wish people knew that.

02:26:04.060 --> 02:26:08.060
Then they wouldn't be so stingy about it, you know.

02:26:08.060 --> 02:26:17.060
She had quite forgotten the Duchess by this time, and was a little startled when she heard her voice close to her ear.

02:26:17.060 --> 02:26:24.060
"You were thinking about something, my dear, and that makes you forget to talk.

02:26:24.060 --> 02:26:31.060
I can't tell you just now what the moral of that is, but I shall remember it in a bit."

02:26:31.060 --> 02:26:36.060
"Perhaps it hasn't won," Alice ventured to remark.

02:26:36.060 --> 02:26:40.060
"Tut, tut, child," said the Duchess.

02:26:40.060 --> 02:26:44.060
"Everything's got a moral, if only you can find it."

02:26:44.060 --> 02:26:49.060
And she squeezed herself up closer to Alice's side as she spoke.

02:26:49.060 --> 02:26:53.060
Alice did not much like keeping so close to her.

02:26:53.060 --> 02:26:57.060
First, because the Duchess was very ugly.

02:26:57.060 --> 02:27:04.060
And secondly, because she was exactly the right height to rest her chin upon Alice's shoulder.

02:27:04.060 --> 02:27:07.060
And it was an uncomfortably sharp chin.

02:27:07.060 --> 02:27:14.060
However, she did not like to be rude, so she bore it as well as she could.

02:27:14.060 --> 02:27:22.060
"The games going on rather better now," she said, by way of keeping up the conversation a little.

02:27:22.060 --> 02:27:25.060
"Tis so," said the Duchess.

02:27:25.060 --> 02:27:34.060
"And the moral of that is, oh, tis love, tis love that makes the world go round."

02:27:34.060 --> 02:27:36.060
"Somebody said," Alice whispered.

02:27:36.060 --> 02:27:42.060
"That it's done by everybody minding their own business."

02:27:42.060 --> 02:27:52.060
"Oh, well, it means much the same thing," said the Duchess, digging her sharp little chin into Alice's shoulder as she added.

02:27:52.060 --> 02:28:02.060
"And the moral of that is, take care of the sense, and the sounds will take care of themselves."

02:28:02.060 --> 02:28:09.060
"How fond she is of finding morals in things," Alice thought to herself.

02:28:09.060 --> 02:28:18.060
"I dare say you're wondering why I don't put my arm round your waist," the Duchess said after a pause.

02:28:18.060 --> 02:28:27.060
"The reason is that I'm doubtful about the temper of your flamingo. Shall I try the experiment?"

02:28:27.060 --> 02:28:36.060
"He might bite," Alice cautiously replied, not feeling at all anxious to have the experiment tried.

02:28:36.060 --> 02:28:39.060
"Very true," said the Duchess.

02:28:39.060 --> 02:28:49.060
"Flamingo's and mustard both bite, and the moral of that is, birds of a feather flock together."

02:28:49.060 --> 02:28:54.060
"Only mustard isn't a bird," Alice remarked.

02:28:54.060 --> 02:28:58.060
"Right," as usual, said the Duchess.

02:28:58.060 --> 02:29:02.060
"What a clear way you have of putting things."

02:29:02.060 --> 02:29:05.060
"It's a mineral, I think."

02:29:05.060 --> 02:29:13.060
"Of course it is," said the Duchess, who seemed ready to agree to everything that Alice said.

02:29:13.060 --> 02:29:21.060
"There's a large mustard of mine near here, and the moral of that is, the more there is of mine,

02:29:21.060 --> 02:29:24.060
the less there is of yours."

02:29:24.060 --> 02:29:31.060
"Oh, I know," exclaimed Alice, who had not attended to this last remark.

02:29:31.060 --> 02:29:36.060
"It's a vegetable. It doesn't look like one, but it is."

02:29:36.060 --> 02:29:40.060
"I quite agree with you," said the Duchess.

02:29:40.060 --> 02:29:46.060
"And the moral of that is, "Be what you would seem to be,

02:29:46.060 --> 02:29:54.060
or if you'd like it put more simply, never imagine yourself, not to be otherwise,

02:29:54.060 --> 02:30:01.060
than what it might appear to others, that what you were, or might have been,

02:30:01.060 --> 02:30:09.060
was not otherwise, than what you had been, would have appeared to them to be otherwise."

02:30:09.060 --> 02:30:15.060
"I think I should understand that better," Alice said very politely.

02:30:15.060 --> 02:30:22.060
"If I had it written down, but I can't quite follow it as you say it.

02:30:22.060 --> 02:30:30.060
That's nothing to what I could say if I chose," the Duchess replied, in a pleased tone.

02:30:30.060 --> 02:30:36.060
"Pray, don't trouble yourself to say it any longer than that," said Alice.

02:30:36.060 --> 02:30:41.060
"Oh, don't talk about trouble," said the Duchess.

02:30:41.060 --> 02:30:49.060
"I make you a present of everything I've said as yet, a cheap sort of present," thought Alice.

02:30:49.060 --> 02:30:57.060
"I'm glad that they don't give birthday presents like that," but she did not venture to say it, out loud.

02:30:57.060 --> 02:31:04.060
"Thinking again," the Duchess asked, with another dig of her sharp little chin.

02:31:04.060 --> 02:31:11.060
"I've a right to think," said Alice, sharply, for she was beginning to feel a little worried.

02:31:11.060 --> 02:31:15.060
"Just about as much right," said the Duchess.

02:31:15.060 --> 02:31:23.060
"As pigs have to fly, and the more, but here, to Alice's great surprise,

02:31:23.060 --> 02:31:30.060
the Duchess's voice died away, even in the middle of her favorite word, moral,

02:31:30.060 --> 02:31:40.060
and the arm that was linked into hers began to tremble," Alice looked up, and there stood the queen in front of them,

02:31:40.060 --> 02:31:44.060
with her arms folded, frowning like a thunderstorm.

02:31:44.060 --> 02:31:51.060
"A fine day, your majesty," the Duchess began in a low, weak voice.

02:31:51.060 --> 02:31:58.060
"Now, I give you fair warning," shouted the queen, stamping on the ground as she spoke.

02:31:58.060 --> 02:32:06.060
"Either you or your head must be off, and that, in about half no time, take your choice."

02:32:06.060 --> 02:32:11.060
The Duchess took her choice, and was gone in a moment.

02:32:11.060 --> 02:32:20.060
"Let's go on with the game," the queen said to Alice, and Alice was much too frightened to say a word,

02:32:20.060 --> 02:32:24.060
but slowly followed her back to the croquet ground.

02:32:24.060 --> 02:32:31.060
The other guests had taken advantage of the queen's absence, and were resting in the shade.

02:32:31.060 --> 02:32:36.060
However, the moment they saw her, they hurried back to the game.

02:32:36.060 --> 02:32:43.060
The queen merely remarking that a moment's delay would cost them their lives.

02:32:43.060 --> 02:32:50.060
All the time they were playing, the queen never left off quarreling with the other players, and shouting,

02:32:50.060 --> 02:32:52.060
"Off with his head!"

02:32:52.060 --> 02:32:55.060
Or, "Off with her head!"

02:32:55.060 --> 02:33:00.060
Those whom she sentenced were taken into custody by the soldiers.

02:33:00.060 --> 02:33:09.060
Who, of course, had to leave off being arches to do this, so that, by the end of half an hour or so,

02:33:09.060 --> 02:33:17.060
there were no arches left, and all the players, except the king, the queen, and Alice,

02:33:17.060 --> 02:33:22.060
were in custody and under sentence of execution.

02:33:22.060 --> 02:33:27.060
"Then the queen left off, quite out of breath," and said to Alice.

02:33:27.060 --> 02:33:30.060
"Have you seen the mock turtle yet?"

02:33:30.060 --> 02:33:32.060
"No," said Alice.

02:33:32.060 --> 02:33:35.060
"I don't even know what a mock turtle is!"

02:33:35.060 --> 02:33:40.060
"It's the thing mock turtle soup is made from," said the queen.

02:33:40.060 --> 02:33:44.060
"I never saw one, or heard of one," said Alice.

02:33:44.060 --> 02:33:46.060
"Come on then," said the queen.

02:33:46.060 --> 02:33:49.060
"And he shall tell you his history!"

02:33:49.060 --> 02:33:54.060
As they walked off together, Alice heard the king say in a low voice,

02:33:54.060 --> 02:33:56.060
to the company generally.

02:33:56.060 --> 02:33:58.060
"You are all pardoned."

02:33:58.060 --> 02:34:01.060
"Come, that's a good thing!"

02:34:01.060 --> 02:34:02.060
She said to herself.

02:34:02.060 --> 02:34:08.060
For she had felt quite unhappy at the number of executions the queen had ordered.

02:34:08.060 --> 02:34:13.060
They very soon came upon a Griffin, lying fast asleep in the sun.

02:34:13.060 --> 02:34:18.060
"If you don't know what a Griffin is, look at the picture."

02:34:18.060 --> 02:34:22.060
"Up, lazy thing," said the queen.

02:34:22.060 --> 02:34:28.060
"And take this young lady to see the mock turtle, and to hear his history.

02:34:28.060 --> 02:34:33.060
I must go back and see after some executions I have ordered."

02:34:33.060 --> 02:34:38.060
And she walked off, leaving Alice alone with the Griffin.

02:34:38.060 --> 02:34:41.060
Alice did not quite like the look of the creature,

02:34:41.060 --> 02:34:46.060
but on the whole she thought it would be quite as safe to stay with it

02:34:46.060 --> 02:34:50.060
as to go after that savage queen.

02:34:50.060 --> 02:34:51.060
So she waited.

02:34:51.060 --> 02:34:54.060
The Griffin sat up and rubbed its eyes.

02:34:54.060 --> 02:34:58.060
Then it watched the queen till she was out of sight.

02:34:58.060 --> 02:34:59.060
Then it chuckled.

02:34:59.060 --> 02:35:05.060
"What fun!" said the Griffin, half to itself, half to Alice.

02:35:05.060 --> 02:35:08.060
"What is the fun?" said Alice.

02:35:08.060 --> 02:35:10.060
"Why, she?" said the queen.

02:35:10.060 --> 02:35:13.060
"It's all her fancy.

02:35:13.060 --> 02:35:17.060
That they never executes nobody, you know.

02:35:17.060 --> 02:35:20.060
Come on, everybody says.

02:35:20.060 --> 02:35:25.060
Come on, here!" thought Alice, as she went slowly after it.

02:35:25.060 --> 02:35:31.060
"I never was so ordered about in all my life, never!"

02:35:31.060 --> 02:35:37.060
They had not gone far before they saw the mock turtle in the distance,

02:35:37.060 --> 02:35:41.060
sitting sad and lonely on a little ledge of rock.

02:35:41.060 --> 02:35:46.060
And as they came nearer Alice could hear him sighing

02:35:46.060 --> 02:35:49.060
as if his heart would break.

02:35:49.060 --> 02:35:51.060
She pitied him deeply.

02:35:51.060 --> 02:35:53.060
"What is his sorrow?"

02:35:53.060 --> 02:36:01.060
She asked the Griffin, and the Griffin answered very nearly in the same words as before.

02:36:01.060 --> 02:36:06.060
"It's all his fancy, that he hasn't got no sorrow, you know.

02:36:06.060 --> 02:36:07.060
Come on!"

02:36:07.060 --> 02:36:10.060
So they went up to the mock turtle,

02:36:10.060 --> 02:36:14.060
who looked at them with large eyes full of tears,

02:36:14.060 --> 02:36:16.060
but said nothing.

02:36:16.060 --> 02:36:19.060
"This here, young lady!" said the Griffin.

02:36:19.060 --> 02:36:22.060
"She wants for to know your history," she do.

02:36:22.060 --> 02:36:28.060
"All to it, her," said the mock turtle in a deep hollow tone.

02:36:28.060 --> 02:36:35.060
"Sit down, both of you, and don't speak a word till I've finished."

02:36:35.060 --> 02:36:40.060
So they sat down, and nobody spoke for some minutes.

02:36:40.060 --> 02:36:42.060
Alice thought to herself,

02:36:42.060 --> 02:36:46.060
"I don't see how he can ever finish if he does it begin."

02:36:46.060 --> 02:36:49.060
But she waited patiently.

02:36:49.060 --> 02:36:54.060
"Once," said the mock turtle at last, with a deep sigh.

02:36:54.060 --> 02:36:57.060
"I was a real turtle.

02:36:57.060 --> 02:37:01.060
These words were followed by a very long silence,

02:37:01.060 --> 02:37:06.060
broken only by an occasional exclamation of..."

02:37:06.060 --> 02:37:11.060
From the Griffin, and the constant heavy sobbing of the mock turtle,

02:37:11.060 --> 02:37:14.060
Alice was very nearly getting up and saying,

02:37:14.060 --> 02:37:17.060
"Thank you, sir, for your interesting story.

02:37:17.060 --> 02:37:22.060
But she could not help thinking there must be more to come,

02:37:22.060 --> 02:37:26.060
so she sat still and said nothing.

02:37:26.060 --> 02:37:30.060
"When we were little," the mock turtle went on at last.

02:37:30.060 --> 02:37:35.060
"More calmly, though still sobbing a little now and then."

02:37:35.060 --> 02:37:38.060
"We went to school in the sea.

02:37:38.060 --> 02:37:41.060
The master was an old turtle.

02:37:41.060 --> 02:37:43.060
We used to call him tortoise."

02:37:43.060 --> 02:37:45.060
"Why did you call him tortoise?

02:37:45.060 --> 02:37:47.060
If he wasn't one."

02:37:47.060 --> 02:37:48.060
Alice asked.

02:37:48.060 --> 02:37:54.060
"We called him tortoise because he taught us," said the mock turtle angrily.

02:37:54.060 --> 02:37:57.060
"Really, you are very dull."

02:37:57.060 --> 02:38:05.060
"You ought to be ashamed of yourself for asking such a simple question," added the Griffin,

02:38:05.060 --> 02:38:09.060
and then they both sat silent and looked at poor Alice,

02:38:09.060 --> 02:38:12.060
who felt ready to sink into the earth.

02:38:12.060 --> 02:38:15.060
At last, the Griffin said to the mock turtle,

02:38:15.060 --> 02:38:18.060
"Drive on, old fellow.

02:38:18.060 --> 02:38:20.060
Don't be all day about it."

02:38:20.060 --> 02:38:23.060
And he went on in these words.

02:38:23.060 --> 02:38:28.060
"Yes, we went to school in the sea.

02:38:28.060 --> 02:38:30.060
Though you may not believe it."

02:38:30.060 --> 02:38:34.060
"I never said I didn't," interrupted Alice.

02:38:34.060 --> 02:38:37.060
"You did," said the mock turtle.

02:38:37.060 --> 02:38:43.060
"Hold your tongue," added the Griffin before Alice could speak again.

02:38:43.060 --> 02:38:45.060
The mock turtle went on.

02:38:45.060 --> 02:38:48.060
"We had the best of educations.

02:38:48.060 --> 02:38:52.060
In fact, we went to school every day."

02:38:52.060 --> 02:38:56.060
"I've been to a day school too," said Alice.

02:38:56.060 --> 02:39:00.060
"You need to be so proud as all that."

02:39:00.060 --> 02:39:05.060
"With extras?" asked the mock turtle a little anxiously.

02:39:05.060 --> 02:39:07.060
"Yes," said Alice.

02:39:07.060 --> 02:39:10.060
"We learned French and music."

02:39:10.060 --> 02:39:13.060
"And washing?" said the mock turtle.

02:39:13.060 --> 02:39:17.060
"Certainly not," said Alice indignantly.

02:39:17.060 --> 02:39:26.060
"Ah, then yours wasn't a really good school," said the mock turtle in a tone of great relief.

02:39:26.060 --> 02:39:37.060
"Now at ours, they had, at the end of the bill, French, music, and washing, extra."

02:39:37.060 --> 02:39:43.060
"You couldn't have wanted it much," said Alice, living at the bottom of the sea.

02:39:43.060 --> 02:39:49.060
"I couldn't afford to learn it," said the mock turtle with the sigh.

02:39:49.060 --> 02:39:52.060
"I only took the regular course."

02:39:52.060 --> 02:39:54.060
"What was that?"

02:39:54.060 --> 02:39:56.060
inquired Alice.

02:39:56.060 --> 02:40:03.060
"Reeling and rising, of course, to begin with," the mock turtle replied.

02:40:03.060 --> 02:40:13.060
"And then the different branches of arithmetic, ambition, distraction,

02:40:13.060 --> 02:40:15.060
agglification, and derision."

02:40:15.060 --> 02:40:20.060
"I never heard of agglification," Alice ventured to say.

02:40:20.060 --> 02:40:22.060
"What is it?"

02:40:22.060 --> 02:40:25.060
The Griffin lifted up both its paws in surprise.

02:40:25.060 --> 02:40:27.060
"What?

02:40:27.060 --> 02:40:29.060
Never heard of agglifying?"

02:40:29.060 --> 02:40:34.060
"You know what to beautify is," I suppose.

02:40:34.060 --> 02:40:37.060
"Yes," said Alice doubtfully.

02:40:37.060 --> 02:40:44.060
"It means to make anything prettier."

02:40:44.060 --> 02:40:48.060
"Well, then," the Griffin went on.

02:40:48.060 --> 02:40:54.060
"If you don't know what to agglify is, you are a simpleton."

02:40:54.060 --> 02:41:02.060
Alice did not feel encouraged to ask any more questions about it, so she turned to the mock turtle, and said,

02:41:02.060 --> 02:41:04.060
"What else had you to learn?"

02:41:04.060 --> 02:41:12.060
"Well, there was mystery," the mock turtle replied, counting off the subjects on his flappers.

02:41:12.060 --> 02:41:20.060
"Mystery, ancient and modern, with seeography, then drawing, the drawing master,

02:41:20.060 --> 02:41:25.060
was an old conger eel that used to come once a week.

02:41:25.060 --> 02:41:32.060
He taught us drawing, stretching, and fainting in coils."

02:41:32.060 --> 02:41:36.060
"What was that like?" said Alice.

02:41:36.060 --> 02:41:42.060
"Well, well, I can't show it you myself," the mock turtle said.

02:41:42.060 --> 02:41:47.060
"I'm too stiff," and the Griffin never learned it.

02:41:47.060 --> 02:41:50.060
"Hadn't time," said the Griffin.

02:41:50.060 --> 02:41:53.060
"I went to the classics master, though.

02:41:53.060 --> 02:41:55.060
He was an old crab.

02:41:55.060 --> 02:41:56.060
He was."

02:41:56.060 --> 02:42:01.060
"I never went to him," the mock turtle said with a sigh.

02:42:01.060 --> 02:42:06.060
"He taught laughing and grief," they used to say.

02:42:06.060 --> 02:42:11.060
"So he did," so he did," said the Griffin,

02:42:11.060 --> 02:42:17.060
sighing in his turn, and both creatures hid their faces in their paws.

02:42:17.060 --> 02:42:22.060
"And how many hours a day did you do lessons?"

02:42:22.060 --> 02:42:25.060
said Alice in a hurry to change the subject.

02:42:25.060 --> 02:42:30.060
"Ten hours the first day," said the mock turtle.

02:42:30.060 --> 02:42:33.060
"Nine the next, and so on."

02:42:33.060 --> 02:42:37.060
"What a curious plan," exclaimed Alice.

02:42:37.060 --> 02:42:40.060
"That's the reason they're called lessons."

02:42:40.060 --> 02:42:42.060
The Griffin remarked.

02:42:42.060 --> 02:42:46.060
"Because they lesson from day to day."

02:42:46.060 --> 02:42:50.060
This was quite a new idea to Alice,

02:42:50.060 --> 02:42:55.060
and she thought it over a little before she made her next remark.

02:42:55.060 --> 02:42:58.060
"Then the eleventh day must have been a holiday?"

02:42:58.060 --> 02:43:02.060
"Of course it was," said the mock turtle.

02:43:02.060 --> 02:43:05.060
"And how did you manage on the twelfth?"

02:43:05.060 --> 02:43:07.060
Alice went on eagerly.

02:43:07.060 --> 02:43:11.060
"That's enough about lessons," the Griffin interrupted

02:43:11.060 --> 02:43:13.060
in a very decided tone.

02:43:13.060 --> 02:43:17.060
"Tell her something about the games now."

02:43:17.060 --> 02:43:41.060
CHAPTER X

02:43:41.060 --> 02:43:49.060
Well, the mock turtle sighed deeply, and drew the back of one flapper across his eyes.

02:43:49.060 --> 02:43:55.060
He looked at Alice, and tried to speak, but four-minute or two.

02:43:55.060 --> 02:43:57.060
Sobs choked his voice.

02:43:57.060 --> 02:44:01.060
"Same as if he had a bone in his throat," said the Griffin.

02:44:01.060 --> 02:44:05.060
"And it set to work shaking him, and punching him in the back.

02:44:05.060 --> 02:44:12.060
At last, the mock turtle recovered his voice, and, with tears running down his cheeks,

02:44:12.060 --> 02:44:14.060
he went on again.

02:44:14.060 --> 02:44:19.060
"You may not have lived much under the sea."

02:44:19.060 --> 02:44:21.060
"I haven't," said Alice.

02:44:21.060 --> 02:44:27.060
"And perhaps you were never even introduced to a lobster."

02:44:27.060 --> 02:44:29.060
Alice began to say.

02:44:29.060 --> 02:44:31.060
"I once tasted."

02:44:31.060 --> 02:44:36.060
But checked herself hastily, and said, "No, never."

02:44:36.060 --> 02:44:44.060
"So you can have no idea what a delightful thing a lobster quadrill is."

02:44:44.060 --> 02:44:48.060
"No, indeed," said Alice.

02:44:48.060 --> 02:44:50.060
"What sort of a dance is it?"

02:44:50.060 --> 02:44:52.060
"Why," said the Griffin.

02:44:52.060 --> 02:44:57.060
"You first form into a line along the sea shore."

02:44:57.060 --> 02:45:01.060
"Two lines!" cried the mock turtle.

02:45:01.060 --> 02:45:05.060
"Seals, turtles, salmon, and so on."

02:45:05.060 --> 02:45:12.060
"Then when you've cleared all the jellyfish out of the way."

02:45:12.060 --> 02:45:16.060
"That generally takes some time," interrupted the Griffin.

02:45:16.060 --> 02:45:18.060
"You advance twice."

02:45:18.060 --> 02:45:23.060
"Each with a lobster as a partner!" cried the Griffin.

02:45:23.060 --> 02:45:26.060
"Of course," the mock turtle said.

02:45:26.060 --> 02:45:30.060
"Advanced twice," said two partners.

02:45:30.060 --> 02:45:34.060
"Change lobsters, and retire in the same order."

02:45:34.060 --> 02:45:36.060
continued the Griffin.

02:45:36.060 --> 02:45:40.060
"Then you know," the mock turtle went on.

02:45:40.060 --> 02:45:42.060
"You throw the—"

02:45:42.060 --> 02:45:47.060
"The lobsters!" shouted the Griffin, with a bound into the air.

02:45:47.060 --> 02:45:51.060
"As far out to sea as you can."

02:45:51.060 --> 02:45:55.060
"Swim after them!" screamed the Griffin.

02:45:55.060 --> 02:45:58.060
"Turn a somersault in the sea."

02:45:58.060 --> 02:46:02.060
cried the mock turtle, capering wildly about.

02:46:02.060 --> 02:46:09.060
"Change lobsters again!" yelled the Griffin at the top of its voice.

02:46:09.060 --> 02:46:11.060
"Back to land again."

02:46:11.060 --> 02:46:15.060
"And that's all the first figure," said the mock turtle.

02:46:15.060 --> 02:46:18.060
Suddenly dropping his voice.

02:46:18.060 --> 02:46:30.060
And the two creatures, who had been jumping about like mad things all this time, sat down again very sadly and quietly.

02:46:30.060 --> 02:46:32.060
And looked at Alice.

02:46:32.060 --> 02:46:37.060
"It must be a very pretty dance," said Alice, timidly.

02:46:37.060 --> 02:46:43.060
"Would you like to see a little of it?" said the mock turtle.

02:46:43.060 --> 02:46:46.060
"Very much indeed," said Alice.

02:46:46.060 --> 02:46:52.060
"Come, let's try the first figure," said the mock turtle to the Griffin.

02:46:52.060 --> 02:46:56.060
"We can do without lobsters," you know.

02:46:56.060 --> 02:46:58.060
"Which shall sing?"

02:46:58.060 --> 02:47:02.060
"Oh, you sing," said the Griffin.

02:47:02.060 --> 02:47:04.060
"I've forgotten the words!"

02:47:04.060 --> 02:47:10.060
So they began solemnly dancing round and round Alice.

02:47:10.060 --> 02:47:16.060
Every now and then treading on her toes when they passed too close.

02:47:16.060 --> 02:47:26.060
And waving their four paws to mark the time, while the mock turtle sang this very slowly and sadly.

02:47:26.060 --> 02:47:32.060
"Will you walk a little faster," said awaiting to a snail.

02:47:32.060 --> 02:47:34.060
There's a porpoise close behind us.

02:47:34.060 --> 02:47:36.060
And he's treading on my tail.

02:47:36.060 --> 02:47:42.060
"See how eagerly the lobsters and the turtles all advance.

02:47:42.060 --> 02:47:45.060
They are waiting on the shingle.

02:47:45.060 --> 02:47:48.060
Will you come and join the dance?"

02:47:48.060 --> 02:47:49.060
"Will you?

02:47:49.060 --> 02:47:50.060
Won't you?

02:47:50.060 --> 02:47:51.060
Will you?

02:47:51.060 --> 02:47:52.060
Won't you?

02:47:52.060 --> 02:47:54.060
Will you join the dance?

02:47:54.060 --> 02:47:55.060
Will you?

02:47:55.060 --> 02:47:56.060
Won't you?

02:47:56.060 --> 02:47:57.060
Won't you?

02:47:57.060 --> 02:47:58.060
Won't you?

02:47:58.060 --> 02:48:00.060
Won't you join the dance?

02:48:00.060 --> 02:48:05.060
You can really have no notion how delightful it will be.

02:48:05.060 --> 02:48:11.060
When they take us up and throw us with the lobsters out to sea.

02:48:11.060 --> 02:48:17.060
But the snail replied, too far, too far, and gave a look a-scance.

02:48:17.060 --> 02:48:23.060
Said he thanked the white-ing kindly, but he would not join the dance.

02:48:23.060 --> 02:48:29.060
Would not, could not, would not, could not, would not join the dance.

02:48:29.060 --> 02:48:35.060
Would not, could not, would not, could not, could not, could not, could not, join the dance.

02:48:35.060 --> 02:48:38.060
What matters at how far we go?"

02:48:38.060 --> 02:48:46.060
His scaly friend replied, "There is another shore you know, upon the other side.

02:48:46.060 --> 02:48:52.060
The further off from England, the nearer is two France.

02:48:52.060 --> 02:48:59.060
Then turn not pale, you love it snail, but come and join the dance.

02:48:59.060 --> 02:49:00.060
Will you?

02:49:00.060 --> 02:49:01.060
Won't you?

02:49:01.060 --> 02:49:02.060
Will you?

02:49:02.060 --> 02:49:03.060
Won't you?

02:49:03.060 --> 02:49:05.060
Will you join the dance?

02:49:05.060 --> 02:49:06.060
Will you?

02:49:06.060 --> 02:49:07.060
Won't you?

02:49:07.060 --> 02:49:08.060
Will you?

02:49:08.060 --> 02:49:09.060
Won't you?

02:49:09.060 --> 02:49:12.060
Won't you join the dance?"

02:49:12.060 --> 02:49:13.060
Thank you.

02:49:13.060 --> 02:49:17.060
It's a very interesting dance to watch.

02:49:17.060 --> 02:49:23.060
Said Alice, feeling very glad that it was over at last.

02:49:23.060 --> 02:49:28.060
"And I do so like that curious song about the waiting."

02:49:28.060 --> 02:49:32.060
"Oh, as to the waiting," said the mock turtle.

02:49:32.060 --> 02:49:36.060
"They, you've seen them, of course?"

02:49:36.060 --> 02:49:39.060
"Yes," said Alice.

02:49:39.060 --> 02:49:42.060
"I've often seen them at dinner."

02:49:42.060 --> 02:49:44.060
She checked herself hastily.

02:49:44.060 --> 02:49:49.060
"I don't know where dinner may be," said the mock turtle.

02:49:49.060 --> 02:49:54.060
"But if you've seen them so often, of course you know what they're like."

02:49:54.060 --> 02:49:59.060
"I believe so," Alice replied thoughtfully.

02:49:59.060 --> 02:50:04.060
"They have their tails in their mouths, and they're all over crumbs."

02:50:04.060 --> 02:50:09.060
"You're wrong about the crumbs," said the mock turtle.

02:50:09.060 --> 02:50:20.060
"Croms would all wash off in the sea, but they have their tails in their mouths, and the reason is."

02:50:20.060 --> 02:50:24.060
Here the mock turtle yawned and shut his eyes.

02:50:24.060 --> 02:50:29.060
"Tell her about the reason and all that," he said to the Griffin.

02:50:29.060 --> 02:50:33.060
"The reason is," said the Griffin.

02:50:33.060 --> 02:50:48.060
"That they would go with the lobsters to the dance, so they got thrown out to sea, so they had to fall a long way, so they got their tails fast in their mouths."

02:50:48.060 --> 02:50:52.060
"So they couldn't get them out again. That's all."

02:50:52.060 --> 02:50:55.060
"Thank you," said Alice.

02:50:55.060 --> 02:51:02.060
"It's very interesting. I never knew so much about a waiting before."

02:51:02.060 --> 02:51:09.060
"I can tell you more than that, if you like," said the Griffin.

02:51:09.060 --> 02:51:12.060
"Do you know why it's called a waiting?"

02:51:12.060 --> 02:51:15.060
"I never thought about it," said Alice.

02:51:15.060 --> 02:51:24.060
"Why? It does the boots and shoes," the Griffin replied very solemnly.

02:51:24.060 --> 02:51:27.060
Alice was thoroughly puzzled.

02:51:27.060 --> 02:51:33.060
"Does the boots and shoes?" she repeated in a wondering tone.

02:51:33.060 --> 02:51:38.060
"Why? What are your shoes done with?" said the Griffin.

02:51:38.060 --> 02:51:42.060
"I mean, what makes them so shiny?"

02:51:42.060 --> 02:51:48.060
Alice looked down at them and considered a little before she gave her answer.

02:51:48.060 --> 02:51:52.060
"They're done with blacking, I believe."

02:51:52.060 --> 02:51:59.060
"Boots and shoes under the sea," the Griffin went on in a deep voice.

02:51:59.060 --> 02:52:04.060
"Are done with a waiting? Now you know."

02:52:04.060 --> 02:52:11.060
"And what are they made of?" Alice asked in a tone of great curiosity.

02:52:11.060 --> 02:52:17.060
"Soles and eels, of course," the Griffin replied rather impatiently.

02:52:17.060 --> 02:52:22.060
"Any shrimp could have told you that. If I'd been the waiting,"

02:52:22.060 --> 02:52:27.060
said Alice, whose thoughts were still running on the song.

02:52:27.060 --> 02:52:34.060
"I'd have said to the porpoise, "Keep back, please. We don't want you with us."

02:52:34.060 --> 02:52:40.060
"They were obliged to have him with them," the mock turtle said.

02:52:40.060 --> 02:52:46.060
"No wise fish would go anywhere without a porpoise."

02:52:46.060 --> 02:52:52.060
"Wouldn't it really?" said Alice in a tone of great surprise.

02:52:52.060 --> 02:52:56.060
"Of course not," said the mock turtle.

02:52:56.060 --> 02:53:02.060
"Why, if a fish came to me and told me he was going on a journey,

02:53:02.060 --> 02:53:06.060
I should say, with what porpoise?"

02:53:06.060 --> 02:53:10.060
"Don't you mean, purpose?" said Alice.

02:53:10.060 --> 02:53:19.060
"I mean what I say," the mock turtle replied in an offended tone, and the Griffin added.

02:53:19.060 --> 02:53:22.060
"Come, let's hear some of your adventures."

02:53:22.060 --> 02:53:29.060
"I could tell you by adventures," beginning from this morning, said Alice a little timidly.

02:53:29.060 --> 02:53:33.060
"But it's no use going back to yesterday."

02:53:33.060 --> 02:53:36.060
"Because I was a different person, then."

02:53:36.060 --> 02:53:41.060
"Explain all that," said the mock turtle.

02:53:41.060 --> 02:53:48.060
"No, no, the adventures first," said the Griffin in an impatient tone.

02:53:48.060 --> 02:53:52.060
"Explinations take such a dreadful time."

02:53:52.060 --> 02:53:59.060
So Alice began telling them her adventures from the time when she first saw the white rabbit.

02:53:59.060 --> 02:54:03.060
She was a little nervous about it just at first.

02:54:03.060 --> 02:54:08.060
"The two creatures got so close to her, one on each side,

02:54:08.060 --> 02:54:13.060
and opened their eyes and mouths so very wide,

02:54:13.060 --> 02:54:17.060
but she gained courage as she went on.

02:54:17.060 --> 02:54:23.060
Her listeners were perfectly quiet until she got to the part about her repeating,

02:54:23.060 --> 02:54:27.060
"You are old, Father William, to the caterpillar."

02:54:27.060 --> 02:54:30.060
And the words all coming different.

02:54:30.060 --> 02:54:35.060
And then the mock turtle drew a long breath, and said,

02:54:35.060 --> 02:54:39.060
"That's very curious."

02:54:39.060 --> 02:54:45.060
"It's all about as curious as it can be," said the Griffin.

02:54:45.060 --> 02:54:50.060
"It all came different," the mock turtle repeated thoughtfully.

02:54:50.060 --> 02:54:55.060
"I should like to hear her try and repeat something now.

02:54:55.060 --> 02:54:57.060
Tell her to begin."

02:54:57.060 --> 02:55:04.060
He looked at the Griffin as if he thought it had some kind of authority over Alice.

02:55:04.060 --> 02:55:06.060
"Stand up and repeat.

02:55:06.060 --> 02:55:10.060
Tis the voice of the sluggard," said the Griffin.

02:55:10.060 --> 02:55:18.060
"How the creatures order one about and make one repeat lessons," thought Alice.

02:55:18.060 --> 02:55:22.060
"I might as well be at school at once."

02:55:22.060 --> 02:55:27.060
However, she got up and began to repeat it.

02:55:27.060 --> 02:55:36.060
But her head was so full of the lobster quadrill that she hardly knew what she was saying.

02:55:36.060 --> 02:55:40.060
And the words came very queer indeed.

02:55:40.060 --> 02:55:43.060
"Tis the voice of the lobster.

02:55:43.060 --> 02:55:45.060
I heard him declare."

02:55:45.060 --> 02:55:47.060
"You have baked me too brown.

02:55:47.060 --> 02:55:50.060
I must sugar my hair."

02:55:50.060 --> 02:55:55.060
"As a duck with its eyelids, so he with his nose.

02:55:55.060 --> 02:56:01.060
Trims his belt and his buttons, and turns out his toes."

02:56:01.060 --> 02:56:05.060
Later additions continued as follows.

02:56:05.060 --> 02:56:16.060
"When the sands are all dry, he is gay as a lark, and will talk in contemptuous tones of the shark.

02:56:16.060 --> 02:56:26.060
But when the tide rises, and sharks are around, his voice has a timid and tremulous sound."

02:56:26.060 --> 02:56:34.060
"That's different from what I used to say when I was a child," said the Griffin.

02:56:34.060 --> 02:56:40.060
"Well, I never heard it before," said the mock turtle.

02:56:40.060 --> 02:56:46.060
"But it sounds uncommon nonsense," Alice said nothing.

02:56:46.060 --> 02:56:56.060
She had sat down with her face in her hands, wondering if anything would ever happen in a natural way again.

02:56:56.060 --> 02:57:01.060
"I should like to have it explained," said the mock turtle.

02:57:01.060 --> 02:57:05.060
"She can't explain it," said the Griffin hastily.

02:57:05.060 --> 02:57:08.060
"Go on with the next verse."

02:57:08.060 --> 02:57:13.060
"The mock turtle persisted.

02:57:13.060 --> 02:57:18.060
How could he turn them out with his nose, you know?"

02:57:18.060 --> 02:57:29.060
"It's the first position in dancing," Alice said, but was dreadfully puzzled by the whole thing, and longed to change the subject.

02:57:29.060 --> 02:57:35.060
"Go on with the next verse," the Griffin repeated impatiently.

02:57:35.060 --> 02:57:39.060
"It begins, I passed by his garden."

02:57:39.060 --> 02:57:49.060
Alice did not dare to disobey, though she felt sure it would all come wrong, and she went on in a trembling voice.

02:57:49.060 --> 02:57:54.060
"I passed by his garden, and marked with one eye.

02:57:54.060 --> 02:57:59.060
How the owl and the panther were sharing a pie."

02:57:59.060 --> 02:58:03.060
Later additions continued as follows.

02:58:03.060 --> 02:58:13.060
The panther took pie crust and gravy and meat, while the owl had to dish as its share of the treat.

02:58:13.060 --> 02:58:22.060
When the pie was all finished, the owl as a boon was kindly permitted to pocket the spoon.

02:58:22.060 --> 02:58:30.060
While the panther received knife and fork with a growl and concluded the banquet.

02:58:30.060 --> 02:58:36.060
"What is the use of repeating all that stuff?" the mock turtle interrupted.

02:58:36.060 --> 02:58:46.060
"If you don't explain it as you go on, it's by far the most confusing thing I ever heard."

02:58:46.060 --> 02:58:55.060
"Yes, I think you'd better leave off," said the Griffin, and Alice was only too glad to do so.

02:58:55.060 --> 02:59:02.060
"Show, we try another figure of the lobster quadrill?" the Griffin went on.

02:59:02.060 --> 02:59:06.060
"Or would you like the mock turtle to sing you a song?"

02:59:06.060 --> 02:59:11.060
"Oh, a song, please. If the mock turtle would be so kind."

02:59:11.060 --> 02:59:18.060
Alice replied, so eagerly that the Griffin said in a rather offended tone.

02:59:18.060 --> 02:59:21.060
"Hmm, no accounting for tastes."

02:59:21.060 --> 02:59:25.060
"Sing her turtle soup, will you, old fellow?"

02:59:25.060 --> 02:59:28.060
"The mock turtle sighed deeply."

02:59:28.060 --> 02:59:34.060
"And began in a voice sometimes choked with sobs to sing this."

02:59:34.060 --> 02:59:39.060
"Beautiful soup, so rich and green."

02:59:39.060 --> 02:59:46.060
"Waiting in a hot terrain. Who, for such dinkies, would not stoop?"

02:59:46.060 --> 02:59:51.060
"Soup of the evening, beautiful soup."

02:59:51.060 --> 02:59:55.060
"Soup of the evening, beautiful soup."

02:59:55.060 --> 03:00:01.060
"Beautiful soup, beautiful soup."

03:00:01.060 --> 03:00:13.060
"Soup of the evening, beautiful, beautiful soup."

03:00:13.060 --> 03:00:18.060
"Who cares for fish, game, or any other dish?"

03:00:18.060 --> 03:00:21.060
"Who would not give all else?"

03:00:21.060 --> 03:00:27.060
"For two put any worth only, a beautiful soup."

03:00:27.060 --> 03:00:30.060
"Penny worth only, a beautiful soup?"

03:00:30.060 --> 03:00:39.060
"Beautiful soup, beautiful soup."

03:00:39.060 --> 03:00:51.060
"Soup of the evening, beautiful, beautiful soup."

03:00:51.060 --> 03:00:58.060
"Course again," cried the Griffin, and the mock turtle had just begun to repeat it,

03:00:58.060 --> 03:01:02.060
when a cry of the trials beginning.

03:01:02.060 --> 03:01:07.060
"Was heard in the distance. Come on," cried the Griffin,

03:01:07.060 --> 03:01:14.060
and, taking Alice by the hand, it hurried off without waiting for the end of the song.

03:01:14.060 --> 03:01:16.060
"What trial is it?"

03:01:16.060 --> 03:01:22.060
Alice panted as she ran, but the Griffin only answered, "Come on!"

03:01:22.060 --> 03:01:27.060
And ran the faster, while more and more faintly came,

03:01:27.060 --> 03:01:32.060
carried on the breeze that followed them, the melancholy words.

03:01:32.060 --> 03:01:42.060
"Soup of the evening, beautiful, beautiful soup."

03:01:42.060 --> 03:02:07.060
CHAPTER XI

03:02:07.060 --> 03:02:12.060
The king and queen of hearts were seated on their throne when they arrived,

03:02:12.060 --> 03:02:18.060
with a great crowd assembled about them, all sorts of little birds and beasts,

03:02:18.060 --> 03:02:21.060
as well as the whole pack of carts.

03:02:21.060 --> 03:02:27.060
The nave was standing before them in chains, with a soldier on each side to guard them.

03:02:27.060 --> 03:02:32.060
And near the king was the white rabbit, with a trumpet in one hand,

03:02:32.060 --> 03:02:36.060
and a scroll of parchment in the other.

03:02:36.060 --> 03:02:42.060
In the very middle of the court was a table, with a large dish of tarts upon it.

03:02:42.060 --> 03:02:47.060
They looked so good that it made Alice quite hungry to look at them.

03:02:47.060 --> 03:02:54.060
"I wish they'd get the trial done," she thought, and hand-round the refreshments.

03:02:54.060 --> 03:03:02.060
But there seemed to be no chance of this, so she began looking at everything about her, to pass away the time.

03:03:02.060 --> 03:03:08.060
Alice had never been in a court of justice before, but she had read about them in books,

03:03:08.060 --> 03:03:14.060
and she was quite pleased to find that she knew the name of nearly everything there.

03:03:14.060 --> 03:03:18.060
"That's the judge," she said to herself.

03:03:18.060 --> 03:03:24.060
"Because of his great wig," the judge, by the way, was the king,

03:03:24.060 --> 03:03:33.060
and as he wore his crown over the wig, look at the frontest piece, if you want to see how he did it.

03:03:33.060 --> 03:03:39.060
He did not look at all comfortable, and it was certainly not becoming.

03:03:39.060 --> 03:03:43.060
"And that's the jury box," thought Alice.

03:03:43.060 --> 03:03:50.060
"And those twelve creatures," she was obliged to say, "creatures," you see,

03:03:50.060 --> 03:03:55.060
"because some of them were animals, and some were birds."

03:03:55.060 --> 03:03:58.060
"I suppose they are the jurors."

03:03:58.060 --> 03:04:04.060
She said this last word two or three times over to herself, being rather proud of it,

03:04:04.060 --> 03:04:07.060
for she thought, and rightly too.

03:04:07.060 --> 03:04:12.060
That very few little girls of her age knew the meaning of it at all.

03:04:12.060 --> 03:04:16.060
However, jury men would have done chess as well.

03:04:16.060 --> 03:04:22.060
The twelve jurors were all writing very busily on slates.

03:04:22.060 --> 03:04:25.060
"What are they doing?" Alice whispered to the Griffin.

03:04:25.060 --> 03:04:30.060
"They can't have anything to put down yet before the trials began.

03:04:30.060 --> 03:04:35.060
They're putting down their names," the Griffin whispered in reply.

03:04:35.060 --> 03:04:40.060
"For fear they should forget them before the end of the trial.

03:04:40.060 --> 03:04:46.060
Stupid things!" Alice began in a loud, indignant voice,

03:04:46.060 --> 03:04:51.060
but she stopped hastily for the white rabbit cried out.

03:04:51.060 --> 03:04:53.060
"Silence in the court!"

03:04:53.060 --> 03:05:00.060
"And the king put on his spectacles and looked anxiously round to make out who was talking.

03:05:00.060 --> 03:05:06.060
Alice could see, as well as if she were looking over their shoulders,

03:05:06.060 --> 03:05:12.060
that all the jurors were writing down, stupid things, on their slates,

03:05:12.060 --> 03:05:18.060
and she could even make out that one of them didn't know how to spell stupid,

03:05:18.060 --> 03:05:22.060
and that he had to ask his neighbor to tell him.

03:05:22.060 --> 03:05:26.060
"A nice muddle their slates will be in before the trials over!"

03:05:26.060 --> 03:05:31.060
"Thought Alice, one of the jurors had a pencil that squeaked.

03:05:31.060 --> 03:05:36.060
This, of course, Alice could not stand,

03:05:36.060 --> 03:05:41.060
and she went round the court and got behind him,

03:05:41.060 --> 03:05:46.060
and very soon found an opportunity of taking it away.

03:05:46.060 --> 03:05:53.060
She did it so quickly that the poor little juror, it was Bill, the lizard,

03:05:53.060 --> 03:05:58.060
could not make out at all what had become of it,

03:05:58.060 --> 03:06:02.060
so, after hunting all about for it,

03:06:02.060 --> 03:06:08.060
he was obliged to write with one finger for the rest of the day,

03:06:08.060 --> 03:06:14.060
and this was of very little use, as it left no mark on the slate.

03:06:14.060 --> 03:06:19.060
"Harold, read the accusation," said the king.

03:06:19.060 --> 03:06:23.060
"On this, the white rabbit blew three blasts on the trumpet,

03:06:23.060 --> 03:06:28.060
and then unrolled the parchment's scroll, and read, as follows.

03:06:28.060 --> 03:06:33.060
"The queen of hearts!" she made some tarts, all on a summer day.

03:06:33.060 --> 03:06:39.060
The nave of hearts!" he stole the tarts, and took them quite away.

03:06:39.060 --> 03:06:43.060
"Consider your verdict," the king said to the jury.

03:06:43.060 --> 03:06:48.060
"Not yet, not yet!" the rabbit hastily interrupted.

03:06:48.060 --> 03:06:52.060
"There's a great deal to come before that!"

03:06:52.060 --> 03:06:56.060
"Call the first witness," said the king,

03:06:56.060 --> 03:07:00.060
and the white rabbit blew three blasts on the trumpet,

03:07:00.060 --> 03:07:03.060
and called out, "First witness!"

03:07:03.060 --> 03:07:06.060
The first witness was the hatter.

03:07:06.060 --> 03:07:09.060
He came in with a teacup in one hand,

03:07:09.060 --> 03:07:12.060
and a piece of bread and butter in the other.

03:07:12.060 --> 03:07:16.060
"I beg pardon your majesty," he began,

03:07:16.060 --> 03:07:19.060
"for bringing these in,

03:07:19.060 --> 03:07:24.060
but I hadn't quite finished my tea when I was sent for.

03:07:24.060 --> 03:07:27.060
"You ought to have finished," said the king.

03:07:27.060 --> 03:07:30.060
"When did you begin?"

03:07:30.060 --> 03:07:32.060
The hatter looked at the march-hair,

03:07:32.060 --> 03:07:34.060
who had followed him into the court,

03:07:34.060 --> 03:07:37.060
arm in arm with the doormouse.

03:07:37.060 --> 03:07:43.060
"Fourteenths of march, I think it was," he said.

03:07:43.060 --> 03:07:50.060
" Fifteenth," said the march-hair. "Sixteenth," added the doormouse.

03:07:50.060 --> 03:07:54.060
"Right that down," the king said to the jury,

03:07:54.060 --> 03:07:59.060
and the jury eagerly wrote down all three dates on their sleighths,

03:07:59.060 --> 03:08:01.060
and then added them up,

03:08:01.060 --> 03:08:04.060
and reduced the answer to shillings and pence.

03:08:04.060 --> 03:08:08.060
"Take off your hat," the king said to the hatter.

03:08:08.060 --> 03:08:12.060
"It isn't mine," said the hatter.

03:08:12.060 --> 03:08:15.060
"Stolen!" the king exclaimed,

03:08:15.060 --> 03:08:17.060
turning to the jury,

03:08:17.060 --> 03:08:21.060
who instantly made a memorandum of the fact.

03:08:21.060 --> 03:08:27.060
"I keep them to sell," the hatter added as an explanation.

03:08:27.060 --> 03:08:31.060
"I've none of my own. I'm a hatter."

03:08:31.060 --> 03:08:35.060
Here, the queen put on her spectacles,

03:08:35.060 --> 03:08:38.060
and began staring at the hatter,

03:08:38.060 --> 03:08:40.060
who turned pale and fidgeted.

03:08:40.060 --> 03:08:44.060
"Give your evidence," said the king,

03:08:44.060 --> 03:08:46.060
"and don't be nervous,

03:08:46.060 --> 03:08:49.060
or I'll have you executed on the spot."

03:08:49.060 --> 03:08:54.060
This did not seem to encourage the witness at all.

03:08:54.060 --> 03:08:58.060
He kept shifting from one foot to the other,

03:08:58.060 --> 03:09:01.060
looking uneasily at the queen,

03:09:01.060 --> 03:09:06.060
and in his confusion he bit a large piece out of his teacup

03:09:06.060 --> 03:09:09.060
instead of the bread and butter.

03:09:09.060 --> 03:09:14.060
Chest at this moment, Alice felt a very curious sensation,

03:09:14.060 --> 03:09:17.060
which puzzled her a good deal,

03:09:17.060 --> 03:09:20.060
until she made out what it was.

03:09:20.060 --> 03:09:23.060
She was beginning to grow larger again,

03:09:23.060 --> 03:09:29.060
and she thought at first she would get up and leave the court.

03:09:29.060 --> 03:09:31.060
But on second thoughts,

03:09:31.060 --> 03:09:34.060
she decided to remain where she was,

03:09:34.060 --> 03:09:37.060
as long as there was room for her.

03:09:37.060 --> 03:09:42.060
"I wish you wouldn't squeeze so," said the doormouse,

03:09:42.060 --> 03:09:44.060
who was sitting next to her.

03:09:44.060 --> 03:09:46.060
"I can hardly breathe.

03:09:46.060 --> 03:09:50.060
I can't help it," said Alice very meekly.

03:09:50.060 --> 03:09:52.060
"I'm growing.

03:09:52.060 --> 03:09:57.060
You've no right to grow here," said the doormouse.

03:09:57.060 --> 03:10:02.060
"Don't talk nonsense," said Alice more boldly.

03:10:02.060 --> 03:10:07.060
"You know, you're growing, too?"

03:10:07.060 --> 03:10:12.060
"Yes, but I grow at a reasonable pace," said the doormouse.

03:10:12.060 --> 03:10:15.060
"Not in that ridiculous fashion."

03:10:15.060 --> 03:10:18.060
And he got up very soakily,

03:10:18.060 --> 03:10:22.060
and crossed over to the other side of the court.

03:10:22.060 --> 03:10:29.060
All this time, the queen had never left off staring at the hatter,

03:10:29.060 --> 03:10:34.060
and chest as the doormouse crossed the court.

03:10:34.060 --> 03:10:39.060
She said to one of the officers of the court,

03:10:39.060 --> 03:10:43.060
"Bring me the list of the singers in the last concert,"

03:10:43.060 --> 03:10:50.060
on which the wretched hatter trembled so that he shook both his shoes off.

03:10:50.060 --> 03:10:54.060
"Give your evidence," the king repeated angrily.

03:10:54.060 --> 03:10:57.060
"Or I'll have you executed,

03:10:57.060 --> 03:11:00.060
whether you're nervous or not."

03:11:00.060 --> 03:11:03.060
"I'm a poor man," your majesty,

03:11:03.060 --> 03:11:06.060
the hatter began in a trembling voice,

03:11:06.060 --> 03:11:09.060
and I hadn't begun my tea,

03:11:09.060 --> 03:11:11.060
not above a week or so,

03:11:11.060 --> 03:11:16.060
and what with the bread and butter getting so thin,

03:11:16.060 --> 03:11:19.060
and the twinkling of the tea,

03:11:19.060 --> 03:11:21.060
the twinkling of the what,

03:11:21.060 --> 03:11:22.060
said the king.

03:11:22.060 --> 03:11:27.060
"It began with the tea," the hatter replied.

03:11:27.060 --> 03:11:32.060
"Of course twinkling begins with a tea," said the king sharply.

03:11:32.060 --> 03:11:34.060
"Do you take me for a dunce?"

03:11:34.060 --> 03:11:36.060
"Go on."

03:11:36.060 --> 03:11:39.060
"I'm a poor man," the hatter went on,

03:11:39.060 --> 03:11:43.060
and most things twinkled after that.

03:11:43.060 --> 03:11:45.060
"Only the March hair," said,

03:11:45.060 --> 03:11:50.060
"I didn't," the March hair interrupted in a great hurry.

03:11:50.060 --> 03:11:53.060
"You did," said the hatter.

03:11:53.060 --> 03:11:56.060
"I deny it," said the March hair.

03:11:56.060 --> 03:11:59.060
"He denies it," said the king.

03:11:59.060 --> 03:12:01.060
"Leave out that part."

03:12:01.060 --> 03:12:05.060
"Well, at any rate," the door-mouse said.

03:12:05.060 --> 03:12:08.060
The hatter went on,

03:12:08.060 --> 03:12:13.060
looking anxiously round to see if he would deny it too,

03:12:13.060 --> 03:12:16.060
but the door-mouse denied nothing,

03:12:16.060 --> 03:12:19.060
being fast asleep.

03:12:19.060 --> 03:12:22.060
After that, continued the hatter.

03:12:22.060 --> 03:12:25.060
"I kept some more bread and butter.

03:12:25.060 --> 03:12:28.060
But what did the door-mouse say?"

03:12:28.060 --> 03:12:30.060
"One of the jury asked."

03:12:30.060 --> 03:12:34.060
"That, I can't remember," said the hatter.

03:12:34.060 --> 03:12:39.060
"You must remember," remarked the king.

03:12:39.060 --> 03:12:42.060
"Or I'll have you executed."

03:12:42.060 --> 03:12:46.060
The miserable hatter dropped his tea cup

03:12:46.060 --> 03:12:50.060
and bread and butter, and went down on one knee.

03:12:50.060 --> 03:12:53.060
"I'm a poor man, your majesty."

03:12:53.060 --> 03:13:00.060
He began, "You're a very poor speaker," said the king.

03:13:00.060 --> 03:13:03.060
Here, one of the guinea pigs cheered,

03:13:03.060 --> 03:13:09.060
and was immediately suppressed by the officers of the court.

03:13:09.060 --> 03:13:11.060
"As that is rather a hard word,

03:13:11.060 --> 03:13:15.060
I will just explain to you how it was done."

03:13:15.060 --> 03:13:18.060
They had a large canvas bag,

03:13:18.060 --> 03:13:21.060
which tied up at the mouth with strings.

03:13:21.060 --> 03:13:24.060
Into this, they slipped the guinea pig,

03:13:24.060 --> 03:13:28.060
head first, and then sat upon it.

03:13:28.060 --> 03:13:32.060
"I'm glad I've seen that done," thought Alice.

03:13:32.060 --> 03:13:36.060
"I've so often read in the newspapers.

03:13:36.060 --> 03:13:38.060
At the end of trials,

03:13:38.060 --> 03:13:42.060
there was some attempts at applause,

03:13:42.060 --> 03:13:47.060
which was immediately suppressed by the officers of the court.

03:13:47.060 --> 03:13:51.060
And I never understood what it meant till now."

03:13:51.060 --> 03:13:54.060
"If that's all you know about it,

03:13:54.060 --> 03:13:56.060
you may stand down."

03:13:56.060 --> 03:13:58.060
"Continue the king."

03:13:58.060 --> 03:14:02.060
"I can't go no lower," said the hatter.

03:14:02.060 --> 03:14:05.060
"I'm on the floor, as it is."

03:14:05.060 --> 03:14:10.060
"Then you may sit down," the king replied.

03:14:10.060 --> 03:14:13.060
Here the other guinea pig cheered,

03:14:13.060 --> 03:14:15.060
and was suppressed.

03:14:15.060 --> 03:14:19.060
"Come, that finished the guinea pigs," thought Alice.

03:14:19.060 --> 03:14:22.060
"Now we shall get on better."

03:14:22.060 --> 03:14:27.060
"I'd rather finish my tea," said the hatter,

03:14:27.060 --> 03:14:30.060
with an anxious look at the queen,

03:14:30.060 --> 03:14:33.060
who was reading the list of singers.

03:14:33.060 --> 03:14:36.060
"You may go," said the king,

03:14:36.060 --> 03:14:39.060
and the hatter hurriedly left the court.

03:14:39.060 --> 03:14:43.060
Without even waiting to put his shoes on,

03:14:43.060 --> 03:14:46.060
and just take his head off outside.

03:14:46.060 --> 03:14:50.060
The queen added to one of the officers.

03:14:50.060 --> 03:14:56.060
But the hatter was out of sight before the officer could get to the door.

03:14:56.060 --> 03:14:59.060
"Call the next witness," said the king.

03:14:59.060 --> 03:15:03.060
The next witness was the Duchess's cook.

03:15:03.060 --> 03:15:06.060
She carried the pepper box in her hand,

03:15:06.060 --> 03:15:09.060
and Alice guessed who it was,

03:15:09.060 --> 03:15:12.060
even before she got into the court,

03:15:12.060 --> 03:15:17.060
by the way the people near the door began sneezing all at once.

03:15:17.060 --> 03:15:20.060
"Give your evidence," said the king.

03:15:20.060 --> 03:15:22.060
"Shant," said the cook.

03:15:22.060 --> 03:15:25.060
The king looked anxiously at the white rabbit,

03:15:25.060 --> 03:15:28.060
who said in a low voice,

03:15:28.060 --> 03:15:33.060
"Your majesty must cross-examine this witness."

03:15:33.060 --> 03:15:37.060
"Well, if I must," I must.

03:15:37.060 --> 03:15:40.060
The king said with a melancholy air,

03:15:40.060 --> 03:15:45.060
and, after folding his arms and frowning at the cook,

03:15:45.060 --> 03:15:48.060
till his eyes were nearly out of sight,

03:15:48.060 --> 03:15:51.060
he said in a deep voice,

03:15:51.060 --> 03:15:54.060
"What are tarts made of?"

03:15:54.060 --> 03:15:57.060
"Papper," mostly, said the cook.

03:15:57.060 --> 03:16:01.060
"Tricle," said a sleepy voice behind her.

03:16:01.060 --> 03:16:06.060
"Call her that door-mouse," the queen shrieked out.

03:16:06.060 --> 03:16:08.060
"Behead that door-mouse."

03:16:08.060 --> 03:16:10.060
"Turn that door-mouse out of court!"

03:16:10.060 --> 03:16:13.060
"Suppress him! pinch him!"

03:16:13.060 --> 03:16:15.060
"Off with his whiskers!"

03:16:15.060 --> 03:16:19.060
"For some minutes the whole court was in confusion,

03:16:19.060 --> 03:16:22.060
getting the door-mouse turned out,

03:16:22.060 --> 03:16:26.060
and, by the time they had settled down again,

03:16:26.060 --> 03:16:29.060
the cook had disappeared.

03:16:29.060 --> 03:16:32.060
"Never mind," said the king,

03:16:32.060 --> 03:16:35.060
with an air of great relief.

03:16:35.060 --> 03:16:37.060
"Call your next witness,"

03:16:37.060 --> 03:16:40.060
and he added in an undertone to the queen.

03:16:40.060 --> 03:16:43.060
"Really, my dear.

03:16:43.060 --> 03:16:47.060
You must cross-examine the next witness.

03:16:47.060 --> 03:16:51.060
It quite makes my forehead ache."

03:16:51.060 --> 03:16:55.060
Alice watched the white rabbit as he fumbled over the list,

03:16:55.060 --> 03:17:01.060
feeling very curious to see what the next witness would be like.

03:17:01.060 --> 03:17:06.060
"For they haven't got much evidence yet," she said to herself.

03:17:06.060 --> 03:17:11.060
"Imagine her surprise when the white rabbit read out

03:17:11.060 --> 03:17:16.060
at the top of his shrill little voice, the name Alice."

03:17:16.060 --> 03:17:25.060
CHAPTER XII

03:17:25.060 --> 03:17:27.060
CHAPTER XII

03:17:27.060 --> 03:17:30.060
Of Alice's Adventures in Wonderland

03:17:30.060 --> 03:17:32.060
By Lewis Carroll

03:17:32.060 --> 03:17:36.060
This liberal box recording is in the public domain.

03:17:36.060 --> 03:17:39.060
CHAPTER XII

03:17:39.060 --> 03:17:41.060
Alice's evidence

03:17:41.060 --> 03:17:46.060
Here, pride Alice, quite forgetting in the flurry of the moment,

03:17:46.060 --> 03:17:50.060
how large she had grown in the last few minutes,

03:17:50.060 --> 03:17:56.060
and she jumped up in such a hurry that she tipped over the jury box

03:17:56.060 --> 03:17:59.060
with the edge of her skirt,

03:17:59.060 --> 03:18:04.060
upsetting all the juriman onto the heads of the crowd below,

03:18:04.060 --> 03:18:07.060
and there they lay sprawling about,

03:18:07.060 --> 03:18:12.060
reminding her, very much, of a globe of goldfish,

03:18:12.060 --> 03:18:16.060
she had accidentally upset the week before.

03:18:16.060 --> 03:18:19.060
"Oh, I beg your pardon?"

03:18:19.060 --> 03:18:23.060
She exclaimed in a tone of great dismay,

03:18:23.060 --> 03:18:28.060
and began picking them up again as quickly as she could,

03:18:28.060 --> 03:18:33.060
for the accident of the goldfish kept running in her head,

03:18:33.060 --> 03:18:39.060
and she had a vague sort of idea that they must be collected at once

03:18:39.060 --> 03:18:45.060
and put back into the jury box, or they would die.

03:18:45.060 --> 03:18:51.060
The trial cannot proceed, said the king in a very grave voice,

03:18:51.060 --> 03:18:57.060
until all the juriman are back in their proper places, all.

03:18:57.060 --> 03:19:03.060
She repeated with great emphasis, looking hard at Alice as he said so.

03:19:03.060 --> 03:19:08.060
Alice looked at the jury box, and saw that in her haste,

03:19:08.060 --> 03:19:11.060
she had put the lizard in head downwards,

03:19:11.060 --> 03:19:18.060
and the poor little thing was waving its tail about in a melancholy way,

03:19:18.060 --> 03:19:21.060
being quite unable to move.

03:19:21.060 --> 03:19:25.060
She soon got it out again, and put it right.

03:19:25.060 --> 03:19:29.060
"Not that it signifies much," she said to herself.

03:19:29.060 --> 03:19:35.060
"I should think it would be quite as much use in the trial one way up as the other."

03:19:35.060 --> 03:19:42.060
As soon as the jury had a little recovered from the shock of being upset,

03:19:42.060 --> 03:19:47.060
and their sleights and pencils had been found and handed back to them,

03:19:47.060 --> 03:19:54.060
they set to work very diligently to write out a history of the accident,

03:19:54.060 --> 03:20:03.060
all except the lizard, who seemed too much overcome to do anything but sit with its mouth open,

03:20:03.060 --> 03:20:06.060
gazing up into the roof of the court.

03:20:06.060 --> 03:20:12.060
"What do you know about this business?" the king said to Alice.

03:20:12.060 --> 03:20:19.060
"Nothing," said Alice. "Nothing whatever," persisted the king.

03:20:19.060 --> 03:20:22.060
"Nothing whatever," said Alice.

03:20:22.060 --> 03:20:28.060
"That's very important," the king said, turning to the jury.

03:20:28.060 --> 03:20:33.060
"They were just beginning to write this down on their sleights,"

03:20:33.060 --> 03:20:35.060
when the white rabbit interrupted.

03:20:35.060 --> 03:20:43.060
"Unimportant, your majesty means, of course," he said in a very respectful tone,

03:20:43.060 --> 03:20:48.060
but frowning and making faces at him as he spoke.

03:20:48.060 --> 03:20:52.060
"Unimportant, of course," I meant.

03:20:52.060 --> 03:20:57.060
The king hastily said and went on to himself in an undertone.

03:20:57.060 --> 03:21:08.060
" Important, unimportant, unimportant, unimportant, important, as if he were trying which word sounded best."

03:21:08.060 --> 03:21:14.060
Some of the jury wrote it down, "important, and some unimportant."

03:21:14.060 --> 03:21:20.060
Alice could see this, as she was near enough to look over their sleights.

03:21:20.060 --> 03:21:24.060
"But it doesn't matter a bit," she thought to herself.

03:21:24.060 --> 03:21:31.060
At this moment, the king, who had been for some time busily writing in his notebook,

03:21:31.060 --> 03:21:37.060
cackled out, silence, and read out from his book.

03:21:37.060 --> 03:21:46.060
Rule 42, all persons more than a mile high to leave the court.

03:21:46.060 --> 03:21:49.060
"Everybody looked at Alice."

03:21:49.060 --> 03:21:54.060
"I'm not a mile high," said Alice.

03:21:54.060 --> 03:21:56.060
"You are," said the king.

03:21:56.060 --> 03:22:08.060
"Nearly two miles high," added the queen.

03:22:08.060 --> 03:22:13.060
"Well, I should go at any rate," said Alice.

03:22:13.060 --> 03:22:19.060
"Besides, that's not a regular rule. You invented it just now."

03:22:19.060 --> 03:22:24.060
"It's the oldest rule in the book," said the king.

03:22:24.060 --> 03:22:26.060
She shut his notebook hastily.

03:22:26.060 --> 03:22:33.060
"Consider your verdict," he said to the jury in a low, trembling voice.

03:22:33.060 --> 03:22:39.060
"There's more evidence to come yet, please, your Majesty," said the white rabbit,

03:22:39.060 --> 03:22:42.060
jumping up in a great hurry.

03:22:42.060 --> 03:22:45.060
"This paper has just been picked up."

03:22:45.060 --> 03:22:49.060
"What in it?" said the queen.

03:22:49.060 --> 03:22:52.060
"I haven't opened it yet," said the white rabbit.

03:22:52.060 --> 03:22:58.060
"But it seems to be a letter written by the prisoner to somebody."

03:22:58.060 --> 03:23:03.060
"It must have been that," said the king.

03:23:03.060 --> 03:23:08.060
"Unless it was written to nobody, which isn't usual, you know."

03:23:08.060 --> 03:23:13.060
"Who is it directed to?" said one of the jurymen.

03:23:13.060 --> 03:23:18.060
"It isn't directed at all," said the white rabbit.

03:23:18.060 --> 03:23:26.060
"In fact, there's nothing written on the outside," he unfolded the letter as he spoke and added.

03:23:26.060 --> 03:23:31.060
"It isn't a letter after all. It's a set of verses."

03:23:31.060 --> 03:23:37.060
"Are they in the prisoner's handwriting?" asked another of the jurymen.

03:23:37.060 --> 03:23:41.060
"No, they're not," said the white rabbit.

03:23:41.060 --> 03:23:45.060
"And that's the queerest thing about it."

03:23:45.060 --> 03:23:48.060
"The jury all looked puzzled."

03:23:48.060 --> 03:23:53.060
"He must have imitated somebody else's hand," said the king.

03:23:53.060 --> 03:23:56.060
"The jury all brightened up again."

03:23:56.060 --> 03:24:00.060
"Please, your Majesty," said the nave.

03:24:00.060 --> 03:24:06.060
"I didn't write it, and they can't prove I did. There's no name signed at the end."

03:24:06.060 --> 03:24:16.060
"If you didn't sign it," said the king. "That only makes the matter worse. You must have meant some mischief.

03:24:16.060 --> 03:24:25.060
Or else you'd have signed your name, like an honest man. There was a general clapping of hands at this."

03:24:25.060 --> 03:24:31.060
"It was the first really clever thing," the king had said that day.

03:24:31.060 --> 03:24:35.060
"That proves his guilt," said the queen.

03:24:35.060 --> 03:24:40.060
"It proves nothing of the sort," said Alice.

03:24:40.060 --> 03:24:44.060
"Why, you don't even know what they're about."

03:24:44.060 --> 03:24:47.060
"Read them," said the king.

03:24:47.060 --> 03:24:50.060
The white rabbit put on his spectacles.

03:24:50.060 --> 03:24:54.060
"Where shall I begin? Please, your Majesty," he asked.

03:24:54.060 --> 03:24:59.060
"Begin at the beginning," the king said gravely.

03:24:59.060 --> 03:25:05.060
"And go on till you come to the end. Then stop."

03:25:05.060 --> 03:25:09.060
"These were the verses," the white rabbit read.

03:25:09.060 --> 03:25:14.060
"They told me you had been to her, and mentioned me to him."

03:25:14.060 --> 03:25:23.060
"She gave me a good character, but said I could not swim. He sent them word I had not gone."

03:25:23.060 --> 03:25:31.060
"We know it to be true. If she should push the matter on, what would become of you?"

03:25:31.060 --> 03:25:44.060
"I gave her one. They gave him two. You gave us three or more. They all returned from him to you, though they were mine before."

03:25:44.060 --> 03:25:57.060
"If I or she should chance to be involved in this affair, he trusts to you to set them free exactly as we were."

03:25:57.060 --> 03:26:11.060
"My notion was that you had been before she had this fit. An obstacle that came between him and ourselves and it."

03:26:11.060 --> 03:26:23.060
"Don't let him know she liked them best. For this must ever be a secret kept from all the rest between yourself and me."

03:26:23.060 --> 03:26:31.060
"That's the most important piece of evidence we've heard yet," said the king, rubbing his hands.

03:26:31.060 --> 03:26:48.060
"So now, let the jury, if any one of them can explain it," said Alice. She had grown so large in the last few minutes that she wasn't a bit afraid of interrupting him.

03:26:48.060 --> 03:26:55.060
"I'll give him six pence. I don't believe there's an atom of meaning in it."

03:26:55.060 --> 03:27:06.060
"The jury all wrote down on their sleights. She doesn't believe there's an atom of meaning in it, but none of them attempted to explain the paper.

03:27:06.060 --> 03:27:24.060
"If there's no meaning in it," said the king, "that saves a world of trouble, you know, as we needn't try to find any. And yet I don't know," he went on, spreading out the verses on his knee and looking at them with one eye.

03:27:24.060 --> 03:27:38.060
"I seem to see some meaning in them, after all," said I could not swim. "You can't swim. Can you?" he added, turning to the nave.

03:27:38.060 --> 03:27:51.060
"The nave shook his head sadly. Do I look like it?" he said, which he certainly did not, being made entirely of cardboard.

03:27:51.060 --> 03:28:02.060
"All right, so far," said the king, and he went on muttering over the verses to himself. "We know it to be true."

03:28:02.060 --> 03:28:05.060
"That's the jury, of course."

03:28:05.060 --> 03:28:14.060
"I gave her one. They gave him two. Why, that must be what he did with the tarts, you know."

03:28:14.060 --> 03:28:21.060
"But it goes on. They all returned from him to you," said Alice.

03:28:21.060 --> 03:28:28.060
"Why, there they are," said the king triumphantly, pointing to the tarts on the table.

03:28:28.060 --> 03:28:41.060
"Nothing can be clearer than that. Then again, before she had this fit, you never had fits," my dear, I think.

03:28:41.060 --> 03:28:52.060
He said to the queen, "Never!" said the queen furiously, throwing an ink stand at the lizard as she spoke.

03:28:52.060 --> 03:29:02.060
The unfortunate little bill had left off writing on his slate with one finger, as he found it made no mark.

03:29:02.060 --> 03:29:11.060
But he now hastily began again, using the ink that was trickling down his face, as long as it lasted.

03:29:11.060 --> 03:29:20.060
"Then the words don't fit, you," said the king, looking round the court with a smile. There was a dead silence.

03:29:20.060 --> 03:29:27.060
"It's a pun!" the king added in an offended tone, and everybody laughed.

03:29:27.060 --> 03:29:34.060
"Let the jury consider their verdict," the king said, for about the twentieth time that day.

03:29:34.060 --> 03:29:38.060
"No, no!" said the queen.

03:29:38.060 --> 03:29:41.060
"sentence first," verdict afterwards.

03:29:41.060 --> 03:29:45.060
"Stop it nonsense!" said Alice loudly.

03:29:45.060 --> 03:29:48.060
"The idea of having the sentence first."

03:29:48.060 --> 03:29:52.060
"Hold your tongue," said the queen, turning purple.

03:29:52.060 --> 03:29:55.060
"I won't," said Alice.

03:29:55.060 --> 03:30:01.060
"Off with her head!" the queen shouted at the top of her voice.

03:30:01.060 --> 03:30:06.060
"Nobody moved. Who cares for you?" said Alice.

03:30:06.060 --> 03:30:10.060
She had grown to her full size by this time.

03:30:10.060 --> 03:30:14.060
"You're nothing but a pack of cards!"

03:30:14.060 --> 03:30:20.060
At this the whole pack rose up into the air, and came flying down upon her.

03:30:20.060 --> 03:30:28.060
She gave a little scream, half of fright and half of anger, and tried to beat them off,

03:30:28.060 --> 03:30:35.060
and found herself lying on the bank, with her head in the lap of her sister,

03:30:35.060 --> 03:30:42.060
who was gently brushing away some dead leaves that had fluttered down from the trees upon her face.

03:30:42.060 --> 03:30:46.060
"Wake up, Alice dear," said her sister.

03:30:46.060 --> 03:30:54.060
"Why, what a long sleep you've had. Oh, I've had such a curious dream!"

03:30:54.060 --> 03:31:01.060
said Alice, and she told her sister, as well as she could remember them.

03:31:01.060 --> 03:31:09.060
All these strange adventures of hers that you have just been reading about, and when she had finished,

03:31:09.060 --> 03:31:17.060
her sister kissed her, and said, "It was a curious dream, dear, certainly,

03:31:17.060 --> 03:31:22.060
but now run into your tea, it's getting late."

03:31:22.060 --> 03:31:29.060
So Alice got up and ran off, thinking while she ran, as well she might.

03:31:29.060 --> 03:31:38.060
"What a wonderful dream it had been, but her sister sat still, chest as she left her.

03:31:38.060 --> 03:31:49.060
Leaning her head on her hand, watching the setting sun, and thinking of little Alice and all her wonderful adventures,

03:31:49.060 --> 03:31:56.060
till she too began dreaming after a fashion, and this was her dream.

03:31:56.060 --> 03:32:05.060
First she dreamed of little Alice herself, and once again the tiny hands were clasped upon her knee,

03:32:05.060 --> 03:32:10.060
and the bright eager eyes were looking up into hers.

03:32:10.060 --> 03:32:25.060
She could hear the very tones of her voice, and see that queer little toss of her head to keep back the wandering hair that would always get into her eyes.

03:32:25.060 --> 03:32:38.060
And still, as she listened, or seemed to listen, the whole place around her became alive with the strange creatures of her little sister's dream.

03:32:38.060 --> 03:32:48.060
The long grass rustled at her feet as the white rabbit hurried by, the frightened mouse splashed his way through the neighboring pool.

03:32:48.060 --> 03:33:04.060
She could hear the rattle of the teacups as the march hair and his friends shared their never-ending meal, and the shrill voice of the queen ordering off her unfortunate guests to execution.

03:33:04.060 --> 03:33:13.060
Once more the pig baby was sneezing on the duchess's knee, while plates and dishes crashed around it.

03:33:13.060 --> 03:33:31.060
Once more the shriek of the Griffin, the squeaking of the lizard's slate pencil, and the choking of the suppressed guinea pigs, filled the air, mixed up with the distant sobs of the miserable mock turtle.

03:33:31.060 --> 03:33:47.060
So she sat on with closed eyes, and half believed herself in Wonderland, though she knew she had but to open them again, and all would change to dull reality.

03:33:47.060 --> 03:34:03.060
The grass would be only rustling in the wind, and the pool rippling to the waving of the reeds.

03:34:03.060 --> 03:34:28.060
Crow cries to the voice of the shepherd boy, and the sneeze of the baby, the shriek of the Griffin, and all the other queer noises would change, she knew, to the confused clamor of the busy farm yard, while the lowing of the cattle in the distance would take the place of the mock turtle's heavy sobs.

03:34:28.060 --> 03:34:57.060
Lastly, she pictured to herself how this same little sister of hers would, in the after time, be herself a grown woman, and how she would keep, through all her riper years, the simple and loving heart of her childhood, and how she would gather about her other little children, and make their eyes bright and eager, with many a strange tale.

03:34:57.060 --> 03:35:16.060
Perhaps, even with the dream of Wonderland a long ago, and how she would feel with all their simple sorrows, and find a pleasure in all their simple joys, remembering her own child life, and the happy summer days.

03:35:16.060 --> 03:35:28.060
End of Chapter 12 End of Alice's Adventures in Wonderland by Lewis Carroll
